  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When glands swell and nerves fail, think sarcoid, steroids prevail!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Sarcoidosis. This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the classic triad of bilateral parotid swelling, dry mouth (xerostomia), and bilateral facial nerve palsies, which are characteristic manifestations of sarcoidosis, particularly Heerfordt's syndrome, and its responsiveness to steroids.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSarcoidosis is a multisystem granulomatous disease of unknown etiology, characterized by non-caseating granulomas. When it affects the parotid glands, it often presents bilaterally (in up to 70% of cases) and can be associated with xerostomia due to glandular infiltration. Cranial nerve involvement, especially the facial nerve (CN VII), is a recognized complication, occurring in 5-10% of sarcoidosis patients and can be bilateral. This specific constellation of uveitis, parotid enlargement, fever, and facial nerve palsy is known as Heerfordt's syndrome (uveoparotid fever). The granulomatous inflammation responds well to corticosteroids, leading to improvement in symptoms like facial nerve palsy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pleomorphic adenoma is the most common benign salivary gland tumor, but it is almost always unilateral and does not cause bilateral facial nerve palsies or systemic symptoms like dry mouth.\nOption C (Incorrect): Warthin's tumour is another benign salivary gland tumor, typically unilateral, and does not cause facial nerve palsy or systemic symptoms. It is more common in smokers.\nOption D (Incorrect): Sialolithiasis (salivary gland stones) causes unilateral, often painful, intermittent swelling, usually related to eating, and does not cause facial nerve palsy or bilateral involvement with dry mouth.\nOption E (Incorrect): Adenoid cystic carcinoma is a malignant salivary gland tumor known for perineural invasion and can cause facial nerve palsy, but it is typically unilateral, aggressive, and less likely to show such a dramatic improvement with steroids.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sarcoidosis (Heerfordt's) | Pleomorphic Adenoma | Warthin's Tumor | Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma |\n| :---------------------- | :------------------------ | :------------------ | :-------------- | :----------------------- |\n| Laterality | Often Bilateral | Unilateral | Unilateral | Unilateral |\n| Facial Nerve Palsy | Common (bilateral) | Rare | Rare | Possible (unilateral) |\n| Steroid Response | Good | None | None | None |\n| Systemic Symptoms | Yes (dry mouth, uveitis) | No | No | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilateral parotid swelling + facial palsy + dry mouth = Sarcoid until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT or MRI), sarcoidosis in the parotid glands would typically show diffuse, often bilateral, glandular enlargement with multiple small, non-enhancing or mildly enhancing nodules, reflecting granulomatous infiltration. Lymphadenopathy may also be present.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thoracic Society (ATS) Clinical Practice Guidelines 2020: Diagnosis and Management of Sarcoidosis. These guidelines recommend corticosteroids as the first-line treatment for symptomatic sarcoidosis, including neurological involvement like facial nerve palsy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pleomorphic adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sarcoid | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Warthins tumour | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Sialolithiasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Adenoid cystic carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Sarcoid occurs bilaterally in 70% of cases and facial nerve involvement is\nrecognised. Treatment is ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
