  "answer": "D) Branchial cysts are usually located laterally and derived from the second\nbranchial cleft. Unless infection has occurred they will usually have an\nanechoic appearance on ultrasound.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lateral neck, fluid-filled, anechoic? Think branchial, not brachial!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Branchial cyst. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the classic presentation of a smooth, fluid-filled, anechoic mass located in the lateral aspect of the anterior triangle of the neck, near the angle of the mandible, in a 3-year-old boy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBranchial cysts are congenital anomalies arising from incomplete obliteration of the branchial clefts during embryological development, most commonly the second branchial cleft. They typically present as a painless, soft, fluctuant mass in the lateral neck, anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle, often near the angle of the mandible. On ultrasound, an uncomplicated branchial cyst appears as a well-defined, anechoic (fluid-filled) lesion with posterior acoustic enhancement, consistent with the description provided in the clinical vignette.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cystic hygroma) (Incorrect): Cystic hygromas (lymphatic malformations) are typically multiloculated, compressible, and often found in the posterior triangle of the neck, though they can extend laterally. They are usually not a single, smooth, anechoic cyst.\nOption B (Dermoid cyst) (Incorrect): Dermoid cysts are typically midline or paramedian, often in the submental or suprahyoid region. While they can be lateral, they usually contain sebaceous material and hair, appearing more heterogeneous on ultrasound rather than purely anechoic.\nOption C (Thyroglossal cyst) (Incorrect): Thyroglossal duct cysts are characteristically midline neck masses, often infrahyoid, and classically move superiorly with tongue protrusion. Their location is inconsistent with the lateral mass described.\nOption E (Lymphoma) (Incorrect): Lymphoma presents as a solid, often firm, mass composed of lymph nodes, not a fluid-filled, anechoic cyst. Ultrasound would show hypoechoic solid nodes, often with abnormal architecture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Branchial Cyst | Thyroglossal Duct Cyst | Cystic Hygroma (Lymphatic Malformation) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Lateral neck, anterior to SCM, near angle of mandible | Midline neck, moves with tongue protrusion | Posterior triangle, often multiloculated, diffuse |\n| **Embryology** | Incomplete obliteration of branchial clefts (2nd most common) | Remnant of thyroglossal duct | Aberrant lymphatic development |\n| **Ultrasound** | Anechoic, well-defined, fluid-filled | Anechoic/hypoechoic, often with internal debris | Multiloculated, anechoic/hypoechoic, septations |\n| **Age of Presentation** | Childhood/adolescence | Infancy/childhood | Infancy/early childhood |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lateral neck mass + anechoic = Branchial cyst until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a branchial cyst typically appears as a unilocular, anechoic, well-circumscribed lesion with posterior acoustic enhancement. In the operating room, it presents as a smooth-walled, encapsulated cyst containing clear, mucoid fluid, often with a tract extending towards the pharynx.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation and Management of Congenital Neck Masses in Children (2018) recommends ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for suspected congenital neck masses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cystic hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Dermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroglossal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Branchial cyst | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Branchial cysts are usually located laterally and derived from the second\nbranchial cleft. Unless in** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
