  "question": "An enthusiastic medical student approaches you with a list of questions about blood transfusion reactions. Which of her following points is incorrect?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Graft versus host disease involves neutrophil proliferation",
    "B": "Thrombocytopaenia may occur in women with a prior pregnancy",
    "C": "IgA antibodies may cause blood pressure compromise during transfusion",
    "D": "Hypocalcaemia can occur",
    "E": "Iron overload can be avoided by chelation therapy"
  },
  "answer": "A) Mnemonic for transfusion reactions:\nGot a bad unit\nG raft vs. Host disease\nO verload\nT hrombocytopaenia\nA lloimmunization\nB lood pressure unstable\nA cute haemolytic reaction\nD elayed haemolytic reaction\nU rticaria\nN eutrophilia\nI nfection\nT ransfusion associated lung injury\nGVHD results from lymphocytic proliferation. The patient's own lymphocytes are similar to the donor's lymphocytes, therefore don't perceive them as being foreign. The donor lymphocytes, however, sees the recipient lymphocytes as being foreign. Therefore they proliferate causing severe complications.\nThrombocytopaenia occurs a few days after transfusion and may resolve spontaneously.\nPatients with IGA antibodies need IgA deficient blood transfusions",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 GVHD: Donor T-cells attack, not neutrophils on patrol!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the incorrect statement regarding blood transfusion reactions. The correct answer, A, highlights a common misconception about the cellular mechanism of Graft versus Host Disease (GVHD), which is a critical transfusion complication.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGraft versus Host Disease (GVHD) is a severe, often fatal, transfusion reaction primarily mediated by donor T-lymphocytes attacking recipient tissues. The donor lymphocytes, recognizing the recipient as foreign, proliferate and mount an immune response. The statement in option A incorrectly attributes this process to neutrophil proliferation, whereas neutrophils are primarily involved in innate immunity and bacterial clearance, not the adaptive immune response characteristic of GVHD.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect as the answer to the question): This statement is correct. Thrombocytopaenia can occur post-transfusion, particularly in multiparous women due to alloimmunization against human platelet antigens (HPA) from prior pregnancies.\nOption C (Incorrect as the answer to the question): This statement is correct. Patients with IgA deficiency who have developed anti-IgA antibodies can experience severe anaphylactic reactions, including significant blood pressure compromise, upon transfusion with IgA-containing blood products.\nOption D (Incorrect as the answer to the question): This statement is correct. Hypocalcaemia can occur during massive transfusions due to the citrate anticoagulant in stored blood binding to and chelating ionized calcium in the recipient's bloodstream.\nOption E (Incorrect as the answer to the question): This statement is correct. Chronic blood transfusions lead to iron overload, which can cause organ damage. Chelation therapy is the standard treatment to remove excess iron and prevent or mitigate this complication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Transfusion Reaction | Key Mechanism | Clinical Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Graft vs. Host Disease (GVHD) | Donor T-lymphocytes attack recipient tissues | Rash, diarrhea, liver dysfunction, pancytopenia |\n| Anaphylactic Reaction | Recipient anti-IgA antibodies react with donor IgA | Hypotension, bronchospasm, urticaria |\n| Hypocalcemia | Citrate in transfused blood chelates calcium | Paresthesias, muscle cramps, cardiac arrhythmias |\n| Iron Overload | Accumulation of iron from chronic transfusions | Organ damage (heart, liver, endocrine glands) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: GVHD is T-cell mediated, not neutrophil-mediated. Remember the 'G' for Graft and 'T' for T-cells.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThere are no images provided in the question. Imaging for GVHD (e.g., CT abdomen for colitis, liver ultrasound for cholestasis) would show non-specific findings related to organ damage rather than the underlying cellular proliferation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAABB (American Association of Blood Banks) Clinical Practice Guideline: Red Blood Cell Transfusion (2016) provides recommendations for safe transfusion practices and management of reactions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Graft versus host disease involves neutrophil proliferation | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Thrombocytopaenia may occur in women with a prior pregnancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | IgA antibodies may cause blood pressure compromise during transfusion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypocalcaemia can occur | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Iron overload can be avoided by chelation therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Mnemonic for transfusion reactions:\nGot a bad unit\nG raft vs. Host disease\nO verload\nT hrombocytopae** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
