  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Dominant Lynch is a cancer risk, not recessive.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify a characteristic that is *not* typical of Lynch syndrome. Lynch syndrome is a well-established autosomal dominant inherited cancer syndrome, making the statement about autosomal recessive inheritance incorrect and thus the correct answer to the question.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLynch syndrome, also known as Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer (HNPCC), is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by germline mutations in DNA mismatch repair (MMR) genes (MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, PMS2) or EPCAM. This dominant inheritance pattern means only one copy of the mutated gene is needed to confer a significantly increased lifetime risk of colorectal cancer (CRC) and various extracolonic cancers. The underlying genetic defect leads to microsatellite instability (MSI), a hallmark of Lynch syndrome, which drives tumorigenesis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Affected patients are more likely to develop right colon mucinous tumours than the general population. This is a typical feature of Lynch syndrome-associated colorectal cancers, which are often right-sided, poorly differentiated, and mucinous.\nOption C (Incorrect): Affected individuals have an an 80% lifetime risk of colon cancer. While the exact percentage varies by specific gene mutation and study, a high lifetime risk (often cited between 50-80%) of CRC is a defining characteristic of Lynch syndrome.\nOption D (Incorrect): Endometrial cancer is seen in 80% of women. Endometrial cancer is the most common extracolonic malignancy in women with Lynch syndrome, with lifetime risks frequently ranging from 40-60% or higher depending on the specific gene mutation, making this statement generally typical.\nOption E (Incorrect): Gastric cancers are more common. Patients with Lynch syndrome have an increased risk of gastric cancer compared to the general population, although it is less common than CRC or endometrial cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Lynch Syndrome (HNPCC) | Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Inheritance | Autosomal Dominant | Autosomal Dominant |\n| Gene Mutation | MMR genes (MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, PMS2), EPCAM | APC gene |\n| Polyps | Few, often flat, right-sided, rapid progression | Hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps |\n| CRC Risk | High (50-80% lifetime) | Nearly 100% lifetime if untreated |\n| Extracolonic Cancers | Endometrial, ovarian, gastric, urinary tract, small bowel, brain, sebaceous | Duodenal, thyroid, desmoid tumors, osteomas, CNS (Gardner's/Turcot's) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lynch syndrome is autosomal dominant, not recessive, with high CRC and extracolonic cancer risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, Lynch syndrome patients may present with fewer polyps than FAP, but these polyps are more likely to be adenocarcinomas or advanced adenomas, often located in the right colon. Intraoperatively, surgeons might encounter synchronous or metachronous colorectal cancers, necessitating careful examination of the entire colon.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colorectal Cancer Screening (Version 1.2024) recommends specific screening and surveillance protocols for individuals with Lynch syndrome, including colonoscopy every 1-2 years starting at age 20-25.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Affected patients are more likely to develop right colon mucinous tumours t | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Affected individuals have an 80% lifetime risk of colon cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Endometrial cancer is seen in 80% of women | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Gastric cancers are more common | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Lynch syndrome is inherited in an autosomal dominant fashion. It is characterised by microsatellite ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
