  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't miss the other 5% – scope the whole colon!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 5%, indicating that approximately 5% of patients with colorectal cancer will have synchronous lesions. This highlights the critical need for a complete colonic evaluation in all patients diagnosed with colorectal cancer to identify additional lesions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSynchronous colorectal lesions are defined as additional primary colorectal cancers or advanced adenomas found at the time of or within six months of the initial diagnosis of colorectal cancer. Their presence necessitates a thorough preoperative workup, typically a full colonoscopy, to ensure all lesions are identified and addressed, either during the initial surgery or in a staged manner. Missing a synchronous lesion can lead to delayed diagnosis, progression, and potentially worse oncologic outcomes for the patient. The 5% figure is a well-established epidemiological fact in colorectal cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): <1% is significantly lower than the reported incidence of synchronous lesions, which is consistently cited around 3-5%.\nOption B (Incorrect): 60% is an extremely high and inaccurate percentage for synchronous lesions; this would imply a much more aggressive and multifocal disease pattern than typically observed.\nOption C (Incorrect): 50% is far too high for synchronous lesions; this percentage is more akin to the prevalence of adenomas in the general population, not synchronous cancers.\nOption D (Incorrect): 20% is substantially higher than the actual incidence of synchronous lesions, which typically ranges from 3-8% in most studies.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Synchronous Lesions | Metachronous Lesions |\n|---|---|---|\n| Definition | Additional primary colorectal cancers or advanced adenomas found at the time of or within 6 months of initial diagnosis. | New primary colorectal cancers or advanced adenomas found more than 6 months after the initial diagnosis and treatment. |\n| Incidence | ~3-8% of CRC patients | ~0.5-1% per patient-year after initial CRC |\n| Detection | Preoperative full colonoscopy, CT colonography, or barium enema. | Postoperative surveillance colonoscopy (e.g., 1 year, then 3 years, then 5 years). |\n| Management | Often addressed during initial surgery or staged procedure. | Managed as a new primary cancer. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always complete colonic evaluation for synchronous lesions in CRC.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, a synchronous lesion would appear as a separate, distinct mass or polyp, often with features suggestive of malignancy (e.g., ulceration, friability, irregular shape) or advanced adenoma (e.g., large size, villous component). CT colonography might show a separate intraluminal mass with associated wall thickening.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend a complete colon evaluation (e.g., colonoscopy) prior to surgery for colon cancer to identify synchronous lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | <1% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 60% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 20% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 5% | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Synchronous colonic tumours are seen in 5% cases and all patients having a flexible sigmoidoscopy sh** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
