  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 NPI: Size, Nodes, Grade – don't miss the big picture!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe Nottingham Prognostic Index (NPI) score of 6.4, combined with a tumor size of 2cm, necessitates a high contribution from both lymph node status and tumor grade. This high score cannot be achieved without the definite presence of lymph node metastasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Nottingham Prognostic Index (NPI) is calculated as (0.2 x tumor size in cm) + lymph node stage + tumor grade. Given a tumor size of 2cm, the size component contributes 0.2 * 2 = 0.4 to the NPI. With an NPI of 6.4, the remaining 6.0 must be accounted for by the sum of the lymph node stage and tumor grade. The maximum score for lymph node stage is 3 (>3 positive nodes) and for tumor grade is 3 (Grade 3). Therefore, to reach a sum of 6.0, both components must be at their maximum (3+3=6), unequivocally indicating the presence of lymph node metastasis (specifically >3 positive nodes) and a high-grade tumor.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A score of 6.4 with a 2cm tumor is too high for a grade 1 tumor. If grade 1 (score 1), the lymph node stage would need to be 5, which is impossible.\nOption B (Incorrect): The Nottingham Prognostic Index does not incorporate vascular invasion as one of its components.\nOption D (Incorrect): Oestrogen receptor status is not a component of the Nottingham Prognostic Index calculation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Option C is a correct inference based on the NPI calculation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| NPI Component | Score | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tumor Size (cm) | 0.2 x size | Measured in centimeters |\n| Lymph Node Stage | 1 | 0 positive nodes |\n| | 2 | 1-3 positive nodes |\n| | 3 | >3 positive nodes |\n| Tumor Grade | 1 | Grade 1 (well differentiated) |\n| | 2 | Grade 2 (moderately differentiated) |\n| | 3 | Grade 3 (poorly differentiated) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: High NPI with small tumor implies significant nodal involvement and high grade.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative imaging (mammography, ultrasound, MRI) would assess tumor size and regional lymph node status, guiding sentinel lymph node biopsy or axillary dissection. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would visually inspect and palpate axillary nodes, with pathology confirming their status.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023). These guidelines incorporate prognostic factors like NPI components (tumor size, grade, nodal status) into treatment recommendations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The tumour is likely to be grade 1 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Vascular invasion is present | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lymph node metastasis are definitely present | ✅ Correct |\n| D | The tumour is oestrogen receptor positive | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) A score of this value is unlikely to be reached with a grade 1 tumour and a size of 2cm. Therefore l** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
