  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Meckel's: The vitelline artery's last stand.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Vitelline artery. This question tests your knowledge of the embryological origins and vascular supply of Meckel's diverticulum, a critical anatomical detail for surgical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeckel's diverticulum is a remnant of the omphalomesenteric (vitelline) duct, which connects the embryonic midgut to the yolk sac. Consequently, its blood supply is derived from the vitelline arterial system. While the primary vitelline artery regresses, its remnants often persist as a distinct vessel supplying the diverticulum, typically branching off the superior mesenteric artery or one of its ileal arcade branches, maintaining its embryological lineage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The right colic artery is a branch of the superior mesenteric artery that supplies the ascending colon, not the small bowel diverticulum.\nOption C (Incorrect): The appendicular artery is a terminal branch of the ileocolic artery, specifically supplying the vermiform appendix.\nOption D (Incorrect): The internal iliac artery supplies pelvic organs, the perineum, and the gluteal region, not the small intestine.\nOption E (Incorrect): The external iliac artery is the main arterial supply to the lower limb, not intra-abdominal structures like Meckel's diverticulum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Structure | Embryological Origin | Primary Blood Supply |\n|---|---|---|\n| Meckel's Diverticulum | Omphalomesenteric (Vitelline) Duct | Vitelline artery (often from ileal arcades) |\n| Appendix | Midgut (cecal bud) | Appendicular artery (from ileocolic artery) |\n| Ileum | Midgut | Ileal arteries (from superior mesenteric artery) |\n| Ascending Colon | Midgut | Right colic artery (from superior mesenteric artery) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Meckel's diverticulum = Vitelline artery remnant.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, an inflamed Meckel's diverticulum appears as a red, edematous outpouching on the antimesenteric border of the ileum, typically 60-90 cm proximal to the ileocecal valve. Its blood supply is often visible as a distinct vessel originating from the mesenteric side, separate from the main ileal arcades, confirming its unique embryological origin.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) guidelines on Meckel's Diverticulum (2018): Recommends resection of symptomatic Meckel's diverticulum and consideration of incidental resection in certain circumstances, emphasizing the importance of identifying its vascular supply.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right colic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Vitelline artery | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Appendicular artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Internal iliac artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | External iliac artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The vitelline arteries supply a Meckels these are usually derived from the ileal arcades** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
