  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get Meckel's mixed up; native ileum, ectopic bleeds!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Ileal mucosa because Meckel's diverticulum is a remnant of the omphalomesenteric duct, typically located in the ileum. While ectopic gastric mucosa is common and causes symptoms, the native lining of an asymptomatic Meckel's is ileal.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeckel's diverticulum represents the most common congenital anomaly of the gastrointestinal tract, resulting from the incomplete obliteration of the vitelline (omphalomesenteric) duct. As it arises from the antimesenteric border of the ileum, its native lining is typically ileal mucosa. However, due to its embryological origin, it can contain heterotopic tissue, most commonly gastric mucosa (leading to peptic ulceration and bleeding) or pancreatic tissue.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gastric mucosa) (Incorrect): While gastric mucosa is the most common type of heterotopic tissue found in Meckel's diverticulum and is responsible for most symptomatic presentations (especially bleeding), the question specifies a non-inflamed, asymptomatic diverticulum found incidentally. In such cases, the native ileal lining is most likely.\nOption B (Non stratified squamous epithelium) (Incorrect): This type of epithelium is not typically found lining the small intestine or Meckel's diverticulum.\nOption D (Stratified squamous epithelium) (Incorrect): Stratified squamous epithelium is found in areas like the esophagus and anus, providing protection against abrasion, but not in the small bowel or Meckel's diverticulum.\nOption E (Jejunal mucosa) (Incorrect): Meckel's diverticulum is typically located in the distal ileum, not the jejunum. Therefore, ileal mucosa is the expected native lining.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Meckel's Diverticulum |\n|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Remnant of omphalomesenteric duct |\n| **Location** | Distal ileum (within 100cm of IC valve) |\n| **Lining** | Ileal mucosa (native), often ectopic gastric/pancreatic |\n| **Complications** | Bleeding, obstruction, diverticulitis, intussusception |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Meckel's: Ileal lining unless symptomatic, then think ectopic gastric.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a Meckel's diverticulum appears as a true diverticulum (containing all layers of the bowel wall) arising from the antimesenteric border of the ileum, typically 2 feet from the ileocecal valve. It can vary in length and may have a mesodiverticular band connecting it to the mesentery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) Guidelines for the Management of Meckel's Diverticulum (2018). Recommends resection for symptomatic diverticula and consideration for incidental resection based on risk factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastric mucosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Non stratified squamous epithelium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ileal mucosa | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Stratified squamous epithelium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Jejunal mucosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Most asymptomatic Meckels diverticulum will be lined by ileal mucosa. Those which present with bleed** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
