  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Three weeks: when callus makes its radiographic debut.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 3 weeks. At this point, the initial soft callus has undergone sufficient mineralization to become visible on plain radiographs, marking a key milestone in the fracture healing process.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFracture healing progresses through several overlapping stages: inflammation, soft callus formation, hard callus formation, and remodeling. The soft callus, composed of fibroblasts and chondroblasts synthesizing fibrocartilage, begins to form around 1-2 weeks. Over the subsequent weeks, this fibrocartilaginous callus undergoes endochondral ossification, leading to the deposition of woven bone. It is this mineralization of the soft callus into hard callus that makes it radiographically detectable, typically becoming evident around 3 weeks post-injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 1 day is too early. At this stage, the fracture site is characterized by hematoma formation and an inflammatory response, with no visible callus.\nOption B (Incorrect): 7 days (1 week) is when early granulation tissue and soft callus begin to form, but it is not yet sufficiently mineralized to be visible on plain radiographs.\nOption C (Incorrect): 8 weeks is well past the initial visibility of callus. By this time, the hard callus is typically well-formed and may even be undergoing early remodeling.\nOption D (Incorrect): 6 weeks is also past the initial visibility. While callus is robustly present and often remodeling by 6 weeks, 3 weeks is when it is most likely to first become radiologically apparent.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stage of Healing | Approximate Timeframe | Radiological Feature |\n| :--------------- | :-------------------- | :------------------- |\n| Inflammation     | Day 0-7               | Fracture line visible, no callus |\n| Soft Callus      | Week 1-3              | Fracture line visible, no or faint callus |\n| Hard Callus      | Week 3-12             | Faint to obvious callus bridging fracture |\n| Remodeling       | Months to Years       | Callus consolidates, fracture line disappears |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Callus appears on X-ray around 3 weeks, solidifies by 6-12 weeks.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs, fracture callus appears as a fluffy, ill-defined radiopacity bridging the fracture gap. Its density increases over time as it matures and remodels.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAO Foundation Principles of Fracture Management (current edition). Recommends understanding biological healing for appropriate fixation and rehabilitation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1 day | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 7 days | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 8 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 6 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 3 weeks | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Fracture callus is composed of fibroblasts and chondroblasts and the synthesis of fibrocartilage. It** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
