  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For SCC, don't be fooled by 'unsafe' claims; radiotherapy is a powerful ally!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with a high-risk squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) due to its size (25mm) and depth (4mm). Option C states that radiotherapy would be unsafe for this lesion, which is incorrect. Radiotherapy is a safe and effective treatment modality for SCC, including high-risk lesions, and is a viable option for primary treatment or adjuvant therapy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadiotherapy is a cornerstone in the management of cutaneous SCC, offering a non-surgical alternative with comparable efficacy to surgery for many lesions. It is particularly valuable for large or deep tumors, lesions in cosmetically sensitive areas where extensive surgery could lead to significant disfigurement, or for patients who are poor surgical candidates. While certain anatomical sites (e.g., nose) may have increased risk of radionecrosis, this does not render radiotherapy generally 'unsafe' for SCC. The decision between surgery and radiotherapy is individualized, considering tumor characteristics, patient factors, and anatomical location, but radiotherapy remains a safe and effective treatment option.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): In this particular case margins of at least 6mm are required. This statement is TRUE. High-risk SCCs (size >20mm, depth >4mm) necessitate wider surgical margins, typically 6mm or more, to ensure complete excision and minimize local recurrence.\nOption B (Incorrect): Use of cryosurgery to treat this patients lesion would have been unsafe. This statement is TRUE. Cryosurgery is generally reserved for superficial, low-risk SCCs. For a deep lesion like this (4mm), cryosurgery cannot reliably achieve adequate depth of destruction, making it an unsafe and ineffective treatment choice.\nOption D (Incorrect): This patients local recurrence rate may approach 15%. This statement is TRUE. The lesion's size (25mm) is a significant risk factor, and SCCs greater than 20mm can have local recurrence rates approaching 15%.\nOption E (Incorrect): The disease usually spreads via lymphatics. This statement is TRUE. Cutaneous SCC, especially high-risk variants, primarily spreads via the lymphatic system to regional lymph nodes before distant metastasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Low-Risk cSCC | High-Risk cSCC |\n| :------ | :------------ | :------------- |\n| Size    | <2 cm         | >2 cm          |\n| Depth   | <2 mm         | >2 mm or >4mm (perineural invasion) |\n| Margins | 4-6 mm        | 6-10 mm or Mohs |\n| Treatment | Excision, ED&C, Cryo, RT | Excision, Mohs, RT, Adjuvant RT |\n| Metastasis Risk | Low (<5%) | High (>10-30%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Don't underestimate SCC; high-risk features demand aggressive management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a high-risk SCC like this would necessitate careful assessment of tumor depth and extent, potentially requiring frozen section analysis to ensure clear margins. Imaging like ultrasound or MRI might be used preoperatively to assess deep invasion or regional lymph node involvement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Basal Cell and Squamous Cell Skin Cancers (2023) recommend considering radiotherapy for high-risk SCC, either as primary treatment or adjuvant therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In this particular case margins of at least 6mm are required | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Use of cryosurgery to treat this patients lesion would have been unsafe | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Use of radiotherapy to treat this lesion would have been unsafe | ✅ Correct |\n| D | This patients local recurrence rate may approach 15% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | The disease usually spreads via lymphatics | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Poor prognostic factors in SCC: Size >20mm (local recurrence rate of up to 15%) Depth greater than 4** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
