  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CA125: The ovarian cancer sentinel.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies CA125 as the most likely elevated tumor marker in ovarian cancer. CA125 is a glycoprotein tumor antigen widely recognized for its association with epithelial ovarian cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCA125 (Cancer Antigen 125) is a high molecular weight glycoprotein that is expressed on the surface of ovarian cancer cells and is shed into the bloodstream. While not perfectly specific, its elevation is a key indicator for screening high-risk individuals, monitoring treatment response, and detecting recurrence in patients with ovarian cancer. Its utility stems from its role as a monoclonal antibody against a carbohydrate or glycoprotein tumor antigen, making it a valuable tool in the management of this malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (IgG 4) (Incorrect): IgG4 is an immunoglobulin subclass and is not a tumor marker for ovarian cancer; it is associated with IgG4-related disease, a fibroinflammatory condition.\nOption B (CEA) (Incorrect): Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) is primarily associated with colorectal cancer, although it can be elevated in other adenocarcinomas, it is not the primary marker for ovarian cancer.\nOption D (CA19-9) (Incorrect): CA19-9 is a tumor marker predominantly associated with pancreatic cancer, and sometimes with other gastrointestinal malignancies, but not typically ovarian cancer.\nOption E (AFP) (Incorrect): Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) is a tumor marker primarily associated with hepatocellular carcinoma and germ cell tumors (like teratomas), not epithelial ovarian cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Marker | Associated Cancer |\n|---|---|\n| CA 125 | Ovarian cancer |\n| CA 19-9 | Pancreatic cancer |\n| CA 15-3 | Breast cancer |\n| PSA | Prostatic carcinoma |\n| AFP | Hepatocellular carcinoma, Teratoma |\n| CEA | Colorectal cancer |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know the primary tumor marker for common cancers.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound, CT, MRI), ovarian cancer often presents as a complex adnexal mass, frequently with solid and cystic components, septations, and ascites. Intraoperatively, one might observe a large, often irregular adnexal mass, peritoneal carcinomatosis, and ascites.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Ovarian Cancer (2023): Recommends CA125 as part of the initial workup for suspected ovarian masses and for monitoring disease recurrence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | IgG 4 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CEA | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CA125 | ✅ Correct |\n| D | CA19-9 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | AFP | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Tumour markers may be divided into: monoclonal antibodies against carbohydrate or glycoprotein tumou** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
