  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Crohn's in the ileum? Think stones in the bile.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Bile duct stones. This patient's long-standing Crohn's disease, particularly affecting the terminal ileum, significantly increases his risk for gallstone formation, which can lead to intermittent obstructive jaundice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCrohn's disease often involves the terminal ileum, the primary site for reabsorption of bile salts. Chronic inflammation or surgical resection of this segment impairs bile salt reabsorption, leading to a reduced bile salt pool. This reduction causes the bile to become supersaturated with cholesterol, promoting the formation of cholesterol gallstones. When these stones migrate from the gallbladder into the common bile duct (choledocholithiasis), they cause obstructive jaundice, which can be intermittent if the stone passes or shifts position.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Crigler Najjar syndrome is a rare genetic disorder causing severe unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia due to a deficiency in UDP-glucuronosyltransferase. It does not cause obstructive jaundice.\nOption B (Incorrect): While parasitic infections can cause obstructive jaundice, they are less likely to present with spontaneously resolving, intermittent obstruction directly linked to the specific pathophysiology of Crohn's disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gilbert's syndrome is a common, benign genetic condition causing mild, unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia, often exacerbated by stress or fasting. It does not cause obstructive jaundice.\nOption E (Incorrect): Multicystic liver disease (e.g., polycystic liver disease) can cause symptoms due to mass effect or infection, but typically not intermittent, spontaneously resolving obstructive jaundice directly related to Crohn's.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Jaundice Type | Cause | Bilirubin Type | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pre-hepatic | Hemolysis, Gilbert's, Crigler-Najjar | Unconjugated | No bilirubin in urine |\n| Hepatic | Hepatitis, Cirrhosis, Drugs | Mixed (mostly conjugated) | Elevated LFTs, variable urine bilirubin |\n| Post-hepatic | Gallstones, Pancreatic mass, Cholangitis | Conjugated | Dark urine, pale stools, pruritus |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Crohn's + terminal ileum disease = increased risk of cholesterol gallstones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound would typically show dilated bile ducts and potentially stones within the common bile duct or gallbladder. MRCP (Magnetic Resonance Cholangiopancreatography) would provide detailed imaging of the biliary tree, confirming the presence and location of stones causing obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Gallstone Disease (2016) discusses risk factors for gallstone formation, including conditions like Crohn's disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Crigler Najjar syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Parasitic infection of the liver | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bile duct stones | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Gilberts syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Multi cystic liver disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Bile salts are absorbed in the terminal ileum. When this process is impaired as in Crohns the patien** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
