  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 APS: The great pretender, clotting and bleeding with a tricky APTT.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS). This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's history of recurrent pulmonary emboli combined with post-procedural bleeding and a prolonged APTT in a young female.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAntiphospholipid syndrome is an autoimmune disorder characterized by arterial or venous thrombosis, pregnancy morbidity, and the presence of antiphospholipid antibodies (lupus anticoagulant, anticardiolipin antibodies, anti-β2-glycoprotein I antibodies). The lupus anticoagulant paradoxically prolongs the APTT in vitro by interfering with phospholipid-dependent coagulation tests, while in vivo, it promotes a prothrombotic state. Bleeding can occur due to associated thrombocytopenia, acquired factor deficiencies, or in the context of anticoagulation for thrombosis, making it a complex presentation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (DIC) (Incorrect): While DIC can cause prolonged APTT and bleeding, it typically presents with widespread microvascular thrombosis, severe bleeding, and significant derangements in other coagulation parameters (e.g., low platelets, low fibrinogen, prolonged PT), which are not described here. Recurrent PEs are not a typical isolated presentation.\nOption C (Haemophilia B) (Incorrect): Haemophilia B (Factor IX deficiency) is an X-linked recessive disorder primarily affecting males, causing bleeding, but not recurrent thrombotic events like pulmonary emboli.\nOption D (von Willebrand disease) (Incorrect): von Willebrand disease is a common bleeding disorder, often with normal or slightly prolonged APTT, but it does not cause recurrent pulmonary emboli.\nOption E (Factor V Leiden deficiency) (Incorrect): Factor V Leiden deficiency is a common inherited thrombophilia that predisposes to venous thrombosis (like PE) but does not cause bleeding or prolong the APTT.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Features | APTT | Thrombosis | Bleeding |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Antiphospholipid Syndrome | Recurrent thrombosis, pregnancy morbidity, autoimmune | Prolonged (Lupus Anticoagulant) | Yes | Yes (often due to thrombocytopenia/anticoagulation) |\n| DIC | Widespread microvascular thrombosis, severe bleeding, organ dysfunction | Prolonged | Yes | Yes |\n| Haemophilia B | X-linked, severe bleeding (joint/muscle) | Prolonged | No | Yes |\n| von Willebrand Disease | Mucocutaneous bleeding, easy bruising | Normal or slightly prolonged | No | Yes |\n| Factor V Leiden | Inherited thrombophilia | Normal | Yes | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Thrombosis + bleeding + prolonged APTT = think Antiphospholipid Syndrome.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging for pulmonary emboli (e.g., CT pulmonary angiography) would show filling defects in the pulmonary arteries. Intraoperatively, during a D+C, persistent bleeding despite appropriate uterine contraction might be observed, prompting investigation into an underlying coagulopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACR/EULAR 2023 Classification Criteria for Antiphospholipid Syndrome: These criteria guide the diagnosis of APS based on clinical and laboratory findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Antiphospholipid syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| B | DIC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Haemophilia B | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | von Willebrand disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Factor V Leiden deficiency | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A combination of thromboembolism and bleeding in a young woman should raise the possibility of antip** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
