  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, check the limb for a lump!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, indicating that sarcomas are most frequently found in the extremities. This is a fundamental epidemiological fact in surgical oncology, as a significant proportion of soft tissue sarcomas (STS) arise in the limbs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSoft tissue sarcomas are mesenchymal tumors, and the extremities, with their abundant connective tissue, provide a common anatomical substrate for their development. Approximately 40-50% of all soft tissue sarcomas are found in the limbs, making it the most prevalent site. These often present as a painless, enlarging mass, which can be a diagnostic challenge due to their non-specific initial symptoms. Common histological subtypes found in the extremities include liposarcoma, undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma (UPS), leiomyosarcoma, and synovial sarcoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While sarcomas can occur in the thorax (e.g., chest wall, mediastinum), they are less common than in the extremities.\nOption B (Incorrect): Retroperitoneal sarcomas are a significant and challenging subset, but their overall incidence is lower than that of extremity sarcomas, typically accounting for 15-20% of cases.\nOption C (Incorrect): Sarcomas can involve the axial skeleton (bone sarcomas) or paraspinal soft tissues, but this location is less frequent than the extremities for soft tissue sarcomas.\nOption E (Incorrect): Head and neck sarcomas are relatively rare, comprising only about 5-10% of all soft tissue sarcomas, and often present unique management challenges due to complex anatomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Location | Approximate % of STS | Common Clinical Presentation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Extremities | 40-50% | Painless, enlarging mass |\n| Retroperitoneum | 15-20% | Vague abdominal discomfort, palpable mass |\n| Trunk/Chest Wall | 10-15% | Palpable mass, sometimes pain |\n| Head & Neck | 5-10% | Mass, potential functional impairment |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Extremities are the most common site for soft tissue sarcomas.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, extremity sarcomas typically appear as heterogeneous masses with variable signal intensity, often demonstrating avid contrast enhancement. They may show areas of necrosis or hemorrhage. Intraoperatively, they can range from well-circumscribed to infiltrative, often appearing firm, fleshy, and sometimes lobulated, requiring careful assessment of margins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (e.g., 2024) recommend a multidisciplinary approach for diagnosis and treatment, emphasizing wide surgical excision with negative margins as the cornerstone of therapy, often combined with radiation and/or chemotherapy based on tumor characteristics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In the thorax | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | In the abdomen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Around the axial spine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | In the extremities | ✅ Correct |\n| E | In the head and neck | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 40% of sarcomas are found in the extremities** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
