  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Wilms: The pediatric renal mass, don't miss it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Wilms tumour. This clinical scenario, featuring a 4-year-old boy with haematuria and a right-sided renal mass, is the classic presentation of a Wilms tumour, also known as nephroblastoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWilms tumour is the most common primary malignant renal tumour in children, typically presenting between 1 and 5 years of age. Its presentation as an asymptomatic abdominal mass is most common, but haematuria, abdominal pain, and hypertension can also occur. The tumour originates from primitive metanephric blastema, explaining its prevalence in early childhood during kidney development. Rapid growth can lead to its detection as a palpable mass.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Glomerulonephritis causes haematuria but does not present as a renal mass. It involves inflammation of the kidney's filtering units.\nOption C (Incorrect): Horseshoe kidney is a congenital fusion anomaly of the kidneys, not a tumour, and typically does not present with a mass and haematuria in this manner. It's usually asymptomatic or associated with obstruction.\nOption D (Incorrect): Renal adenocarcinoma (renal cell carcinoma) is overwhelmingly a tumour of adulthood, typically occurring in patients over 50 years old, making it highly unlikely in a 4-year-old.\nOption E (Incorrect): Ureteric transitional cell carcinoma is also predominantly a tumour of adults, usually presenting with painless haematuria but rarely as a renal mass in a child.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Age Group | Presentation | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Wilms Tumour | Young Children (1-5 yrs) | Abdominal mass, haematuria, hypertension | Most common pediatric renal malignancy |\n| Renal Cell Carcinoma | Adults (>50 yrs) | Haematuria, flank pain, palpable mass | Adult renal malignancy |\n| Neuroblastoma | Infants/Young Children | Abdominal mass (often adrenal), systemic symptoms | Originates from neural crest cells |\n| Polycystic Kidney Disease | Variable (childhood/adult) | Cysts, renal failure, hypertension | Genetic, bilateral involvement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Renal mass in a young child = Wilms tumour until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a Wilms tumour typically appears as a large, heterogeneous renal mass, often with areas of necrosis or hemorrhage, distorting the renal architecture. Intraoperatively, it's a large, encapsulated, often friable mass arising from the kidney.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Wilms Tumor Study Group Guidelines (e.g., COG AREN0532, AREN03B2) recommend specific staging, surgical approaches, and adjuvant therapies based on risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wilms tumour | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Glomerulonephritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Horseshoe kidney | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Renal adenocarcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Ureteric transitional cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Wilms tumours (nephroblastoma) usually present in the first 4 years of life and may cause lung metas** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
