  "answer": "E) Lynch syndrome usually results in colonic cancer which is right sided and mucinous. The next most common site to be affected is the uterus. The stomach is at particular risk and this risk is up to 10 times greater in HNPCC (Lynch) patients than the general population. Duodenal adenomas (and rarely carcinoma) are usually seen in association with FAP. Whilst pancreatic carcinoma is associated with HNPCC it is far less likely to occur than gastric cancer. We are often asked how these patients become jaundiced, this occurs as a result of nodal spread along the hepatoduodenal ligament nodes to occlude the porta hepatis resulting in jaundice.",
