  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When small bowel diaphragms appear, NSAIDs are the culprit, clear and near!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, oral non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), because diaphragm disease of the small intestine is a well-recognized complication predominantly caused by chronic NSAID use, leading to characteristic strictures and subsequent small bowel obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiaphragm disease, also known as NSAID-induced enteropathy, is characterized by multiple, thin, circumferential strictures in the small intestine that resemble diaphragms. Chronic NSAID use inhibits cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, leading to reduced prostaglandin synthesis. Prostaglandins are crucial for maintaining mucosal integrity, blood flow, and mucus production in the gastrointestinal tract. Their depletion makes the small bowel mucosa vulnerable to injury, ulceration, and subsequent fibrosis and stricture formation, which can ultimately cause small bowel obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Alcohol abuse) (Incorrect): While chronic alcohol abuse can lead to various gastrointestinal issues, including gastritis and pancreatitis, it is not a direct cause of diaphragm disease.\nOption C (Abdominal radiotherapy) (Incorrect): Abdominal radiotherapy can cause radiation enteritis, leading to strictures and obstruction, but the morphology is typically diffuse fibrosis rather than the distinct \"diaphragm-like\" strictures seen in NSAID enteropathy.\nOption D (Oral steroids) (Incorrect): Oral steroids are generally anti-inflammatory and can be used to treat inflammatory bowel conditions. They are not known to cause diaphragm disease; in fact, they might be used in conjunction with NSAIDs, but they are not the precipitant of this specific pathology.\nOption E (Chronic laxative misuse) (Incorrect): Chronic laxative misuse can lead to conditions like melanosis coli or cathartic colon, characterized by colonic dysfunction and mucosal changes, but it does not cause diaphragm disease of the small intestine.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Common Cause | Pathological Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Diaphragm Disease | Chronic NSAID use | Multiple, thin, circumferential strictures |\n| Crohn's Disease | Autoimmune/Genetic | Transmural inflammation, skip lesions, strictures, fistulas |\n| Radiation Enteritis | Abdominal Radiotherapy | Fibrosis, inflammation, strictures, malabsorption |\n| Ischemic Stricture | Vascular insufficiency | Segmental necrosis, fibrosis, stricture |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NSAIDs are the primary cause of small bowel diaphragm disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT enterography or capsule endoscopy, diaphragm disease appears as multiple, short, concentric strictures with intervening normal bowel. Intraoperatively, these strictures are palpable as thin, ring-like constrictions within the small bowel lumen, often requiring careful palpation to identify all affected segments.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Small Bowel Obstruction (2016) recommends considering NSAID-induced enteropathy in patients with small bowel obstruction and a history of NSAID use, especially when other causes are excluded.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Alcohol abuse | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Oral non steroidal anti inflammatory drugs | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Abdominal radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Oral steroids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Chronic laxative misuse | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Diaphragm disease of the small intestine is caused by NSAIDS in most cases and treated by surgical r** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
