  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Medial winging? Long thoracic nerve's singing!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Long thoracic nerve. The patient's symptoms of a medially protruding scapula and inability to push forward are pathognomonic for a winged scapula caused by serratus anterior muscle paralysis, which results from injury to the long thoracic nerve during axillary node clearance.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe long thoracic nerve, originating from C5, C6, and C7 nerve roots, innervates the serratus anterior muscle. The serratus anterior is crucial for protracting the scapula (e.g., pushing forward) and holding it firmly against the chest wall. During axillary lymph node dissection, this nerve is vulnerable as it courses along the chest wall on the superficial aspect of the serratus anterior. Injury to the long thoracic nerve leads to paralysis of the serratus anterior, causing the medial border and inferior angle of the scapula to protrude, especially when the patient attempts to push against resistance, a condition known as 'winged scapula'.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (C5, C6) (Incorrect): While C5 and C6 contribute to the long thoracic nerve, simply stating the nerve roots is too broad and could imply other brachial plexus injuries like Erb's palsy, which presents differently.\nOption B (C8, T1) (Incorrect): C8 and T1 nerve roots are primarily associated with Klumpke's palsy, affecting intrinsic hand muscles and forearm flexors, not the shoulder girdle stability in this manner.\nOption C (Axillary nerve) (Incorrect): The axillary nerve (C5, C6) innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles. Injury to this nerve causes weakness in shoulder abduction and external rotation, along with sensory loss over the lateral shoulder, but does not cause scapular winging.\nOption E (Spinal accessory nerve) (Incorrect): The spinal accessory nerve (CN XI) innervates the trapezius muscle. Injury to this nerve causes a different type of scapular winging, where the scapula rotates laterally (inferior angle moves laterally, superior angle protrudes), and the patient has difficulty shrugging the shoulder. The question describes medial protrusion, which is characteristic of long thoracic nerve injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve Injured | Muscle Affected | Scapular Winging Type | Key Clinical Sign |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Long Thoracic Nerve | Serratus Anterior | Medial | Medial border of scapula protrudes, difficulty pushing forward |\n| Spinal Accessory Nerve | Trapezius | Lateral | Lateral rotation of scapula, difficulty shrugging shoulder |\n| Dorsal Scapular Nerve | Rhomboids, Levator Scapulae | Medial (less common) | Scapula displaced laterally, difficulty retracting scapula |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial scapular winging post-axillary dissection = Long Thoracic nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the long thoracic nerve is identified running on the superficial aspect of the serratus anterior muscle, often described as lying on the 'chest wall' or 'rib cage' during axillary dissection. On physical exam, the medial border and inferior angle of the scapula will visibly protrude, especially when the patient performs a wall push-up or pushes against resistance.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024). These guidelines outline surgical approaches for breast cancer, including axillary dissection, and implicitly address the importance of minimizing iatrogenic nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | C5, C6 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | C8, T1 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Axillary nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Long thoracic nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Spinal accessory nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The patient has a winged scapula caused by damage to the long thoracic nerve (C5,6,7) during surgery** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
