  "answer": "D) Where axillary nodal involvement is suspected from the outset it is important to establish whether this is the case prior to surgery. This is because, if axillary metastatic disease is present then the correct management would be an axillary node clearance and this is irrespective of the surgical plans for the breast primary. In the case of breast cancer, image guided FNAC is acceptable as it is accurate and if carcinoma cells are identified at FNA then axillary node clearance can be performed. If FNAC is negative then a sentinel node biopsy should accompany excision of the primary tumour. Where the axilla is clinically clear on palpation and imaging then a sentinel lymph node biopsy should accompany excision of the primary tumour.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
