  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let the goose get your goat; check the pes anserinus!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Pes Anserinus Bursitis. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the patient's symptoms of medial, proximal tibia pain, especially with stair climbing, in an athlete, and crucially, a negative McMurray test which effectively rules out meniscal injury.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe pes anserinus is the conjoined insertion of the sartorius, gracilius, and semitendinosus tendons onto the anteromedial aspect of the proximal tibia, resembling a goose's foot. Bursitis in this area is a common overuse injury in athletes, particularly those involved in running or sports requiring repetitive knee flexion and extension, like stair climbing. The inflammation of the bursa beneath these tendons causes localized pain and swelling precisely where the patient reports symptoms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Anterior cruciate ligament tear) (Incorrect): An ACL tear typically presents with instability, a 'pop' sensation, and positive Lachman or anterior drawer tests, not isolated medial proximal tibia pain.\nOption B (Prepatellar bursitis) (Incorrect): Prepatellar bursitis causes pain and swelling directly over the patella, on the anterior aspect of the knee, not the medial side.\nOption C (Medial meniscus injury) (Incorrect): While a medial meniscus injury causes medial knee pain, it often presents with mechanical symptoms like locking or catching, and the McMurray test would typically be positive, which is explicitly negative in this case.\nOption E (Fracture of tibia) (Incorrect): A tibial fracture would present with acute, severe pain, often following significant trauma, and would likely impair weight-bearing significantly, which is not described here.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Location of Pain | Key Clinical Feature | McMurray Test |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pes Anserinus Bursitis | Medial, proximal tibia | Pain with stairs, overuse in athletes | Negative |\n| Medial Meniscus Tear | Medial joint line | Locking, catching, giving way | Positive |\n| MCL Sprain | Medial joint line | Valgus stress tenderness, instability | Negative |\n| Medial Compartment OA | Medial joint line | Gradual onset, stiffness, crepitus | Variable |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial proximal tibia pain + negative McMurray = Pes Anserinus Bursitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound can confirm pes anserinus bursitis by showing fluid accumulation within the bursa and thickening of the surrounding tendons. MRI may also show bursal fluid and inflammation, helping to rule out other intra-articular pathologies. There are no image tags in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Medical Society for Sports Medicine (AMSSM) Position Statement: Overuse Injuries in Athletes (2019) recommends conservative management for most bursitides.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anterior cruciate ligament tear | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Prepatellar bursitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Medial meniscus injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pes Anserinus Bursitis | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Fracture of tibia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Pes anserinus: GOOSE'S FOOT Combination of sartorius, gracilis and semitendinous tendons inserting i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
