  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Deep peroneal nerve injury means drop foot, but not a floppy foot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Peroneus longus because its innervation comes from the superficial peroneal nerve, not the deep peroneal nerve. Division of the deep peroneal nerve would therefore spare the Peroneus longus muscle, which is responsible for ankle eversion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe common peroneal nerve divides into superficial and deep branches. The deep peroneal nerve primarily innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg, responsible for ankle dorsiflexion and toe extension, including the Tibialis anterior, Extensor hallucis longus, Extensor digitorum longus, and Peroneus tertius. In contrast, the superficial peroneal nerve innervates the muscles of the lateral compartment, namely the Peroneus longus and Peroneus brevis, which are responsible for ankle eversion and some plantarflexion. Therefore, injury to the deep peroneal nerve would not affect the Peroneus longus.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Tibialis anterior is innervated by the deep peroneal nerve and is responsible for dorsiflexion and inversion; its function would be affected.\nOption C (Incorrect): Extensor hallucis longus is innervated by the deep peroneal nerve and extends the great toe; its function would be affected.\nOption D (Incorrect): Extensor digitorum longus is innervated by the deep peroneal nerve and extends the lateral four toes; its function would be affected.\nOption E (Incorrect): Peroneus tertius is innervated by the deep peroneal nerve and assists in dorsiflexion and eversion; its function would be affected.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve Branch | Compartment | Key Muscles | Primary Action |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Deep Peroneal | Anterior | Tibialis anterior, Extensor hallucis longus, Extensor digitorum longus, Peroneus tertius | Ankle dorsiflexion, toe extension |\n| Superficial Peroneal | Lateral | Peroneus longus, Peroneus brevis | Ankle eversion, some plantarflexion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Deep peroneal = dorsiflexion, Superficial peroneal = eversion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a divided deep peroneal nerve would appear as a transected white, cord-like structure, often with a visible neuroma if chronic. Nerve repair would involve careful identification of the nerve ends and microsurgical anastomosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Tibial Shaft Fractures (2019). Recommends careful neurovascular assessment and documentation in all tibial fracture cases, with consideration for nerve exploration and repair in cases of documented injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Tibialis anterior | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Peroneus longus | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Extensor hallucis longus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Extensor digitorum longus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Peroneus tertius | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Peroneus longus is innervated by the superficial peroneal nerve (L4, L5, S1)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
