  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tongue's motor maestro? Hypoglossal, always!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Hypoglossal. The hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) is the primary motor nerve for the tongue, innervating all intrinsic and most extrinsic muscles, including styloglossus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) originates from the medulla, exits the skull through the hypoglossal canal, and then courses through the neck to supply the tongue. Styloglossus is one of the three extrinsic tongue muscles (along with genioglossus and hyoglossus) responsible for altering the tongue's position, crucial for speech, swallowing, and mastication. Damage to this nerve can lead to ipsilateral tongue deviation and atrophy, highlighting its vital role in tongue function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Facial nerve (CN VII) primarily supplies muscles of facial expression, taste to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, and parasympathetic innervation to salivary glands, not motor to styloglossus.\nOption B (Incorrect): The Trigeminal nerve (CN V) is responsible for mastication muscles, sensory innervation to the face, and general sensation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, but not motor innervation to styloglossus.\nOption C (Incorrect): The Vagus nerve (CN X) primarily innervates muscles of the pharynx, larynx, and soft palate. While it contributes to the innervation of palatoglossus (the only extrinsic tongue muscle not primarily supplied by CN XII), it does not innervate styloglossus.\nOption E (Incorrect): The Glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) supplies the stylopharyngeus muscle, taste and general sensation to the posterior one-third of the tongue, and parasympathetic innervation to the parotid gland, but not motor to styloglossus.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cranial Nerve | Primary Tongue Motor Function | Primary Tongue Sensory/Taste Function |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hypoglossal (CN XII) | All intrinsic & extrinsic (except palatoglossus) | None |\n| Vagus (CN X) | Palatoglossus (via pharyngeal plexus) | None |\n| Glossopharyngeal (CN IX) | None | Taste & general sensation posterior 1/3 |\n| Trigeminal (CN V) | None | General sensation anterior 2/3 |\n| Facial (CN VII) | None | Taste anterior 2/3 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hypoglossal moves the tongue; others taste or feel it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) can be identified in the submandibular triangle, typically running superficial to the hyoglossus muscle and deep to the posterior belly of the digastric muscle. It is a critical structure to preserve during neck dissections, submandibular gland excisions, or floor of mouth surgeries.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific guideline applies directly to this anatomical fact.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Facial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Trigeminal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Vagus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypoglossal | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Glossopharyngeal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The hypoglossal nerve supplies motor innervation to all extrinsic and intrinsic muscles of the tongu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
