  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hepatic artery branches: Know them or risk a surgical misstep!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, 'Pancreatic artery'. This question tests fundamental knowledge of upper abdominal vascular anatomy, specifically the branches of the hepatic artery. The pancreatic artery is notably a branch of the splenic artery, not the hepatic artery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUnderstanding the arterial supply to the upper abdomen, particularly the celiac trunk and its major branches (common hepatic, splenic, left gastric), is critical for safe hepatobiliary and pancreatic surgery. The common hepatic artery typically gives rise to the gastroduodenal artery and then continues as the proper hepatic artery, which further branches into the right and left hepatic arteries. The cystic artery usually originates from the right hepatic artery, and the right gastric artery often arises from the proper hepatic artery. The pancreatic arteries, conversely, are typically branches of the splenic artery or gastroduodenal artery, not directly from the hepatic artery proper.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Cystic artery) (Incorrect): The cystic artery is a common branch of the right hepatic artery, which itself is a branch of the proper hepatic artery.\nOption C (Right gastric artery) (Incorrect): The right gastric artery is typically a branch of the proper hepatic artery, supplying the lesser curvature of the stomach.\nOption D (Right hepatic artery) (Incorrect): The right hepatic artery is a terminal branch of the proper hepatic artery, supplying the right lobe of the liver.\nOption E (Gastroduodenal artery) (Incorrect): The gastroduodenal artery is a major branch of the common hepatic artery, supplying the duodenum and head of the pancreas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery | Key Branches |\n|---|---|\n| **Celiac Trunk** | Common Hepatic Artery, Splenic Artery, Left Gastric Artery |\n| **Common Hepatic Artery** | Gastroduodenal Artery, Proper Hepatic Artery |\n| **Proper Hepatic Artery** | Right Hepatic Artery, Left Hepatic Artery, (often) Right Gastric Artery |\n| **Right Hepatic Artery** | Cystic Artery |\n| **Splenic Artery** | Pancreatic branches (e.g., dorsal pancreatic, great pancreatic), Short Gastric Arteries, Left Gastroepiploic Artery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know your celiac trunk branches cold for upper GI surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring angiography or intraoperative dissection, the common hepatic artery is identified originating from the celiac trunk. Tracing it distally reveals the gastroduodenal artery descending posterior to the first part of the duodenum, while the proper hepatic artery ascends towards the liver hilum. The splenic artery, in contrast, courses tortuously along the superior border of the pancreas, giving off numerous pancreatic branches before reaching the spleen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nN/A - This is a fundamental anatomy question. General surgical anatomy textbooks (e.g., Gray's Anatomy, Netter's Atlas of Human Anatomy) serve as the primary reference for this knowledge.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pancreatic artery | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Cystic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right gastric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Right hepatic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Gastroduodenal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The pancreatic artery is a branch of the splenic artery.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
