  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Posterior scalp pain? Think C2-C3, not CN V!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B is the false statement because the trigeminal nerve primarily innervates the face and anterior scalp. The posterior scalp receives its sensory supply from cervical spinal nerves, specifically C2 and C3.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe trigeminal nerve (CN V) is the principal sensory nerve of the face and anterior scalp, and also provides motor innervation to the muscles of mastication. Its three main divisions (ophthalmic, maxillary, mandibular) cover distinct facial territories. In contrast, the posterior scalp's sensory innervation is derived from the greater occipital nerve (C2) and lesser occipital nerve (C2, C3), highlighting a clear anatomical distinction between cranial nerve and spinal nerve territories.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The trigeminal nerve indeed originates from the lateral aspect of the pons, making this statement true.\nOption C (Incorrect): The maxillary nerve (V2) consistently exits the skull through the foramen rotundum, a true anatomical fact.\nOption D (Incorrect): The maxillary nerve (V2) is purely sensory, carrying no motor fibers, thus this statement is true.\nOption E (Incorrect): The motor root of the trigeminal nerve bypasses the trigeminal (Gasserian) ganglion and joins the mandibular nerve (V3) distal to it, as the ganglion contains only sensory neuron cell bodies. This statement is true.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Trigeminal Division | Primary Function | Exit Foramen |\n|---|---|---|\n| Ophthalmic (V1) | Sensory (forehead, upper eyelid, nose) | Superior Orbital Fissure |\n| Maxillary (V2) | Sensory (midface, upper teeth, palate) | Foramen Rotundum |\n| Mandibular (V3) | Sensory (lower face, lower teeth, tongue) & Motor (muscles of mastication) | Foramen Ovale |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Trigeminal nerve: Face and anterior scalp. Posterior scalp: C2-C3.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring skull base surgery, precise identification of the foramen rotundum is crucial for accessing the maxillary nerve (V2), while the foramen ovale is the landmark for the mandibular nerve (V3). No image was provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Neurological Surgeons (AANS) Guidelines for Trigeminal Neuralgia (2019) provide detailed anatomical context for understanding trigeminal nerve distribution and pathology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The nerve originates at the pons | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The posterior scalp is supplied by the trigeminal nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| C | The maxillary nerve exits via the foramen rotundum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The maxillary nerve is purely sensory | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | The motor root is not in the trigeminal ganglion | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The posterior scalp is supplied by C2-C3.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
