  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 First web space sensation? Deep peroneal's domain!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, the Deep peroneal nerve. This nerve is responsible for providing sensory innervation to the skin of the first web space of the foot, a key anatomical landmark for its distribution.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe deep peroneal nerve, a terminal branch of the common peroneal nerve (which itself arises from the sciatic nerve), descends in the anterior compartment of the leg. It runs closely with the anterior tibial artery. Distally, it crosses the ankle joint and divides into medial and lateral branches. The medial branch provides sensory innervation to the adjacent sides of the first and second toes, forming the first web space. It also supplies motor innervation to the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg and the intrinsic muscles of the dorsum of the foot.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Popliteal nerve is a general term for the nerve in the popliteal fossa, which then divides into the tibial and common peroneal nerves. It does not directly innervate the foot web space.\nOption B (Incorrect): The Superficial peroneal nerve primarily supplies sensory innervation to the dorsum of the foot and toes, but specifically *excludes* the first web space, which is supplied by the deep peroneal nerve.\nOption D (Incorrect): The Tibial nerve primarily innervates the posterior compartment of the leg and, via its medial and lateral plantar branches, provides sensory innervation to the sole of the foot.\nOption E (Incorrect): The Saphenous nerve, a branch of the femoral nerve, provides sensory innervation to the medial side of the leg and foot, but not the web spaces.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Primary Sensory Innervation (Foot) | Primary Motor Innervation (Foot/Leg) |\n| :----------------------- | :--------------------------------- | :----------------------------------- |\n| Deep Peroneal Nerve      | 1st web space                      | Anterior compartment muscles, intrinsic dorsal foot muscles |\n| Superficial Peroneal Nerve | Dorsum of foot (except 1st web space) | Lateral compartment muscles          |\n| Tibial Nerve (plantar branches) | Sole of foot                       | Posterior compartment muscles, intrinsic plantar foot muscles |\n| Sural Nerve              | Lateral aspect of foot, 5th toe    | None (sensory only)                  |\n| Saphenous Nerve          | Medial aspect of leg and foot      | None (sensory only)                  |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Deep peroneal nerve, first web space: \"D\" for Deep, \"D\" for Digit 1.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, the deep peroneal nerve can be identified running with the anterior tibial artery, often deep to the extensor retinaculum at the ankle. Injury to this nerve can result in a \"foot drop\" (motor deficit) and loss of sensation in the first web space (sensory deficit).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNot applicable for basic anatomical questions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Popliteal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Superficial peroneal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Deep peroneal nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Tibial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Saphenous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The first web space is innervated by the deep peroneal nerve.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
