  "answer": "D) Upper motor neurone lesions of the facial nerve- Paralysis of the lower half of face. Lower motor neurone lesion- Paralysis of the entire ipsilateral face.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 If the brow can furrow, the lesion's higher.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 'Raise eyebrow' because it directly assesses the muscles of the upper face. In an upper motor neuron (UMN) lesion, the forehead muscles are typically spared due to bilateral cortical innervation, whereas in a lower motor neuron (LMN) lesion, the entire ipsilateral face, including the forehead, is paralyzed.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe facial nucleus in the brainstem receives innervation from both cerebral hemispheres for the upper face (frontalis and orbicularis oculi muscles), while the lower face (muscles of the mouth) receives contralateral innervation only. Therefore, a unilateral UMN lesion (e.g., stroke in the motor cortex) will only affect the contralateral lower face, sparing the forehead. Conversely, an LMN lesion (e.g., Bell's palsy, tumor affecting the facial nerve itself) affects the entire ipsilateral facial nerve, leading to paralysis of both upper and lower facial muscles on that side. Testing the ability to raise the eyebrow directly evaluates the frontalis muscle, making it the most useful distinguishing test.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Blow cheeks out) (Incorrect): This tests the buccinator muscle, which is part of the lower face. Both UMN and LMN lesions would impair this function, making it unhelpful for distinction.\nOption B (Loss of chin reflex) (Incorrect): The chin reflex (jaw jerk) primarily involves the trigeminal nerve (V) and is not a standard test for distinguishing UMN from LMN facial nerve lesions.\nOption C (Close eye) (Incorrect): While orbicularis oculi is affected in LMN lesions, its involvement in UMN lesions can be variable or less pronounced than the lower face, making 'raise eyebrow' a more definitive test for forehead sparing.\nOption E (Open mouth against resistance) (Incorrect): This primarily tests muscles of mastication (trigeminal nerve) or neck muscles, not the facial nerve, and is irrelevant for distinguishing UMN/LMN facial nerve lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Upper Motor Neuron (UMN) Lesion | Lower Motor Neuron (LMN) Lesion |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------ | :------------------------------ |\n| **Forehead**        | Spared (can raise eyebrow)      | Paralyzed (cannot raise eyebrow) |\n| **Eye Closure**     | Often spared or mild weakness   | Impaired (lagophthalmos)        |\n| **Lower Face**      | Contralateral paralysis         | Ipsilateral paralysis           |\n| **Cause**           | Stroke, tumor (cortex/brainstem)| Bell's palsy, trauma, tumor (nerve) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Forehead sparing = UMN. Entire face = LMN.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo image was provided in the question. Imaging such as MRI of the brain or temporal bone would be used to identify the location of the lesion (e.g., cortical stroke for UMN, acoustic neuroma or inflammatory changes for LMN).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Neurology (AAN) Practice Guideline: Evaluation and Management of Bell's Palsy (2012). It recommends clinical examination to distinguish Bell's palsy (LMN) from other causes of facial weakness.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Blow cheeks out | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Loss of chin reflex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Close eye | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Raise eyebrow | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Open mouth against resistance | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Upper motor neurone lesions of the facial nerve- Paralysis of the lower half of face. Lower motor ne** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
