  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Upper trunk woes? Think C5-C6, not C8-T1!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Palmar interossei. An isolated injury to the upper trunk of the brachial plexus (C5, C6) will primarily affect muscles innervated by nerves originating from these roots, while muscles supplied by the ulnar nerve (C8, T1) are typically spared.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe brachial plexus is formed by the ventral rami of C5-T1. The upper trunk is formed by the union of C5 and C6 roots. Nerves arising directly from or significantly contributed to by the upper trunk include the suprascapular nerve (infraspinatus), musculocutaneous nerve (brachialis), and parts of the radial nerve (supinator brevis). The ulnar nerve, however, is a terminal branch of the medial cord, which is formed by the anterior division of the lower trunk (C8, T1). Therefore, an injury isolated to the upper trunk would not typically affect the ulnar nerve or its innervated muscles like the palmar interossei.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The infraspinatus is innervated by the suprascapular nerve, which arises directly from the upper trunk (C5, C6). Injury to the upper trunk would impair its function.\nOption C (Incorrect): The brachialis muscle is innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve, which is a terminal branch of the lateral cord, formed by contributions from the upper and middle trunks (C5, C6, C7). Its function would be impaired.\nOption D (Incorrect): The supinator brevis is innervated by the posterior interosseous nerve, a branch of the radial nerve. The radial nerve receives contributions from all roots (C5-T1), but C5 and C6 are significant, making impairment likely.\nOption E (Incorrect): Option A is the correct answer, as the palmar interossei are least likely to be affected.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Roots | Example Muscle | Upper Trunk Injury Effect |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Suprascapular | C5, C6 | Infraspinatus | Impaired |\n| Musculocutaneous | C5, C6, C7 | Brachialis | Impaired |\n| Radial | C5-T1 | Supinator brevis | Likely Impaired |\n| Ulnar | C8, T1 | Palmar interossei | Unlikely Impaired |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Upper trunk injury spares C8/T1 innervated muscles.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a laceration or avulsion of the C5 and C6 nerve roots or the upper trunk itself would be visible, often with associated hematoma or scar tissue requiring careful neurolysis or repair.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Surgery of the Hand (ASSH) Clinical Practice Guideline for Brachial Plexus Injury (2017) recommends early surgical exploration and repair for sharp transections of the brachial plexus to optimize functional outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Palmar interossei | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Infraspinatus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Brachialis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Supinator brevis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The palmar interossei are supplied by the ulnar nerve. Which lies inferiorly and is therefore less l** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
