  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Iliac nodes are the first stop for endometrial body cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Iliac lymph nodes. Endometrial carcinoma arising from the uterine body primarily drains to the external and internal iliac lymph nodes, making them the initial site of metastatic spread. This understanding is crucial for accurate surgical staging and appropriate lymphadenectomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lymphatic drainage of the uterine body predominantly follows the uterine vessels to the external and internal iliac lymph node chains. Specifically, while the superior aspect of the uterine body (fundus) can also drain to the para-aortic nodes via the infundibulopelvic ligament, the main body's primary drainage is to the iliacs. This direct anatomical connection dictates the pattern of initial lymphatic metastasis, which is a cornerstone of surgical planning for endometrial cancer, guiding the extent of lymphadenectomy during procedures like a modified radical hysterectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Para aortic nodes) (Incorrect): While the uterine fundus can drain to para-aortic nodes, the primary drainage for the main uterine body is to the iliac nodes. Para-aortic involvement usually indicates more advanced disease or spread from the fundus.\nOption C (Inguinal nodes) (Incorrect): Inguinal nodes are the primary drainage for the vulva, lower vagina, and clitoris, not the uterine body. Spread to inguinal nodes from endometrial cancer is rare and typically indicates advanced disease with involvement of the lower uterine segment or direct extension.\nOption D (Pre sacral nodes) (Incorrect): Presacral nodes primarily drain the posterior pelvic organs like the rectum and sacrum. They are not the initial drainage site for the uterine body.\nOption E (Mesorectal lymph nodes) (Incorrect): Mesorectal lymph nodes are associated with the rectum and its lymphatic drainage. They are not involved in the primary lymphatic spread of endometrial carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organ/Region | Primary Lymphatic Drainage |\n|---|---|\n| Uterine Body | External and Internal Iliac nodes |\n| Uterine Fundus | Para-aortic nodes (via infundibulopelvic ligament), External/Internal Iliac nodes |\n| Cervix | Obturator, Internal Iliac, External Iliac, Presacral nodes |\n| Vulva/Lower Vagina | Inguinal nodes (superficial and deep) |\n| Ovary/Fallopian Tube | Para-aortic nodes (via infundibulopelvic ligament) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Endometrial body cancer drains to iliac nodes first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, surgeons meticulously identify and dissect the external and internal iliac lymph node chains, often guided by anatomical landmarks like the external iliac artery and obturator nerve. On imaging (CT/MRI), enlarged or suspicious iliac lymph nodes would raise concern for metastatic disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Endometrial Carcinoma (2024) recommend pelvic lymphadenectomy (including external and internal iliac nodes) for staging in intermediate to high-risk endometrial cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Para aortic nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Iliac lymph nodes | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Inguinal nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pre sacral nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Mesorectal lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Tumours of the uterine body will tend to spread to the iliac nodes initially. Tumour expansion cross** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
