  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Thumb's palmar touch? Median nerve's clutch!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is B, Median nerve. The median nerve is the primary sensory nerve for the palmar aspect of the thumb, as well as the radial side of the hand, making it crucial for fine motor control and sensation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe median nerve provides sensory innervation to the palmar surface of the thumb, index, middle, and radial half of the ring finger, including their nail beds. This innervation is supplied by the common palmar digital nerves, which then divide into proper palmar digital nerves. The palmar cutaneous branch of the median nerve also supplies the skin over the thenar eminence, which includes the base of the thumb. This extensive sensory supply is vital for tactile discrimination and grip function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The ulnar nerve supplies the palmar aspect of the little finger and the ulnar half of the ring finger, as well as the hypothenar eminence, not the thumb.\nOption C (Incorrect): The radial nerve primarily supplies the dorsal aspect of the hand, specifically the dorsal thumb, index, middle, and radial half of the ring finger up to the PIP joint, and the dorsal web space, but not the palmar aspect of the thumb.\nOption D (Incorrect): The musculocutaneous nerve supplies muscles of the anterior arm and the skin of the lateral forearm via the lateral antebrachial cutaneous nerve; it does not innervate any part of the hand.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Sensory Distribution (Palmar) | Sensory Distribution (Dorsal) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Median | Thumb, index, middle, radial 1/2 ring finger, thenar eminence | Distal phalanges of index, middle, radial 1/2 ring finger |\n| Ulnar | Little finger, ulnar 1/2 ring finger, hypothenar eminence | Little finger, ulnar 1/2 ring finger |\n| Radial | None (palmar) | Thumb, index, middle, radial 1/2 ring finger (proximal to PIP), dorsal web space |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Median nerve: 'LOAF' muscles and palmar thumb sensation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, during carpal tunnel release, the median nerve is identified deep to the transverse carpal ligament. Its palmar cutaneous branch typically arises proximal to the ligament and courses superficially, requiring careful dissection to avoid injury. The recurrent motor branch to the thenar muscles usually arises from the radial side of the median nerve within the carpal tunnel.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Surgery of the Hand (ASSH) 2022 Clinical Practice Guideline for Carpal Tunnel Syndrome. This guideline emphasizes the importance of understanding median nerve anatomy for diagnosis and treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ulnar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Median | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Radial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Musculocutaneous | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
