  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Know your Calot's triangle; the right hepatic artery is often the culprit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the Right hepatic artery. Avulsion of the cystic artery during laparoscopic cholecystectomy most commonly results in brisk hemorrhage from its parent vessel, the right hepatic artery, due to its typical anatomical origin.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe cystic artery, which supplies the gallbladder, typically originates from the right hepatic artery in approximately 90% of cases. This anatomical relationship is crucial in Calot's triangle. When the cystic artery is avulsed, the bleeding point is often the stump of the right hepatic artery itself, or a significant branch directly off it, leading to brisk arterial hemorrhage. While anatomical variations exist, understanding the most common origin is paramount for safe dissection and hemorrhage control during cholecystectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Portal vein) (Incorrect): The portal vein is a large venous structure that carries blood from the gastrointestinal tract to the liver; it is not an arterial source of brisk hemorrhage in Calot's triangle.\nOption C (Gastroduodenal artery) (Incorrect): The gastroduodenal artery originates from the common hepatic artery and supplies the stomach, duodenum, and pancreas, not directly involved in the blood supply of the gallbladder or Calot's triangle.\nOption D (Liver bed) (Incorrect): While the liver bed can bleed, avulsion of a named artery like the cystic artery would result in a more significant, pulsatile hemorrhage than typical capillary ooze from the liver bed.\nOption E (Common hepatic artery) (Incorrect): The common hepatic artery is more proximal and gives rise to the proper hepatic artery, which then branches into the right and left hepatic arteries. It is not the direct source of the cystic artery in most cases.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery | Typical Origin | Primary Supply |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cystic Artery | Right Hepatic Artery | Gallbladder |\n| Right Hepatic Artery | Proper Hepatic Artery | Right hepatic lobe, (Cystic Artery) |\n| Common Hepatic Artery | Celiac Trunk | Proper Hepatic Artery, Gastroduodenal Artery |\n| Gastroduodenal Artery | Common Hepatic Artery | Stomach, Duodenum, Pancreas |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The cystic artery usually branches directly from the right hepatic artery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, brisk, pulsatile bleeding from the superior aspect of Calot's triangle after avulsion of the cystic artery strongly suggests injury to the right hepatic artery. The surgeon would see a jet of bright red blood emanating from the area where the cystic artery was previously attached, often requiring immediate clip application or suture ligation to the right hepatic artery stump.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Safe Cholecystectomy Task Force Guidelines 2014: Emphasizes critical view of safety and awareness of anatomical variations to prevent bile duct and vascular injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right hepatic artery | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Portal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gastroduodenal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Liver bed | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Common hepatic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The cystic artery is a branch of the right hepatic artery. There are recognised variations in the an** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
