  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spinal shock hides UMN signs; hyperreflexia emerges later.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. A thoracic spinal cord lesion, after the resolution of spinal shock, manifests as an Upper Motor Neuron (UMN) lesion. UMN lesions cause hyperreflexia, not diminished reflexes, making diminished patellar reflex the finding that would *not* be present 6 weeks after injury.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute spinal cord injury initially causes spinal shock, characterized by flaccid paralysis and areflexia below the level of injury. This phase typically lasts days to weeks. As spinal shock resolves, the classic UMN signs emerge: spasticity, hyperreflexia (including extensor plantar reflexes or Babinski sign), and autonomic dysfunction such as neurogenic bladder leading to incontinence. The patellar reflex is a deep tendon reflex, which would become hyperactive in an UMN lesion due to loss of inhibitory supraspinal control, not diminished.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Extensor plantar reflexes (Babinski sign) are a classic sign of an UMN lesion, which would be present after spinal shock resolves.\nOption B (Incorrect): Spasticity of the lower limbs is a hallmark of chronic UMN lesions below the level of injury.\nOption D (Incorrect): Urinary incontinence is common with thoracic spinal cord lesions due to loss of supraspinal control over bladder function (neurogenic bladder).\nOption E (Incorrect): Sensory ataxia can result from damage to the posterior columns (proprioception pathways) in the spinal cord, which is likely with severe cord compression.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Spinal Shock (Acute) | Chronic UMN Lesion (Post-shock) | LMN Lesion |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Reflexes | Areflexia/Hyporeflexia | Hyperreflexia | Areflexia/Hyporeflexia |\n| Tone | Flaccid | Spastic | Flaccid |\n| Plantar Reflex | Absent/Flexor | Extensor (Babinski) | Absent/Flexor |\n| Muscle Atrophy | Minimal | Disuse atrophy | Severe, rapid |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: UMN lesions cause hyperreflexia, not hyporeflexia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMRI of the thoracic spine would show a T4 vertebral body pathological fracture with significant retropulsion of bone fragments into the spinal canal, causing severe spinal cord compression. Edema within the spinal cord at the T4 level would also be visible, indicating acute injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Central Nervous System Cancers (2023). These guidelines provide recommendations for the management of metastatic spinal cord compression, including surgical intervention and radiation therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Extensor plantar reflexes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Spasticity of the lower limbs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Diminished patellar tendon reflex | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Urinary incontinence | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sensory ataxia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) A thoracic cord lesion causes spastic paraperesis, hyperrflexia and extensor plantar responses (UMN ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
