  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Know your hip rotators, or you'll be rotating out of the OR!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies the Quadratus femoris as the muscle that does not insert on the medial surface of the greater trochanter. Its distinct insertion on the intertrochanteric crest differentiates it from the other deep external rotators of the hip.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe deep external rotators of the hip, often remembered by the mnemonic POGO (Piriformis, Obturator internus, Gemelli, Obturator externus), all share a common theme of inserting onto the greater trochanter or its medial aspect/trochanteric fossa. The Quadratus femoris, while also a powerful external rotator, has a unique insertion point on the quadrate tubercle located on the intertrochanteric crest. This precise anatomical distinction is critical for understanding hip biomechanics, surgical approaches, and potential sites of pathology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gemelli - Incorrect): The superior and inferior gemelli insert with the obturator internus tendon into the medial surface of the greater trochanter.\nOption B (Obturator internus - Incorrect): The obturator internus inserts into the medial surface of the greater trochanter, specifically the trochanteric fossa.\nOption C (Piriformis - Incorrect): The piriformis inserts into the superior aspect of the greater trochanter.\nOption E (Obturator externus - Incorrect): The obturator externus inserts into the trochanteric fossa of the greater trochanter.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Muscle | Primary Action | Insertion Site |\n|---|---|---|\n| Piriformis | External rotation, abduction | Superior aspect of greater trochanter |\n| Obturator Internus | External rotation, abduction | Medial surface of greater trochanter (trochanteric fossa) |\n| Gemelli (Sup & Inf) | External rotation, abduction | Medial surface of greater trochanter (with Obturator Internus) |\n| Obturator Externus | External rotation, adduction | Trochanteric fossa of greater trochanter |\n| Quadratus Femoris | External rotation, adduction | Quadrate tubercle on intertrochanteric crest |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: POGO muscles insert on the greater trochanter; Quadratus femoris inserts on the intertrochanteric crest.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring a posterior hip approach, the short external rotators are encountered. The quadratus femoris lies inferior to the gemelli and obturator internus complex, with its distinct tendinous insertion on the intertrochanteric crest palpable or visible. On MRI, these individual muscle and tendon insertions can be clearly delineated, aiding in the diagnosis of tendinopathy or avulsion injuries.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific surgical guideline applies to this fundamental anatomical knowledge.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gemelli | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Obturator internus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Piriformis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Quadratus femoris | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Obturator externus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Mnemonic for muscle attachment on greater trochanter is POGO:\nPiriformis\nObturator internus\nGemelli\n** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
