  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The jaw's angle is a greater auricular nerve's angle!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, the greater auricular nerve (C2-C3). This nerve provides sensory innervation to the skin over the angle of the mandible, an important exception to the general facial sensory supply by the trigeminal nerve.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe greater auricular nerve is a cutaneous branch of the cervical plexus, arising from the C2 and C3 spinal nerves. It ascends superficially on the sternocleidomastoid muscle, then curves around its posterior border to supply sensation to the skin over the parotid gland, mastoid process, and crucially, the angle of the mandible. This distinct innervation pattern is a classic anatomical detail that differentiates it from the trigeminal nerve's extensive facial sensory distribution.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The maxillary branch of the trigeminal nerve (V2) supplies sensation to the midface, including the upper lip, nose, and cheek, but not the angle of the jaw.\nOption B (Incorrect): The mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (V3) supplies sensation to the lower face, including the lower lip, chin, and temporal region, but the angle of the jaw is a well-known exception.\nOption C (Incorrect): While C3-C4 contribute to the cervical plexus, simply stating 'C3-C4' is too broad; the specific nerve responsible is the greater auricular nerve.\nOption E (Incorrect): The buccal branch of the facial nerve (CN VII) is primarily a motor nerve supplying muscles of facial expression, not sensory innervation to the skin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve                  | Origin           | Sensory Distribution                                                               | Key Exception/Note                               |\n|------------------------|------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|\n| Trigeminal Nerve (V1)  | Pons             | Forehead, upper eyelid, nose dorsum                                                | Ophthalmic division                              |\n| Trigeminal Nerve (V2)  | Pons             | Midface, upper lip, maxillary teeth                                                | Maxillary division                               |\n| Trigeminal Nerve (V3)  | Pons             | Lower face, lower lip, mandibular teeth, anterior 2/3 tongue (general sensation) | Mandibular division; *excludes angle of jaw*     |\n| Greater Auricular Nerve| Cervical Plexus (C2, C3) | Skin over parotid gland, mastoid, and *angle of the mandible*                      | Key sensory nerve for the angle of the jaw       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Angle of jaw sensation? Think greater auricular, not trigeminal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring neck dissection or parotidectomy, the greater auricular nerve is often identified as it crosses the sternocleidomastoid muscle. Surgeons must be mindful of its location to preserve sensation to the earlobe and angle of the jaw, as injury can lead to numbness in these areas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis is fundamental human anatomy, not typically covered by specific surgical society guidelines. It is a core concept in neuroanatomy and head and neck surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Maxillary branch of the trigeminal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | C3-C4 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Greater auricular nerve (C2-C3) | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Buccal branch of the facial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The trigeminal nerve is the major sensory nerve to the face except over the angle of the jaw. The an** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
