  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let tight pants pinch your nerve; meralgia paresthetica is a real pain!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, the lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh. The classic presentation of burning pain in the anterolateral thigh, exacerbated by walking, and a positive Tinel's sign over the inguinal ligament, is pathognomonic for meralgia paresthetica, which is entrapment of this specific nerve.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeralgia paresthetica results from compression of the lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh (LCFNT) as it passes under or through the inguinal ligament, typically near the anterior superior iliac spine. This purely sensory nerve supplies the skin of the anterolateral thigh. Its superficial course makes it vulnerable to external compression (e.g., tight clothing, obesity, pregnancy) or internal factors. The positive Tinel's sign at the inguinal ligament directly indicates nerve irritation at this common entrapment point.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The ilioinguinal nerve supplies sensation to the upper medial thigh, root of the penis/scrotum, or labia majora. Its distribution does not match the patient's symptoms.\nOption B (Incorrect): The genitofemoral nerve supplies sensation to the femoral triangle (femoral branch) and the scrotum/labia majora (genital branch). Its sensory distribution is distinct from the anterolateral thigh.\nOption D (Incorrect): The femoral nerve is a major mixed nerve supplying motor function to the quadriceps and sensation to the anterior thigh and medial leg via its saphenous branch. Entrapment would typically involve motor deficits and a broader sensory loss.\nOption E (Incorrect): The saphenous nerve is a terminal sensory branch of the femoral nerve, providing sensation to the medial aspect of the leg and foot. Its distribution does not align with the patient's symptoms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Sensory Distribution | Common Entrapment Syndrome |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Lateral Cutaneous Nerve of Thigh | L2-L3 | Anterolateral thigh | Meralgia Paresthetica |\n| Ilioinguinal Nerve | L1 | Upper medial thigh, root of penis/scrotum, labia majora | Ilioinguinal nerve entrapment |\n| Genitofemoral Nerve | L1-L2 | Femoral triangle, scrotum/labia majora | Genitofemoral neuralgia |\n| Femoral Nerve | L2-L4 | Anterior thigh, medial leg (via saphenous) | Femoral neuropathy (motor & sensory) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anterolateral thigh burning + Tinel's at inguinal ligament = Meralgia Paresthetica.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging like X-ray or MRI is usually normal but can rule out other causes. Ultrasound may show focal swelling or altered echogenicity of the lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh at the inguinal ligament. Intraoperatively, the nerve may appear compressed or tethered as it passes under or through the inguinal ligament.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Peripheral Nerve Entrapment Syndromes (2016) - Recommends conservative measures first, followed by injections or surgical decompression if refractory.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ilioinguinal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Genitofemoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Femoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Saphenous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The lateral cutaneous nerve supplies sensation to the anterior and lateral aspect of the thigh. Entr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
