  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 T12: Celiac's high-rise, foregut's supply.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, T12. The celiac axis consistently originates from the anterior aspect of the abdominal aorta at the T12 vertebral level, making it a crucial anatomical landmark for interventional radiologists performing angiograms for gastrointestinal bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe celiac axis is the first major anterior branch of the abdominal aorta, typically arising just below the aortic hiatus of the diaphragm at the T12 vertebral level. It is responsible for supplying blood to the foregut derivatives, including the stomach, liver, spleen, pancreas, and parts of the duodenum. Its consistent anatomical position at T12 is a reliable landmark for catheter placement during angiography and for surgical dissection, allowing for precise localization of bleeding sources in the upper gastrointestinal tract.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (T10) (Incorrect): T10 is too high for the celiac axis; it is more commonly associated with the origin of the superior mesenteric artery in some variations, or the renal arteries are lower. The celiac axis is typically at T12.\nOption B (L3) (Incorrect): L3 is too low for the celiac axis. The inferior mesenteric artery (IMA) typically arises around the L3 vertebral level.\nOption C (L4) (Incorrect): L4 is the level at which the abdominal aorta typically bifurcates into the common iliac arteries. No major visceral arteries originate at this level.\nOption E (None of the above) (Incorrect): T12 is the correct anatomical level for the origin of the celiac axis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery | Spinal Level | Key Supply |\n|---|---|---|\n| Celiac Axis | T12 | Foregut (stomach, liver, spleen, pancreas, duodenum) |\n| Superior Mesenteric Artery (SMA) | L1 | Midgut (small intestine, right colon) |\n| Renal Arteries | L1-L2 | Kidneys, adrenal glands |\n| Inferior Mesenteric Artery (IMA) | L3 | Hindgut (left colon, rectum) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Celiac at T12, SMA at L1, IMA at L3.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an angiogram, the catheter is advanced to the T12 level to cannulate the celiac axis. Contrast injection will then reveal the characteristic 'seagull sign' branching pattern formed by its three main branches: the left gastric, splenic, and common hepatic arteries. On CT angiography, the celiac axis origin at T12 is clearly visualized, often just inferior to the diaphragm.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Suspected Gastrointestinal Bleeding (e.g., 2021). These guidelines recommend angiography for active GI bleeding when endoscopy is unsuccessful or not feasible, emphasizing the importance of precise anatomical localization for successful intervention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | T10 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | L3 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | L4 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | T12 | ✅ Correct |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The coeliac axis lies at T12, it takes an almost horizontal angle off the aorta. It has three major ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
