  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't pull the right adrenal; it's directly connected to the IVC!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Inferior Vena Cava. The right adrenal vein is uniquely short and drains directly into the IVC, making it highly susceptible to avulsion during traction, leading to brisk and potentially life-threatening bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe right adrenal gland's venous drainage is via a single, short right adrenal vein that empties directly into the posterior aspect of the Inferior Vena Cava. This anatomical proximity and short length make it extremely vulnerable to tearing or avulsion from the IVC wall when the gland is manipulated or pulled, as described in the scenario. Such an injury results in significant hemorrhage due to the high flow and pressure within the IVC. Management typically involves immediate control, often with a Satinsky clamp, and repair with fine non-absorbable suture.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The portal vein is part of the hepatic portal system, draining the gastrointestinal tract, spleen, and pancreas, not the adrenal gland.\nOption B (Incorrect): Phrenic veins drain the diaphragm. While anatomically close, they are not the primary or most vulnerable venous drainage of the adrenal gland during its mobilization.\nOption C (Incorrect): The right renal vein drains the right kidney. While the left adrenal vein typically drains into the left renal vein, the right adrenal vein drains directly into the IVC, not the right renal vein.\nOption D (Incorrect): The superior mesenteric vein drains parts of the small and large intestines and is not involved in adrenal venous drainage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Right Adrenal Gland                               | Left Adrenal Gland                                |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------------ |\n| Venous Drainage     | Single, short right adrenal vein                  | Single, longer left adrenal vein                  |\n| Drainage Destination| Directly into Inferior Vena Cava (IVC)            | Into Left Renal Vein                              |\n| Surgical Vulnerability | Avulsion from IVC due to short length and direct connection | Injury to left renal vein or adrenal vein during dissection |\n| Arterial Supply     | Superior, middle, and inferior adrenal arteries   | Superior, middle, and inferior adrenal arteries   |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right adrenal vein: short, direct to IVC, high avulsion risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, during a right adrenalectomy, the right adrenal gland is found superior to the right kidney, often partially retrohepatic. The critical structure to identify and carefully ligate is the short right adrenal vein, which can be seen entering the posterior aspect of the IVC. Brisk bleeding from this area after traction strongly suggests an IVC injury at the adrenal vein ostium.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Tumors (2019). Recommends careful dissection and early control of the adrenal vein to prevent hemorrhage.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Portal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Phrenic vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right renal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Superior mesenteric vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Inferior vena cava | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) It drains directly via a very short vessel. If the sutures are not carefully tied then it may be avu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
