  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The omentum's lifeline is the gastroepiploic, a key cut in gastrectomy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Gastroepiploic artery. The greater omentum, a key structure often removed during radical gastrectomy for gastric carcinoma, receives its primary blood supply from the gastroepiploic arteries. Understanding this vascular anatomy is crucial for safe surgical dissection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe greater omentum is predominantly vascularized by the right and left gastroepiploic arteries, which run along the greater curvature of the stomach within the omental layers. The right gastroepiploic artery originates from the gastroduodenal artery (a branch of the common hepatic artery), while the left gastroepiploic artery arises from the splenic artery. Both the common hepatic and splenic arteries are terminal branches of the celiac trunk. This rich anastomotic arcade ensures robust blood flow to the omentum and necessitates their ligation during omentectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The ileocolic artery is a branch of the superior mesenteric artery, supplying the terminal ileum, cecum, and ascending colon, not the omentum.\nOption B (Incorrect): The superior mesenteric artery is a major vessel supplying midgut derivatives (small intestine, ascending colon, and proximal transverse colon) but does not directly vascularize the omentum.\nOption D (Incorrect): The middle colic artery is a branch of the superior mesenteric artery, primarily supplying the transverse colon, and is not involved in omental blood supply.\nOption E (Incorrect): The inferior mesenteric artery supplies hindgut derivatives (distal transverse colon, descending colon, sigmoid colon, and superior rectum) and has no anatomical connection to the omentum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery | Origin | Primary Supply |\n|---|---|---|\n| Celiac Trunk | Abdominal Aorta | Foregut (stomach, liver, spleen, pancreas, duodenum proximal to major papilla) |\n| Superior Mesenteric Artery | Abdominal Aorta | Midgut (duodenum distal to major papilla, jejunum, ileum, ascending colon, proximal 2/3 transverse colon) |\n| Inferior Mesenteric Artery | Abdominal Aorta | Hindgut (distal 1/3 transverse colon, descending colon, sigmoid colon, superior rectum) |\n| Gastroepiploic Arteries | Gastroduodenal (right) & Splenic (left) | Greater curvature of stomach, Greater Omentum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Omental blood supply = gastroepiploic arteries, direct branches from celiac trunk system.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the greater omentum appears as a fatty apron. The right and left gastroepiploic arteries are clearly visible running along the greater curvature of the stomach within the omental layers. During gastrectomy, these vessels are meticulously identified, ligated, and divided to facilitate the removal of the omentum and stomach.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., Version 2.2023) recommend D2 lymphadenectomy for resectable gastric cancer, which includes a complete omentectomy as part of the standard surgical procedure to ensure adequate oncologic clearance.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ileocolic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Superior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gastroepiploic artery | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Middle colic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Inferior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The vessels supplying the omentum are the omental branches of the right and left gastro-epiploic art** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
