  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When you see oxyphil, think parathyroid, not thyroid!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Parathyroid gland. Oxyphil cells are a characteristic histological feature of the parathyroid glands, though their exact function is not fully understood. Identifying them at the periphery of a resected specimen helps confirm the presence of parathyroid tissue.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOxyphil cells are larger than chief cells, which are the primary functional cells of the parathyroid gland responsible for PTH secretion. They are characterized by abundant eosinophilic, granular cytoplasm due to numerous mitochondria. While their exact physiological role remains unclear, they are thought to be inactive or senescent chief cells, increasing in number with age. Their presence is a definitive marker for parathyroid tissue, crucial for pathologists to identify parathyroid glands, especially in cases of hyperplasia or adenoma or to confirm parathyroid tissue in a resected specimen.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The thymus is primarily composed of lymphocytes and epithelial reticular cells, not oxyphil cells.\nOption B (Incorrect): The thyroid gland contains follicular cells (producing thyroid hormones) and parafollicular C cells (producing calcitonin), neither of which are oxyphil cells.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lymph nodes are immune organs composed mainly of lymphocytes, macrophages, and dendritic cells, distinct from oxyphil cells.\nOption E (Incorrect): The adrenal gland consists of a cortex (producing steroid hormones) and a medulla (producing catecholamines), with cell types entirely different from oxyphil cells.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cell Type | Gland | Primary Function | Key Histological Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Chief Cells | Parathyroid | PTH secretion | Small, polygonal, clear cytoplasm |\n| Oxyphil Cells | Parathyroid | Unknown (possibly inactive chief cells) | Larger, abundant eosinophilic granular cytoplasm |\n| Follicular Cells | Thyroid | Thyroid hormone synthesis | Cuboidal, surround colloid-filled follicles |\n| Parafollicular (C) Cells | Thyroid | Calcitonin secretion | Pale-staining, located between follicles |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Oxyphil cells confirm parathyroid tissue, often seen with age.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, parathyroid glands are typically tan-yellow to reddish-brown, often ovoid, and can be identified by their location near the thyroid poles. Histologically, the presence of oxyphil cells confirms the tissue as parathyroid, which is critical during parathyroidectomy to ensure complete removal of diseased tissue while preserving normal glands.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Definitive Management of Primary Hyperparathyroidism (2016). Recommends surgical parathyroidectomy as the definitive treatment for symptomatic primary hyperparathyroidism, emphasizing accurate localization and histological confirmation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thymus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thyroid gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Parathyroid gland | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Lymph node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Adrenal gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Oxyphil cells are typically found in parathyroid glands** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
