  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Numb earlobe? Blame the greater auricular, not the facial!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, the greater auricular nerve. This nerve is frequently encountered and susceptible to injury during superficial parotidectomy, leading to sensory deficits in the earlobe and preauricular region. While the facial nerve is the primary concern, the greater auricular nerve is statistically more commonly injured.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe greater auricular nerve, a branch of the cervical plexus (C2, C3), ascends superficially over the sternocleidomastoid muscle and then curves anteriorly to supply sensation to the skin over the parotid gland, mastoid process, and the lower part of the auricle. Its superficial course and proximity to the surgical incision and dissection planes during a superficial parotidectomy make it highly vulnerable to transection or traction injury. Surgeons routinely counsel patients about potential numbness in this distribution post-operatively, acknowledging its common involvement. In contrast, meticulous dissection and identification of the facial nerve trunk and its branches are paramount in superficial parotidectomy, making its injury less common when performed by experienced surgeons.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Facial nerve injury is the most feared complication of parotidectomy due to its motor function, but with careful technique in a *superficial* parotidectomy, it is less commonly injured than the greater auricular nerve.\nOption C (Incorrect): The greater occipital nerve supplies sensation to the posterior scalp and is located far from the surgical field of a parotidectomy.\nOption D (Incorrect): The accessory nerve (CN XI) innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles and is primarily at risk during neck dissections, not typically during a superficial parotidectomy.\nOption E (Incorrect): The ophthalmic branch of the trigeminal nerve (CN V1) supplies sensation to the forehead, upper eyelid, and cornea, and is anatomically distant from the parotid gland.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Type | Common Injury in Parotidectomy | Clinical Consequence |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Greater Auricular | Sensory (C2, C3) | Most common (superficial parotidectomy) | Numbness/dysesthesia of earlobe, preauricular skin |\n| Facial (CN VII) | Motor | Less common (superficial parotidectomy) | Facial paralysis (eyelid lag, mouth droop) |\n| Marginal Mandibular | Motor (branch of CN VII) | At risk during inferior dissection | Lower lip weakness/droop |\n| Accessory (CN XI) | Motor | Not typically in superficial parotidectomy | Shoulder weakness, trapezius dysfunction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Greater auricular nerve injury is the most common sensory deficit after superficial parotidectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the greater auricular nerve is often seen crossing the sternocleidomastoid muscle, superficial to the parotid gland capsule, making it susceptible to injury during skin flap elevation or dissection around the inferior pole of the gland. The facial nerve, conversely, emerges from the stylomastoid foramen and is meticulously identified and preserved, often using nerve monitoring.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery Foundation (AAO-HNSF) Clinical Practice Guideline: Salivary Gland Neoplasms (2016). This guideline emphasizes careful surgical technique and patient counseling regarding potential nerve injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Greater auricular | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Facial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Greater occipital | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Accessory | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Opthalmic branch of the trigeminal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The greater auricular nerve and in particular its lobular branch is commonly injured in parotid surg** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
