  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spongy urethra's lymph goes deep, like a secret in the groin.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Deep inguinal nodes. This is because the lymphatic drainage of the spongy urethra, along with the glans penis, follows a pathway to the deep inguinal lymph nodes, reflecting its distal anatomical location.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lymphatic drainage of the male urethra is anatomically segmented, a critical concept for staging urethral cancers. The distal portion, specifically the spongy (penile) urethra and the glans penis, drains primarily to the superficial inguinal nodes and subsequently to the deep inguinal nodes. This superficial-to-deep progression is a common pattern for structures in the external genitalia, distinguishing it from the more internal drainage of the proximal urethra.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): External iliac nodes drain structures like the bladder, prostate, and seminal vesicles, not the spongy urethra.\nOption B (Incorrect): Internal iliac nodes drain the more proximal parts of the urethra, specifically the prostatic and membranous urethra, as well as the bladder, rectum, and prostate, but not the spongy urethra.\nOption C (Incorrect): Para aortic nodes drain organs like the testes, ovaries, and kidneys, which are much higher and distinct from urethral drainage.\nOption E (Incorrect): Meso rectal nodes are involved in the lymphatic drainage of the rectum, which is unrelated to the urethra.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Urethral Segment | Lymphatic Drainage |\n| :--------------- | :----------------- |\n| Spongy Urethra   | Deep Inguinal Nodes |\n| Glans Penis      | Deep Inguinal Nodes |\n| Prostatic Urethra | Internal Iliac Nodes |\n| Membranous Urethra | Internal Iliac Nodes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Spongy urethra and glans drain to deep inguinal nodes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), enlarged deep inguinal lymph nodes in a patient with spongy urethral pathology would raise suspicion for metastatic disease. Intraoperatively, a sentinel lymph node biopsy may be performed to assess these nodes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Association of Urology (EAU) Guidelines on Penile Cancer (2023) recommend evaluation of inguinal lymph nodes for staging of distal urethral and penile cancers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | External iliac nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Internal iliac nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Para aortic nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Deep inguinal nodes | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Meso rectal nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The lymphatic drainage of the spongy urethra and the glans penis is to the deep inguinal nodes. The ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
