  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sunshine vitamin keeps bones strong, or they'll bend!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Vitamin D. Deficiency of Vitamin D is the primary cause of Rickets in children, as it is essential for proper calcium and phosphate absorption and subsequent bone mineralization.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVitamin D plays a critical role in maintaining calcium and phosphate homeostasis. It promotes the absorption of these minerals from the gut and regulates their levels in the blood, which are vital for the mineralization of the growing bone matrix. Without adequate Vitamin D, the cartilage at the growth plates fails to mineralize properly, leading to soft, weak bones that can bend and deform under weight-bearing stress, characteristic of Rickets.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Vitamin C) (Incorrect): Deficiency of Vitamin C causes Scurvy, characterized by impaired collagen synthesis, leading to bleeding gums, skin hemorrhages, and poor wound healing, not Rickets.\nOption B (Vitamin B3) (Incorrect): Deficiency of Vitamin B3 (Niacin) causes Pellagra, presenting with dermatitis, diarrhea, dementia, and eventually death.\nOption D (Vitamin A) (Incorrect): Deficiency of Vitamin A primarily affects vision (night blindness, xerophthalmia) and immune function, not bone mineralization in the manner of Rickets.\nOption E (Vitamin E) (Incorrect): Deficiency of Vitamin E is rare but can lead to neurological symptoms (ataxia, peripheral neuropathy) and hemolytic anemia, not Rickets.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Vitamin | Deficiency Disease | Key Symptoms |\n|---|---|---|\n| Vitamin D | Rickets (children), Osteomalacia (adults) | Bone deformities, muscle weakness, bone pain |\n| Vitamin C | Scurvy | Bleeding gums, petechiae, poor wound healing, joint pain |\n| Vitamin B3 (Niacin) | Pellagra | Dermatitis, Diarrhea, Dementia ('3 Ds') |\n| Vitamin A | Xerophthalmia, Night Blindness | Impaired vision, dry eyes, weakened immunity |\n| Vitamin E | Neurological dysfunction | Ataxia, peripheral neuropathy, hemolytic anemia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rickets = Vitamin D deficiency, leading to soft, deformed bones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-rays, Rickets typically presents with widened, irregular, and frayed growth plates (epiphyses), cupping of the metaphyses, and bowing of long bones, particularly in weight-bearing areas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) 2014 Clinical Report: recommends 400 IU of Vitamin D daily for all infants and children.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Vitamin C | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Vitamin B3 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Vitamin D | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Vitamin A | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Vitamin E | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Vitamin D is needed to help mineralise bone. When this is deficient, mineralisation is inadequate an** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
