  "answer": "C) Construction of a stoma may be complicated by several factors. Necrosis may occur because of technical errors in mesenteric division, excessive tension or failure to construct a fascial defect of adequate size to permit safe passage of the mesentery and the bowel.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A dusky stoma is a surgical emergency, not just a bad tan.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Necrosis. Stoma necrosis is the earliest and most critical complication because it directly results from immediate technical errors during construction, compromising the blood supply to the stoma. This can manifest within hours to days post-operatively.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStoma necrosis occurs due to ischemia, a direct consequence of compromised blood flow to the bowel segment forming the stoma. This compromise can stem from several intraoperative technical errors: inadequate mesenteric division leading to insufficient blood supply, excessive tension on the mesentery or bowel, or a fascial defect that is too small, constricting the mesentery and its vessels. These issues immediately impair the viability of the stoma, making it the earliest complication to present and requiring urgent attention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Prolapse) (Incorrect): Stoma prolapse typically occurs later, weeks to months after surgery, due to inadequate fixation of the bowel or a fascial opening that is too wide.\nOption B (Retraction) (Incorrect): Stoma retraction can occur early, often due to excessive tension on the bowel, inadequate length, or significant weight gain, but necrosis due to immediate vascular compromise is generally considered earlier and more acute.\nOption D (Parastomal hernia) (Incorrect): A parastomal hernia is a late complication, developing months to years post-operatively, caused by a weakness in the abdominal wall around the stoma.\nOption E (Dermatitis) (Incorrect): Peristomal dermatitis is a common complication that can occur at any time post-operatively, but it is related to effluent leakage and skin irritation, not an immediate surgical technical error affecting stoma viability.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Timing | Primary Cause |\n|---|---|---|\n| Necrosis | Earliest (hours-days) | Ischemia (technical errors: mesenteric division, tension, small fascial defect) |\n| Retraction | Early-Intermediate (days-weeks) | Excessive tension, inadequate bowel length, obesity |\n| Prolapse | Intermediate-Late (weeks-months) | Inadequate fixation, wide fascial opening |\n| Parastomal Hernia | Late (months-years) | Weakness in abdominal wall, large fascial defect |\n| Dermatitis | Any time | Effluent leakage, skin irritation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always prioritize stoma viability; necrosis is an immediate surgical emergency.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, stoma viability is assessed by observing the color (pink/red is good, dusky/black is bad), bleeding from the cut edge, and presence of peristalsis. If necrosis is suspected, a 'finger test' into the stoma can assess the color of the deeper mucosa. Fluorescein dye can also be used to assess perfusion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Ostomy Surgery (2020) recommends careful attention to blood supply and tension during stoma creation to prevent complications like necrosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Prolapse | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Retraction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Necrosis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Parastomal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Dermatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Construction of a stoma may be complicated by several factors. Necrosis may occur because of technic** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
