  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When eyes bleed and cerebellum grows, think VHL, the vascular show!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome (VHL) because the combination of bilateral vitreous hemorrhage, indicative of retinal hemangioblastomas, and cerebellar lesions strongly points to this inherited disorder. VHL is characterized by the development of highly vascular tumors in multiple organs, including the retina and cerebellum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVon Hippel-Lindau syndrome is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by a mutation in the VHL tumor suppressor gene on chromosome 3p25-26. This gene is crucial for regulating hypoxia-inducible factor (HIF) pathways. Its inactivation leads to the uncontrolled growth of highly vascularized tumors, known as hemangioblastomas. In the retina, these hemangioblastomas can bleed, causing vitreous hemorrhage, and are often bilateral. In the cerebellum, hemangioblastomas are the most common primary posterior fossa tumor in VHL patients, presenting as cystic lesions with a mural nodule, and are a hallmark of the disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Neurofibromatosis type I (NF1) is characterized by café-au-lait spots, neurofibromas, Lisch nodules, and optic pathway gliomas, not typically retinal hemangioblastomas or cerebellar hemangioblastomas.\nOption B (Incorrect): Neurofibromatosis type II (NF2) is primarily associated with bilateral vestibular schwannomas, meningiomas, and ependymomas, not retinal hemangioblastomas or cerebellar hemangioblastomas.\nOption C (Incorrect): Tuberous sclerosis (TSC) presents with cortical tubers, subependymal giant cell astrocytomas, renal angiomyolipomas, and retinal astrocytic hamartomas (not hemangiomas), which are distinct from the vascular lesions seen in VHL.\nOption E (Incorrect): Sarcoidosis is a systemic granulomatous disease that can affect various organs, including the brain and eyes, but it does not typically cause bilateral vitreous hemorrhage from hemangiomas or specific cerebellar hemangioblastomas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Key Ocular Manifestations | Key CNS Manifestations | Genetic Basis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Von Hippel-Lindau | Retinal hemangioblastomas (often bilateral, leading to hemorrhage) | Cerebellar hemangioblastomas, spinal hemangioblastomas, endolymphatic sac tumors | VHL gene (Chr 3) |\n| Neurofibromatosis Type 1 | Lisch nodules (iris hamartomas), optic pathway gliomas | Optic pathway gliomas, neurofibromas, brainstem gliomas | NF1 gene (Chr 17) |\n| Neurofibromatosis Type 2 | Posterior subcapsular cataracts, retinal hamartomas | Bilateral vestibular schwannomas, meningiomas, ependymomas | NF2 gene (Chr 22) |\n| Tuberous Sclerosis | Retinal astrocytic hamartomas | Cortical tubers, subependymal giant cell astrocytomas (SEGA) | TSC1/TSC2 genes (Chr 9/16) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilateral vitreous hemorrhage + cerebellar lesions = VHL until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, cerebellar hemangioblastomas in VHL typically appear as a cystic lesion with a brightly enhancing mural nodule. Retinal hemangioblastomas are seen on ophthalmoscopy as elevated, reddish-orange lesions with dilated, tortuous feeding and draining vessels.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Von Hippel-Lindau Disease (2023) recommends surveillance for VHL-associated tumors, including annual ophthalmologic exams and regular CNS imaging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Neurofibromatosis type I | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Neurofibromatosis type II | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tuberous sclerosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Sarcoidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Retinal and cerebellar haemangiomas are key features of Von Hippel- Lindau syndrome. Retinal haemang** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
