  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's greasy, stuck-on, and full of plugs, think SK!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Seborrhoeic keratosis. The clinical presentation of a 70-year-old lady with multiple raised, greasy lesions with scattered keratin plugs on her trunk is pathognomonic for seborrhoeic keratosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSeborrhoeic keratoses are common benign epidermal tumors, particularly prevalent in older individuals. They are characterized by their 'stuck-on' appearance, often described as looking like a 'dab of warm wax' on the skin. Histologically, they are composed of proliferating basaloid cells and often contain horn cysts (keratin plugs) and pseudocysts, which clinically manifest as the scattered keratin plugs mentioned. The greasy surface is due to hyperkeratosis and acanthosis. They typically occur on the trunk, face, and extremities, and their diagnosis is primarily clinical.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Keratoacanthoma) (Incorrect): Keratoacanthomas are rapidly growing, dome-shaped nodules with a central keratin-filled crater, often resolving spontaneously. They do not typically present as multiple greasy lesions with scattered keratin plugs on the surface.\nOption B (Pilar cysts) (Incorrect): Pilar cysts (or trichilemmal cysts) are smooth, firm, subcutaneous nodules, most commonly found on the scalp. They are not characterized by a greasy surface or superficial keratin plugs.\nOption C (Dermatofibroma) (Incorrect): Dermatofibromas are firm, reddish-brown papules or nodules, often with a 'dimple sign' when squeezed. They are typically found on the extremities and do not have a greasy surface or keratin plugs.\nOption E (Epidermoid cyst) (Incorrect): Epidermoid cysts are subcutaneous, mobile nodules often with a central punctum, containing cheesy, malodorous keratin. They are not typically described as having a greasy surface with scattered keratin plugs on the surface.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Seborrhoeic Keratosis                               | Keratoacanthoma                                   | Basal Cell Carcinoma (Nodular)                    |\n|---------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| **Appearance**      | 'Stuck-on', greasy, waxy, raised, keratin plugs     | Dome-shaped, central keratin crater, rapid growth | Pearly papule/nodule, rolled border, telangiectasias |\n| **Location**        | Trunk, face, extremities (common in elderly)        | Sun-exposed areas (face, hands)                   | Sun-exposed areas (face, neck, hands)             |\n| **Nature**          | Benign epidermal tumor                              | Benign, but can be aggressive; often spontaneous regression | Malignant, locally invasive                       |\n| **Key Differentiating Feature** | Greasy surface, keratin pseudocysts, 'stuck-on' | Rapid growth, central crater                      | Pearly translucency, telangiectasias, rolled border |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Greasy, 'stuck-on' lesions with keratin plugs in an elderly patient = Seborrhoeic keratosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nSeborrhoeic keratosis is a clinical diagnosis. Dermoscopy can reveal characteristic features like milia-like cysts (keratin pseudocysts) and comedo-like openings. Intraoperatively, these lesions are typically excised for cosmetic reasons or if symptomatic (e.g., irritation, bleeding), or biopsied if there is diagnostic uncertainty.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) Guidelines for the Management of Seborrheic Keratoses (though specific guidelines for management are less common than for malignant lesions, AAD provides patient information and general guidance on diagnosis and treatment options like cryotherapy or shave excision).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Keratoacanthoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pilar cysts | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dermatofibroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Seborrhoeic keratosis | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Epidermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Seborrhoeic keratosis may have a number of appearances. However,\nthe scaly, thick, greasy surface wi** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
