  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Potassium follows the cell; severe malnutrition depletes it.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Severe malnutrition, because it typically does not cause hyperkalemia; in fact, it often leads to hypokalemia, especially during refeeding. Understanding the mechanisms of potassium balance is crucial for managing critically ill patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHyperkalemia arises from increased potassium intake, decreased renal excretion, or a shift of potassium from the intracellular to the extracellular compartment. Conditions like haemolysis and severe burns cause massive cell destruction, releasing abundant intracellular potassium into the bloodstream. Type 4 renal tubular acidosis impairs the kidney's ability to excrete potassium due to aldosterone deficiency or resistance. Conversely, severe malnutrition often results in overall electrolyte depletion, and during refeeding syndrome, intracellular shifts of potassium, phosphate, and magnesium can paradoxically lead to hypokalemia, not hyperkalemia.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Haemolysis causes hyperkalemia by releasing large amounts of intracellular potassium into the extracellular fluid.\nOption B (Incorrect): Severe burns lead to extensive tissue damage and cell lysis, resulting in the release of intracellular potassium and subsequent hyperkalemia.\nOption C (Incorrect): Familial periodic paralysis includes a hyperkalemic form (hyperkalemic periodic paralysis) where potassium shifts out of cells, causing transient hyperkalemia.\nOption D (Incorrect): Type 4 renal tubular acidosis is characterized by impaired renal potassium excretion, often due to hypoaldosteronism, leading to hyperkalemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Hyperkalemia | Mechanism |\n|---|---|\n| Haemolysis | Intracellular K+ release from lysed cells |\n| Severe Burns | Massive tissue destruction and cell lysis |\n| Type 4 RTA | Impaired renal K+ excretion due to aldosterone issues |\n| **Cause of Hypokalemia** | **Mechanism** |\n| Severe Malnutrition/Refeeding | Intracellular K+ shift during anabolism |\n| Diuretics (loop/thiazide) | Increased renal K+ excretion |\n| Vomiting/Diarrhea | Gastrointestinal K+ loss |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Potassium follows the cell; understand shifts and excretion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable for this question, as it pertains to electrolyte physiology rather than imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo single overarching guideline directly addresses all causes of hyperkalemia comprehensively, but various society guidelines (e.g., AHA/ACC for cardiac, ASN for renal) touch upon aspects of potassium management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Haemolysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Burns | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Familial periodic paralysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Type 4 renal tubular acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Severe malnutrition | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Familial periodic paralysis has subtypes associated with hyper and\nhypokalaemia.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
