  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Biceps femoris: the posterolateral hamstring that loves to tear in rugby.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, the long head of the biceps femoris. This muscle is located on the posterolateral aspect of the thigh, precisely where the patient experienced severe pain during a rugby injury, which commonly involves sudden acceleration or deceleration, leading to hamstring strains.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHamstring injuries are common in sports requiring sprinting, jumping, and sudden changes in direction, like rugby. The biceps femoris, particularly its long head, is the most frequently injured hamstring muscle, accounting for over 80% of hamstring strains. Its posterolateral location directly correlates with the patient's described pain. The hamstrings (biceps femoris, semitendinosus, semimembranosus) originate from the ischial tuberosity and cross both the hip and knee joints, making them susceptible to injury during eccentric contractions, such as the terminal swing phase of running.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Semimembranosus) (Incorrect): This muscle is located on the posteromedial aspect of the thigh, not posterolateral.\nOption B (Semitendinosus) (Incorrect): This muscle is also located on the posteromedial aspect of the thigh, not posterolateral.\nOption D (Gastrocnemius) (Incorrect): The gastrocnemius is a calf muscle located in the posterior lower leg, not the thigh. While it can be injured, the pain location described points to the thigh.\nOption E (Soleus) (Incorrect): The soleus is a calf muscle located deep to the gastrocnemius in the posterior lower leg, not the thigh.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Muscle Group | Location | Primary Action | Innervation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Biceps Femoris (Long Head) | Posterolateral thigh | Hip extension, knee flexion, external rotation of flexed knee | Sciatic nerve (tibial division) |\n| Semitendinosus | Posteromedial thigh | Hip extension, knee flexion, internal rotation of flexed knee | Sciatic nerve (tibial division) |\n| Semimembranosus | Posteromedial thigh (deep to semitendinosus) | Hip extension, knee flexion, internal rotation of flexed knee | Sciatic nerve (tibial division) |\n| Gastrocnemius | Posterior lower leg (superficial) | Plantarflexion, knee flexion | Tibial nerve |\n| Soleus | Posterior lower leg (deep) | Plantarflexion | Tibial nerve |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Posterolateral thigh pain in athletes = think biceps femoris.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMRI is the gold standard for diagnosing hamstring injuries, showing edema, fiber disruption, or complete avulsion at the musculotendinous junction or origin. Intraoperatively, a tear or avulsion of the biceps femoris tendon from the ischial tuberosity or within the muscle belly would be visible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Hamstring Injuries (e.g., 2010s-2020s). It recommends MRI for definitive diagnosis and grading of hamstring injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Semimembranosus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Semitendinosus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Long head of biceps femoris | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Gastrocnemius | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Soleus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The biceps femoris is the laterally located hamstring muscle. The\nsemitendinosus and semimembranosus** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
