  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bankart: The anterior labral tear that keeps coming back for more!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Bankart lesion. This is the most common underlying anatomical abnormality responsible for recurrent anterior shoulder dislocations, particularly in young, active individuals like a rugby player.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA Bankart lesion is an injury to the anterior-inferior glenoid labrum, often occurring during an initial anterior shoulder dislocation. This avulsion creates a defect or 'pocket' at the front of the glenoid, compromising the static stability of the glenohumeral joint. The humeral head can then repeatedly dislocate into this defect, leading to chronic and recurrent instability. Surgical repair of the Bankart lesion aims to restore the labral-ligamentous complex to the glenoid, thereby re-establishing stability.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Rotator cuff tears are more common in older patients and typically cause pain and weakness, not recurrent dislocations in a young athlete.\nOption B (Incorrect): Biceps tendon rupture is usually a traumatic event or degenerative process, and while it can cause pain, it is not the primary cause of recurrent shoulder instability.\nOption D (Incorrect): Axillary nerve injury is a common complication of shoulder dislocation, but it is a neurological deficit resulting from the dislocation, not the structural abnormality causing the recurrence itself.\nOption E (Incorrect): Infraspinatus tendinitis is an inflammatory condition of a rotator cuff tendon, causing pain but not structural instability leading to recurrent dislocations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lesion | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bankart Lesion** | Avulsion of anterior-inferior glenoid labrum (often with bone) | Most common cause of recurrent anterior shoulder dislocation, especially in young athletes |\n| **Hill-Sachs Lesion** | Compression fracture on posterior-superior humeral head | Consequence of anterior dislocation, can contribute to recurrence by engaging the glenoid rim |\n| **SLAP Lesion** | Superior Labrum Anterior to Posterior tear | Pain, clicking, instability (less common for recurrent dislocation than Bankart) |\n| **Rotator Cuff Tear** | Tear in one or more rotator cuff tendons | Pain, weakness, limited range of motion; rarely primary cause of recurrent dislocation in young patients |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Recurrent anterior shoulder dislocation in young athletes = Bankart lesion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a Bankart lesion appears as a detachment or avulsion of the anterior-inferior labrum from the glenoid rim, often with associated edema or fluid. A bony Bankart will show a fracture fragment on CT. Arthroscopically, the detached labrum is clearly visible, often with fraying or a complete avulsion, creating a 'peeled off' appearance from the glenoid, which is then reattached.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Glenohumeral Instability (2019). Recommends surgical stabilization for young, active patients with recurrent anterior instability to reduce recurrence rates.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rotator cuff tear | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Biceps tendon rupture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bankart lesion | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Axillary nerve injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Infraspinatus tendinitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) A Bankart lesion is an injury of the anterior (inferior) glenoid labrum of\nthe shoulder due to anter** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
