  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When swallowing fails, PEG prevails for long-term feeding success.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is PEG tube feeding. For a patient recovering from a CVA with persistent aspiration and inability to feed safely, a Percutaneous Endoscopic Gastrostomy (PEG) tube is the preferred long-term solution for nutritional support.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA PEG tube provides a direct route for nutrition into the stomach, bypassing the compromised swallowing mechanism. It is placed endoscopically, which is less invasive than surgical options like a feeding jejunostomy, making it suitable for an elderly patient recovering from a CVA. While associated with some morbidity, it offers a more comfortable and reliable long-term feeding solution compared to nasogastric tubes, and avoids the significant risks and costs of total parenteral nutrition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Feeding jejunostomy) (Incorrect): This requires a general anesthetic and a surgical procedure, which is more invasive and carries higher risks for an elderly patient recovering from a CVA compared to an endoscopic PEG placement.\nOption C (Total parenteral nutrition) (Incorrect): TPN is reserved for patients with non-functional gastrointestinal tracts or severe malabsorption. It is associated with higher risks of infection, metabolic complications, and cost, and is not indicated when the GI tract is functional.\nOption D (Long term naso gastric tube feeding) (Incorrect): Nasogastric tubes are generally for short-term use (typically <4-6 weeks). Long-term use is associated with discomfort, increased risk of dislodgement, sinusitis, skin breakdown, and persistent aspiration risk.\nOption E (Withhold feeding and palliate) (Incorrect): While palliation is an option in some end-of-life scenarios, the question implies ongoing rehabilitation and a need for long-term feeding, not immediate withdrawal of care. The goal is to provide safe and adequate nutrition.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feeding Method | Duration | Invasiveness | Key Considerations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nasogastric Tube (NGT) | Short-term (<4-6 weeks) | Non-invasive | Discomfort, dislodgement, aspiration risk |\n| Percutaneous Endoscopic Gastrostomy (PEG) | Long-term (>4-6 weeks) | Minimally invasive (endoscopic) | Preferred for dysphagia, lower aspiration risk than NGT |\n| Feeding Jejunostomy | Long-term | Surgical | Reserved for gastric outlet obstruction or high aspiration risk with PEG |\n| Total Parenteral Nutrition (TPN) | Long-term | Intravenous | Used when GI tract non-functional, high cost, infection risk |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For long-term enteral feeding in dysphagia, PEG is the gold standard.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring PEG placement, an endoscope visualizes the stomach wall, and a light source transilluminates the abdominal wall to guide needle puncture. A guidewire is then passed, and the PEG tube is pulled through the abdominal wall into the stomach. On plain film or fluoroscopy, the PEG tube's tip should be coiled within the stomach, and the external bumper should be flush with the skin.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition (ASPEN) Clinical Guidelines for Nutrition Support in Adult Patients (2016) recommends enteral nutrition as the preferred route for nutrition support in patients with a functional GI tract.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | PEG tube feeding | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Feeding jejunostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Total parenteral nutrition | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Long term naso gastric tube feeding | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Withold feeding and palliate | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A PEG tube is the best long term option although they are associated with a significant degree of mo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
