  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the critically ill like a slow-cooked meal, not a microwave dinner.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is correct because severely ill patients require a cautious approach to nutritional support, often starting with less than 50% of energy needs in the initial 24-48 hours. This strategy, known as permissive underfeeding, is crucial to prevent metabolic complications and refeeding syndrome.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe rationale behind permissive underfeeding in critically ill patients is to avoid overfeeding, which can lead to hyperglycemia, increased CO2 production, fluid overload, and hepatic steatosis. Starting with a lower caloric intake allows the body to gradually adapt to exogenous nutrition, minimizing metabolic stress and the risk of refeeding syndrome, especially in those with pre-existing malnutrition. This approach prioritizes patient safety and metabolic stability over immediate full caloric replacement, ensuring a smoother metabolic transition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 35 kcal/kg/day is a standard target for nutritional support, but it is far too high for initial refeeding in patients at risk of refeeding syndrome. These patients require a very gradual increase, starting at 10-20 kcal/kg/day or even lower, with close electrolyte monitoring.\nOption C (Incorrect): Providing full energy needs (100%) in the first 24-48 hours to severely ill patients is dangerous and can precipitate refeeding syndrome, hyperglycemia, and other metabolic complications. The \"start low, go slow\" principle is paramount.\nOption D (Incorrect): Diuretics, particularly loop diuretics, can increase urinary excretion of thiamine, thereby increasing the risk of thiamine deficiency and the need for supplementation, not decreasing it.\nOption E (Incorrect): Chemotherapy can induce nausea, vomiting, mucositis, and anorexia, leading to poor oral intake and increased metabolic demand. This often increases the risk of thiamine deficiency, making supplementation potentially necessary, not unlikely.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Group | Initial Energy Target (first 24-48h) | Refeeding Syndrome Risk | Key Considerations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Severely Ill/Critically Ill | < 50% of estimated needs (e.g., 10-20 kcal/kg/day) | Moderate to High | Permissive underfeeding, monitor electrolytes, glucose, fluid balance |\n| High Refeeding Risk | 10-20 kcal/kg/day (max 50% of needs) | Very High | Start very low, slow advancement, aggressive electrolyte repletion (K, Phos, Mg), thiamine supplementation |\n| Stable, Moderately Malnourished | 50-70% of estimated needs | Low to Moderate | Gradual increase to full needs over several days |\n| Well-nourished, Elective Surgery | Full estimated needs (if indicated) | Low | Standard nutritional support protocols |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: In severe illness, start nutritional support low and slow to prevent refeeding syndrome.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable to this question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN (American Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition) Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016) recommends initiating nutrition support at 10-20 kcal/kg/day or 80% of target in the first week for critically ill patients. ESPEN (European Society for Clinical Nutrition and Metabolism) Guidelines on Clinical Nutrition in the Intensive Care Unit (2019) also supports a gradual increase in caloric intake.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | For severely ill patients aim to give < 50% energy needs in the first 24-48 | ✅ Correct |\n| B | For patients at risk of refeeding syndrome, they should be given 35 kcal/kg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | For severely ill patients aim to give the full energy needs in the first 24 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Patients on diuretics are unlikely to need thiamine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Patients on chemotherapy are unlikely to need thiamine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
