  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bleeding spleen + colon cancer = PRBCs, not cell saver!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Infusion of packed red cells. In a patient with profuse bleeding from an iatrogenic splenic injury, the immediate priority is to restore oxygen-carrying capacity to prevent hemorrhagic shock and end-organ damage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute, profuse bleeding primarily leads to a loss of red blood cells, which are critical for oxygen transport. Packed red blood cells (PRBCs) directly address this deficit by providing hemoglobin, thereby improving tissue oxygenation and mitigating the effects of hypovolemic shock. While other components may be needed later, PRBCs are the most appropriate initial intervention for life-threatening hemorrhage to maintain hemodynamic stability and organ perfusion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Infusion of human prothrombin complex is indicated for reversal of anticoagulant effects or specific factor deficiencies, not for acute blood loss where the primary need is oxygen-carrying capacity.\nOption C (Incorrect): Infusion of blood from the cell saver salvaged during surgery is contraindicated in this scenario. The presence of colon cancer and potential fecal contamination from open bowel makes reinfusion of salvaged blood unsafe due to the risk of disseminating malignant cells and infection.\nOption D (Incorrect): Infusion of factor VIII concentrate is used to treat Hemophilia A or acquired factor VIII deficiency, not for general acute blood loss from trauma.\nOption E (Incorrect): Infusion of gelofusine (a colloid) is a plasma expander used to increase intravascular volume, but it does not provide oxygen-carrying capacity, which is the critical need in profuse hemorrhage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Blood Product/Fluid | Primary Indication | Key Benefit |\n|--------------------|--------------------|-------------|\n| Packed Red Blood Cells | Acute hemorrhage, symptomatic anemia | Restores oxygen-carrying capacity |\n| Fresh Frozen Plasma | Coagulopathy, massive transfusion protocol | Replaces clotting factors |\n| Platelets | Thrombocytopenia, platelet dysfunction | Improves hemostasis |\n| Crystalloids/Colloids | Volume expansion, resuscitation | Increases intravascular volume |\n| Prothrombin Complex Concentrate | Reversal of anticoagulation, specific factor deficiencies | Provides concentrated clotting factors |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For acute surgical hemorrhage, prioritize oxygen-carrying capacity with PRBCs, and avoid contaminated cell saver blood.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a splenic injury would present as active, often brisk, bleeding from the splenic capsule or parenchyma, typically a dark red, continuous ooze or pulsatile flow, requiring immediate control.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe European Guidelines on Management of Major Bleeding and Coagulopathy Following Trauma (2019) recommend early and aggressive transfusion of red blood cells in patients with ongoing hemorrhage to maintain hemodynamic stability and prevent shock.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Infusion of human prothrombin complex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Infusion of packed red cells | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Infusion of blood from the cell saver salvaged during surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Infusion of factor VIII concentrate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Infusion of gelofusine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The cell saver is inappropriate because the cells will be contaminated with malignant cells and faec** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
