  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 90% carotid stenosis? Cut it out, save the brain!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nLeft carotid endarterectomy is the most appropriate treatment option. A 90% stenosis of the internal carotid artery represents a very high risk for stroke, and surgical intervention via endarterectomy is the gold standard for significant, high-grade stenosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCarotid endarterectomy (CEA) involves surgically removing the atherosclerotic plaque from the internal carotid artery, directly restoring luminal patency and reducing the risk of embolic stroke. The internal carotid artery supplies a large portion of the cerebral hemisphere, and high-grade stenosis significantly impedes blood flow and, more importantly, serves as a nidus for thrombus formation and embolization. By removing the plaque, CEA improves cerebral perfusion and, crucially, eliminates the source of microemboli, which are the primary cause of stroke in carotid artery disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Right carotid endarterectomy. While 60% stenosis can be treated, the 90% left-sided stenosis carries a much higher immediate stroke risk and should be addressed first.\nOption C (Incorrect): Right carotid artery stenting. Stenting for 60% stenosis is less clearly beneficial than for higher grades, and the left side is more critical.\nOption D (Incorrect): Left carotid artery stenting. While stenting is an option for high-grade stenosis, CEA is generally preferred over CAS for primary treatment of high-grade ICA stenosis in patients without specific contraindications to CEA, due to a slightly higher periprocedural stroke risk with CAS in some studies and populations. The question doesn't provide reasons to favor CAS.\nOption E (Incorrect): No surgical/e. A 90% stenosis carries a very high stroke risk, making observation alone inappropriate.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stenosis Grade | Symptomatic Patient | Asymptomatic Patient | Preferred Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| <50% | Medical management | Medical management | Medical management |\n| 50-69% | CEA (if life expectancy >5 years) | Medical management (consider CEA if high-risk features) | CEA (symptomatic) |\n| 70-99% | CEA (strong recommendation) | CEA (strong recommendation, especially >80%) | CEA |\n| Total Occlusion | Medical management | Medical management | Medical management (no benefit from revascularization) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Treat the highest-grade, highest-risk carotid stenosis first, typically with CEA.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPre-operative imaging (Duplex ultrasound, CTA, or MRA) would show severe luminal narrowing and turbulent flow at the origin of the left internal carotid artery. Intraoperatively, after arteriotomy, a thick, friable, often calcified atherosclerotic plaque would be visible within the left internal carotid artery, significantly obstructing the lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Management of Extracranial Carotid Artery Disease (2017). These guidelines generally recommend carotid endarterectomy for symptomatic patients with 70-99% internal carotid artery stenosis and for select asymptomatic patients with 70-99% stenosis, especially those with an estimated perioperative stroke/death risk of <3%.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right carotid endarterectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Left carotid endarterectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right carotid artery stenting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Left carotid artery stenting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | No surgical/e | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
