  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't operate on asymptomatic octogenarians unless you have a really good reason.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, \"No surgical/endovascular intervention.\" This 85-year-old patient is asymptomatic, and despite a 90% left internal carotid artery stenosis, their advanced age generally contraindicates intervention due to increased perioperative risk outweighing long-term benefit for asymptomatic disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCarotid endarterectomy (CEA) is primarily indicated for symptomatic patients with >70% internal carotid artery (ICA) stenosis. For asymptomatic patients, CEA is considered for >60% stenosis, but the benefit significantly diminishes or is outweighed by risk in patients over 80 years old. The risk reduction from stroke (e.g., 12% to 6% over 5 years in some trials) in asymptomatic patients must be carefully weighed against surgical risk, which increases with age and comorbidities. Carotid artery stenting (CAS) is generally reserved for high-risk surgical patients or specific anatomical considerations and is still considered experimental in many contexts, especially for asymptomatic disease, due to higher stroke rates compared to CEA.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Right carotid endarterectomy is incorrect because the right ICA has only 40% stenosis, which is not considered significant enough for intervention, even if the patient were symptomatic.\nOption B (Incorrect): Left carotid endarterectomy is incorrect because, despite the 90% stenosis, the patient is asymptomatic and 85 years old. The perioperative risks of CEA in this age group for asymptomatic disease often outweigh the long-term stroke prevention benefits.\nOption C (Incorrect): Right carotid artery stenting is incorrect for the same reason as A (40% stenosis is not significant) and because stenting is generally not first-line for asymptomatic disease and has higher stroke rates than CEA.\nOption D (Incorrect): Left carotid artery stenting is incorrect because, similar to B, the patient's age and asymptomatic status make intervention generally inappropriate. Furthermore, CAS is not preferred over CEA for asymptomatic disease due to higher periprocedural stroke risk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Symptomatic Carotid Stenosis | Asymptomatic Carotid Stenosis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Definition | TIA, amaurosis fugax, stroke | No neurological symptoms |\n| Intervention Threshold (CEA) | >70% (NASCET/ECST criteria) | >60% (ACAS/ACST criteria) |\n| Age Consideration | Benefit generally outweighs risk | Benefit diminishes significantly >80 years old |\n| Stenting (CAS) | Reserved for high-risk CEA patients | Generally not recommended, higher stroke risk than CEA |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Asymptomatic >80yo carotid stenosis? Watch and wait.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound would show high-velocity flow and turbulent waveforms at the site of stenosis, with a peak systolic velocity ratio >4.0 for 90% stenosis. CTA would reveal the degree of luminal narrowing and plaque morphology. Intraoperatively, the plaque would be visualized and removed during endarterectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 American Heart Association/American Stroke Association (AHA/ASA) Guidelines for the Prevention of Stroke in Patients With Stroke and Transient Ischemic Attack. These guidelines recommend against routine revascularization for asymptomatic carotid stenosis in patients with a life expectancy of less than 5 years or those over 80 years old, due to increased procedural risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right carotid endarterectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Left carotid endarterectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right carotid artery stenting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Left carotid artery stenting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | No surgical/endovascular intervention. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Carotid endarterectomy is indicated for patients with a symptomatic (ie transient ischaemic attack [** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
