  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the brain cries out, find the contralateral culprit.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Right carotid endarterectomy. The patient's recurrent left upper limb symptoms are classic for a transient ischemic attack (TIA) originating from the contralateral (right) internal carotid artery, which has a high-grade 90% stenosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCarotid artery stenosis causes neurological symptoms when plaque or thrombus embolizes to the cerebral circulation. Symptoms like left upper limb weakness or numbness are contralateral to the affected carotid artery, meaning the right internal carotid artery is the symptomatic lesion. A 90% stenosis is considered severe and symptomatic, warranting intervention. Carotid endarterectomy (CEA) is the gold standard for symptomatic high-grade carotid stenosis in suitable patients, as it directly removes the atherosclerotic plaque, effectively reducing the risk of future stroke.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Left carotid endarterectomy is incorrect because the patient's symptoms (left upper limb) are contralateral to the *right* carotid artery. Intervening on the asymptomatic left ICA would not address the current symptoms.\nOption C (Incorrect): Right carotid artery stenting is an alternative, but endarterectomy is generally preferred for symptomatic high-grade stenosis in patients suitable for surgery, especially given the patient's age (72 years), where CEA often has better long-term outcomes and lower periprocedural stroke risk compared to CAS in this demographic.\nOption D (Incorrect): Left carotid artery stenting is incorrect for the same reasons as B and C; the symptoms are not related to the left ICA, and CEA is generally preferred over CAS for symptomatic high-grade stenosis in this age group.\nOption E (Incorrect): No surgical/endovascular intervention is incorrect because the patient has symptomatic, high-grade (90%) carotid stenosis, which carries a high risk of future stroke and warrants intervention to prevent further neurological events.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Symptomatic Carotid Stenosis | Asymptomatic Carotid Stenosis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Definition | TIA/stroke symptoms referable to the stenotic artery | No TIA/stroke symptoms |\n| Intervention Threshold | >50% stenosis (CEA preferred >70%) | >60% stenosis (CEA considered) |\n| Primary Goal | Prevent recurrent stroke/TIA | Prevent first stroke |\n| Treatment | CEA or CAS (patient-specific) | Medical management +/- CEA/CAS |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nContralateral symptoms, ipsilateral stenosis: operate on the symptomatic side.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDoppler ultrasound would show high-velocity flow and spectral broadening at the right ICA bulb, indicating severe stenosis. CTA or MRA would confirm the 90% luminal narrowing of the right ICA. Intraoperatively, a thick, calcified, or ulcerated plaque would be visualized within the right common carotid artery bifurcation extending into the ICA.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2014 AHA/ASA Guidelines for the Prevention of Stroke in Patients With Stroke and Transient Ischemic Attack. These guidelines recommend carotid endarterectomy for symptomatic patients with 70-99% ICA stenosis who are good surgical candidates.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right carotid endarterectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Left carotid endarterectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right carotid artery stenting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Left carotid artery stenting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | No surgical/endovascular intervention. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) In this case, the 90% stenosis of the right carotid artery correlates with recurrent transient loss ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
