  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When swelling strikes young, think Praecox, not just puberty!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Lymphoedema Praecox. This diagnosis is appropriate for a 15-year-old girl presenting with recent leg swelling and confirmed lymphatic abnormality, as it typically manifests around puberty and before age 35 without an obvious secondary cause.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLymphoedema Praecox is a form of primary lymphoedema, meaning it's not caused by an identifiable external factor. It characteristically presents between puberty and 35 years of age, often in females, with progressive swelling due to impaired lymphatic drainage. The patient's age (15 years), recent onset of swelling, and the finding of lymphatic abnormality on lymphoscintigraphy, coupled with the absence of other obvious causes, strongly point to this diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Kippel-Trenaunay Syndrome) (Incorrect): This syndrome is characterized by a triad of capillary malformation (port-wine stain), venous malformations, and limb overgrowth, which are not described in the patient's presentation.\nOption C (Lymphoedema Tarda) (Incorrect): Lymphoedema Tarda is a primary lymphoedema that manifests after the age of 35, making it inconsistent with a 15-year-old patient.\nOption D (Milroy Disease) (Incorrect): Milroy Disease is a congenital form of primary lymphoedema, typically presenting at birth or in early infancy, not at 15 years old with recent onset.\nOption E (Secondary Lymphoedema) (Incorrect): Secondary lymphoedema results from an identifiable cause like surgery, radiation, infection, or trauma. The question states the abdomen and groin ultrasound were unremarkable, and no other aetiology is mentioned, making this less likely.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Lymphoedema | Onset Age | Key Features |\n| :------------------ | :-------- | :----------- |\n| Milroy Disease      | Congenital (birth/infancy) | Primary, genetic, often bilateral |\n| Lymphoedema Praecox | Puberty - 35 years | Primary, more common in females, often unilateral |\n| Lymphoedema Tarda   | > 35 years | Primary, slower progression |\n| Secondary Lymphoedema | Any age | Due to identifiable cause (surgery, radiation, infection, trauma) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Age of onset is key to differentiating primary lymphoedema types.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nLymphoscintigraphy in lymphoedema typically shows delayed or absent lymphatic flow, dermal backflow, and reduced or absent visualization of lymph nodes, confirming lymphatic dysfunction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Society of Lymphology (ISL) Consensus Document on the Management of Lymphoedema (2020). It recommends lymphoscintigraphy for the diagnosis of primary lymphoedema.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Kippel-Trenaunay Syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lymphoedema Praecox | ✅ Correct |\n| C | LymphodemaTarda | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Milroy Disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Secondary Lymphoedema. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) This is primary lymphoedema that occurs after puberty and before the age of 35 years. It is more com** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
