  "answer": "C) Chronic venous insufficiency describes a spectrum of disease of the lower limb veins in which venous return is chronically impaired by reflux, obstruction, or calf pump failure. This results in sustained venous hypertension, which is associated with clinical complications such as oedema, eczema, lipodermatosclerosis and ulceration. Varicose veins are usually characteristic of this condition, and provide visual confirmation of venous reflux. However, the absence of visible varicose veins does not exclude the presence of significant superficial reflux. The pain associated with this condition tends to be worse following prolonged periods of standing (gravitational effects/calf pump not functional), and is relieved by rest and elevation of the affected limb. In the case described (and most commonly) the insufficiency is secondary to previous venous obstruction of the deep veins by thrombosis (DVT).",
