  "question": "A 72-year-old man presents with a 4-hour history of acute ischaemia of the left leg. Clinical examination demonstrates signs of acute ischaemia with no evidence of gangrene, mottling or neurological deficit. An urgent angiogram reveals a complete thrombotic occlusion of the distal superficial femoral artery. Select the most likely single treatment for this case.",
