  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't operate on claudication that doesn't bother the patient.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is \"Lifestyle changes only\" because the patient presents with intermittent claudication that does not impact his lifestyle, work, or social activities. Initial management for non-disabling claudication always prioritizes conservative measures, including risk factor modification and supervised exercise programs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntermittent claudication, especially when not lifestyle-limiting, is primarily managed with aggressive risk factor modification (smoking cessation, blood pressure control, lipid management, diabetes control) and a structured exercise program. This approach aims to improve walking distance, reduce cardiovascular event risk, and often stabilizes or improves symptoms, delaying or avoiding the need for invasive procedures. The patient's symptoms are mild and do not warrant immediate revascularization.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Below-knee amputation) (Incorrect): Amputation is reserved for critical limb ischemia (CLI) with tissue loss, intractable rest pain, or severe infection, none of which are present here.\nOption B (Fasciotomy) (Incorrect): Fasciotomy is a surgical procedure to relieve pressure in a compartment syndrome, a distinct acute condition not related to chronic intermittent claudication.\nOption C (Femorodistal bypass) (Incorrect): Femorodistal bypass is a revascularization procedure for severe, lifestyle-limiting claudication or critical limb ischemia, typically involving bypass to arteries below the knee. It is too aggressive for this patient's mild symptoms.\nOption D (Femoropopliteal bypass) (Incorrect): Femoropopliteal bypass is a revascularization procedure for severe, lifestyle-limiting claudication or critical limb ischemia, bypassing a diseased superficial femoral artery. It is an invasive procedure not indicated for non-disabling claudication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| PAD Stage/Symptom | Description | Initial Treatment | Intervention (if needed) |\n| :---------------- | :---------- | :---------------- | :----------------------- |\n| Asymptomatic | No symptoms | Risk factor modification | Surveillance |\n| Intermittent Claudication (non-limiting) | Pain with exertion, no impact on daily life | Risk factor modification, supervised exercise | Rarely indicated |\n| Intermittent Claudication (limiting) | Pain with exertion, impacts daily life | Risk factor modification, supervised exercise | Endovascular or surgical revascularization |\n| Critical Limb Ischemia | Rest pain, tissue loss (ulcers, gangrene) | Urgent revascularization, pain management, wound care | Endovascular or surgical revascularization, amputation (last resort) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-disabling claudication = lifestyle changes first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAngiography would reveal the 12-cm stenosis in the proximal superficial femoral artery, confirming the anatomical lesion but not necessarily dictating immediate intervention given the patient's mild symptoms.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AHA/ACC Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease. It recommends supervised exercise therapy and risk factor modification as first-line treatment for intermittent claudication.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Below-knee amputation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fasciotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Femorodistal bypass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Femoropopliteal bypass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Lifestyle changes only | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The initial treatment of intermittent claudication is correction of risk factors, such as diabetes, ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
