  "answer": "D) There are many adverse effects associated with excess glucocorticoids. Thinning of the skin, osteonecrosis and osteoporosis are all common. Steroids are associated with retention of sodium and water. Potassium loss may occur and hypokalaemic alkalosis has been reported.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Steroids: great for inflammation, terrible for everything else!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Hyponatraemia. Excess glucocorticoids, whether endogenous or exogenous, typically lead to sodium and water retention due to their mineralocorticoid activity, making hyponatremia an unlikely direct consequence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nExcess glucocorticoids exert significant mineralocorticoid effects, particularly at high concentrations, leading to increased sodium reabsorption in the renal tubules and subsequent water retention. This mechanism often results in hypernatremia or normonatremia, not hyponatremia. Concurrently, this mineralocorticoid activity promotes potassium excretion, frequently causing hypokalemia. Beyond electrolyte imbalances, glucocorticoids are profoundly catabolic, leading to muscle wasting, skin thinning, and severe bone demineralization, manifesting as osteoporosis and osteonecrosis. In pediatric patients, chronic exposure significantly inhibits growth, resulting in growth retardation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Osteonecrosis is a well-established and severe complication of chronic glucocorticoid excess, particularly affecting weight-bearing joints.\nOption B (Incorrect): Osteoporosis is a classic and highly prevalent adverse effect of glucocorticoid excess, leading to increased fracture risk due to impaired bone formation and accelerated bone resorption.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hypokalaemia is a common electrolyte disturbance seen with excess glucocorticoids, resulting from their mineralocorticoid-like effects on renal potassium excretion.\nOption E (Incorrect): Growth retardation is a significant concern in children on chronic glucocorticoid therapy, as these hormones suppress growth hormone secretion and directly inhibit growth plate function.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| System | Effect of Excess Glucocorticoids |\n| :----- | :------------------------------- |\n| Electrolytes | Sodium retention, Hypokalemia |\n| Musculoskeletal | Osteoporosis, Osteonecrosis, Muscle wasting |\n| Skin | Thinning, Easy bruising, Striae |\n| Growth (Children) | Growth retardation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Glucocorticoids retain Na+, excrete K+, and destroy bone.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging studies such as DEXA scans would reveal decreased bone mineral density consistent with osteoporosis. MRI of affected joints, particularly the hips, may demonstrate osteonecrosis, appearing as areas of altered signal intensity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis of Cushing's Syndrome (2008, updated 2015) outlines the systemic effects of glucocorticoid excess.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Osteonecrosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Osteoporosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hypokalaemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hyponatraemia | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Growth retardation in children | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) There are many adverse effects associated with excess glucocorticoids. Thinning of the skin, osteone** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
