  "question": "Considering cluster randomised trials, which of the following statements is false?",
  "options": {
    "A": "They consider interventions targeted at groups",
    "B": "They require increased recruitment to achieve the same level of statistical power as individual trials",
    "C": "If results are analysed on an individual basis a lower P value may be obtained",
    "D": "They are less prone to unit of analyses errors than trials involving individual observations",
    "E": "The statistical analyses for these trials is more complex than that required for trials based on individuals"
  },
  "answer": "D) Cluster randomised trials are more prone to unit of analyses errors than individual based trials. Clustering needs to be considered in trial design and data analysis. One of the commonest errors is where a study is a cluster study but researchers have failed to recognise this fact. This will then result in the incorrect analysis being pursued. A lower P value will then result and a false positive error will occur.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cluster-fudge your stats, or you'll get a false positive!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies statement D as false. Cluster randomized trials are, in fact, more prone to unit of analysis errors than individual-level trials, primarily due to the inherent correlation within clusters that must be accounted for in the analysis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCluster randomized trials involve randomizing groups (clusters) rather than individuals, leading to a correlation between outcomes of individuals within the same cluster, known as intra-cluster correlation (ICC). Failing to account for this ICC in the analysis, often by treating individual observations as independent, constitutes a unit of analysis error. This error artificially inflates the effective sample size, reduces the standard errors, and can lead to a falsely low P-value and an increased risk of Type I error (false positive). Proper design and analysis, using methods like mixed-effects models, are crucial to avoid these pitfalls.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This statement is true. Cluster trials are specifically designed for interventions that are naturally applied to groups, such as educational programs for classrooms or public health campaigns for communities.\nOption B (Incorrect): This statement is true. Due to intra-cluster correlation, individuals within a cluster are not independent. To achieve the same statistical power as an individually randomized trial, a cluster trial requires a larger total sample size, often quantified by the design effect.\nOption C (Incorrect): This statement is true. If results are analyzed on an individual basis without accounting for clustering, the standard errors will be underestimated, leading to a smaller P-value and an increased chance of finding a statistically significant, but potentially false, effect.\nOption E (Incorrect): This statement is true. The statistical analysis for cluster randomized trials is more complex, requiring methods that account for the hierarchical structure and intra-cluster correlation, such as mixed-effects models or generalized estimating equations (GEE).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Individual RCT | Cluster RCT |\n|---|---|---|\n| Intervention Target | Individuals | Groups/Clusters |\n| Unit of Randomization | Individual | Cluster |\n| Sample Size for Power | Smaller | Larger (due to ICC) |\n| Statistical Analysis | Simpler (e.g., t-test, chi-square) | More Complex (e.g., mixed models, GEE) |\n| Unit of Analysis Error Risk | Lower | Higher (if clustering ignored) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cluster trials need more people and complex stats to avoid false positives.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable to this question, as it pertains to trial design and statistical methodology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCONSORT Statement for Cluster Randomized Trials (2012). This guideline provides an extension to the main CONSORT statement, offering specific guidance for reporting cluster randomized trials, including details on design, analysis, and interpretation to ensure transparency and reduce bias.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | They consider interventions targeted at groups | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | They require increased recruitment to achieve the same level of statistical | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | If results are analysed on an individual basis a lower P value may be obtai | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | They are less prone to unit of analyses errors than trials involving indivi | ✅ Correct |\n| E | The statistical analyses for these trials is more complex than that require | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Cluster randomised trials are more prone to unit of analyses errors than individual based trials. Cl** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
