  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Median nerve injury: Ape hand, but dorsal thenar sensation stays!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B. A median nerve injury proximal to the flexor retinaculum will cause significant motor and sensory deficits in the hand, but the dorsal aspect of the thenar eminence is primarily innervated by the radial nerve, making sensation loss in this area least likely.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe median nerve provides motor innervation to the thenar muscles (abductor pollicis brevis, opponens pollicis, superficial head of flexor pollicis brevis) and the first two lumbricals. Its sensory distribution includes the palmar aspect of the thumb, index, middle, and radial half of the ring finger, as well as the dorsal tips of these digits. The dorsal aspect of the thenar eminence, however, receives sensory innervation from the superficial branch of the radial nerve. Therefore, even with a complete median nerve transection at this level, sensation on the dorsal thenar eminence would be preserved, making its loss the least likely feature.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Weakness of thumb abduction is expected as abductor pollicis brevis (median nerve) is paralyzed. While abductor pollicis longus (radial nerve) contributes, overall abduction power will be significantly diminished.\nOption C (Incorrect): Loss of power of opponens pollicis is expected as this muscle is solely innervated by the median nerve, crucial for thumb opposition.\nOption D (Incorrect): Adduction and lateral rotation of the thumb at rest (ape hand deformity) is a classic sign of median nerve palsy, resulting from paralysis of the thenar muscles and unopposed action of adductor pollicis (ulnar nerve) and extensor pollicis longus/brevis (radial nerve).\nOption E (Incorrect): Loss of power of abductor pollicis brevis is expected as it is a key thenar muscle innervated by the median nerve, responsible for true thumb abduction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Motor Innervation (Key Muscles) | Sensory Innervation (Key Areas) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Median Nerve | Abductor Pollicis Brevis, Opponens Pollicis, Flexor Pollicis Brevis (superficial head), 1st/2nd Lumbricals | Palmar aspect of thumb, index, middle, radial half of ring finger; dorsal tips of same fingers |\n| Ulnar Nerve | Adductor Pollicis, Hypothenar muscles, Interossei, 3rd/4th Lumbricals, Flexor Pollicis Brevis (deep head) | Palmar and dorsal aspect of little finger and ulnar half of ring finger |\n| Radial Nerve | Extensor muscles of forearm/hand, Abductor Pollicis Longus | Dorsal aspect of thumb, index, middle, radial half of ring finger (proximal to DIPs); dorsal thenar eminence |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Median nerve injury spares dorsal thenar sensation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring surgical exploration, a transected median nerve at the proximal border of the flexor retinaculum would appear as a complete discontinuity of the nerve fascicles, often with associated hematoma or scar tissue from the glass shard injury. The surrounding tendons (flexor digitorum superficialis/profundus, flexor pollicis longus) would be visibly intact.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Peripheral Nerve Injuries (2019) recommends early diagnosis and surgical repair for sharp transections.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Weakness of thumb abduction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Loss of sensation on the dorsal aspect of the thenar eminence | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Loss of power of opponens pollicis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Adduction and lateral rotation of the thumb at rest | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Loss of power of abductor pollicis brevis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) he median nerve may be injured proximal to the flexor retinaculum. This will result in loss of abduc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
