  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The 'tailor's muscle' is a hip and knee flexor, but it doesn't attach to the femur!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the untrue statement regarding the sartorius muscle. Option E is the correct answer because the sartorius muscle inserts onto the medial aspect of the upper tibia, specifically as part of the pes anserinus, not the medial femoral condyle.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe sartorius is the longest muscle in the human body, originating from the anterior superior iliac spine (ASIS) and inserting onto the medial aspect of the upper tibia. Its oblique course across the anterior thigh allows it to act on both the hip and knee joints, performing flexion, abduction, and lateral rotation at the hip, and flexion at the knee. Its innervation by the femoral nerve and its anatomical relationships, such as forming the lateral boundary of the femoral triangle and the roof of the adductor canal, are critical anatomical facts.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This statement is true. The sartorius muscle is innervated by the femoral nerve (L2, L3).\nOption B (Incorrect): This statement is true. The sartorius muscle forms the lateral boundary of the femoral triangle.\nOption C (Incorrect): This statement is true. The sartorius muscle forms the roof of the adductor canal (Hunter's canal).\nOption D (Incorrect): This statement is true. The sartorius muscle is a flexor of both the hip and knee joints.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sartorius Muscle |\n|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Anterior superior iliac spine (ASIS) |\n| **Insertion** | Medial aspect of upper tibia (pes anserinus) |\n| **Innervation** | Femoral nerve (L2, L3) |\n| **Actions** | Flexes, abducts, laterally rotates hip; flexes knee |\n| **Key Relations** | Lateral boundary of femoral triangle, roof of adductor canal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sartorius: ASIS to pes anserinus, femoral nerve, flexes hip and knee.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring surgical exposure of the femoral triangle or adductor canal, the sartorius muscle is a key superficial landmark. On ultrasound, it appears as a superficial, strap-like muscle, often used as a landmark for femoral nerve blocks or saphenous nerve blocks within the adductor canal.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGray's Anatomy, 42nd Edition (2020) provides detailed anatomical descriptions of the sartorius muscle and its attachments.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is supplied by the femoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It forms the lateral boundary of the femoral triangle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The middle third forms the roof of the adductor canal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It is a flexor of the hip and knee | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It inserts into the medial femoral condyle | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) It inserts into the medial aspect of the upper part o** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
