  "question": "Which of the following is least likely to be associated with hypercalcaemia?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Thiazides",
    "B": "Antacids",
    "C": "Coeliac disease",
    "D": "Sarcoidosis",
    "E": "Zolinger-Ellison syndrome"
  },
  "answer": "C) Patients with coeliac disease tend to develop hypocalcaemia due to malabsorption of calcium by the bowel.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Coeliac disease: malabsorption means low calcium, not high!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Coeliac disease, because it leads to malabsorption of calcium and vitamin D, resulting in hypocalcemia, making it the least likely cause of hypercalcemia among the options provided.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCalcium absorption primarily occurs in the small intestine, a process significantly enhanced by active vitamin D. Coeliac disease, an autoimmune disorder, causes inflammation and villous atrophy in the small intestine upon gluten exposure. This damage severely impairs the absorptive surface, leading to malabsorption of dietary calcium and vitamin D. Consequently, patients with coeliac disease typically experience a net deficit of calcium, often manifesting as hypocalcemia, rather than elevated calcium levels.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Thiazide diuretics decrease renal calcium excretion by enhancing calcium reabsorption in the distal tubule, leading to increased serum calcium levels.\nOption B (Incorrect): Chronic ingestion of calcium-containing antacids, especially with milk or vitamin D, can lead to milk-alkali syndrome, characterized by hypercalcemia, metabolic alkalosis, and renal insufficiency.\nOption D (Incorrect): Sarcoidosis is a granulomatous disease where activated macrophages in the granulomas produce 1-alpha hydroxylase, which converts inactive vitamin D to its active form. This leads to increased intestinal calcium absorption and hypercalcemia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Zollinger-Ellison syndrome (gastrinoma) is frequently associated with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 1 (MEN1). MEN1 commonly includes primary hyperparathyroidism, which is a leading cause of hypercalcemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Effect on Calcium | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Coeliac Disease | Hypocalcemia | Malabsorption of calcium and vitamin D due to villous atrophy |\n| Thiazide Diuretics | Hypercalcemia | Increased renal tubular reabsorption of calcium |\n| Sarcoidosis | Hypercalcemia | Granuloma production of active vitamin D (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D) |\n| Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome (via MEN1) | Hypercalcemia | Primary hyperparathyroidism (parathyroid adenoma/hyperplasia) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malabsorption causes hypocalcemia; other options cause hypercalcemia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor coeliac disease, endoscopy with biopsy would reveal characteristic villous atrophy, crypt hyperplasia, and increased intraepithelial lymphocytes in the small intestine. In cases of hypercalcemia due to primary hyperparathyroidism (often associated with ZES/MEN1), a Sestamibi scan might localize a parathyroid adenoma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNICE Guideline NG20: Coeliac disease: recognition, assessment and management (2015, updated 2023) recommends screening for nutritional deficiencies, including calcium and vitamin D, in patients with coeliac disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thiazides | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Antacids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Coeliac disease | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Sarcoidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Zolinger-Ellison syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Patients with coeliac disease tend to develop hypocalcaemia due to malabsorption of calcium by the b** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
