  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's punched out and shallow, think acute, not scary.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Acute peptic ulcer. The endoscopic description of a \"punched out,\" \"shallow,\" 1cm ulcer on the anterior wall of the stomach, without mention of induration or fibrosis, strongly suggests an acute process rather than a chronic one or malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute peptic ulcers are characterized by their superficial nature, often appearing as a clean, punched-out defect in the mucosa, typically without significant surrounding inflammation or fibrosis. Their small size (often <1-2 cm) and shallow depth distinguish them from chronic ulcers, which tend to be deeper, larger, and have evidence of healing and scarring. The anterior wall location is common, and the absence of features like irregular margins, nodularity, or friability further supports a benign, acute etiology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Chronic peptic ulcer) (Incorrect): Chronic ulcers are typically deeper, larger, and often show signs of fibrosis, scarring, or induration at their base and margins, which are not described here.\nOption C (Adenocarcinoma) (Incorrect): Gastric adenocarcinomas presenting as ulcers are usually irregular, raised, nodular, or friable, and often have heaped-up margins, not a clean \"punched out\" appearance.\nOption D (Lymphoma) (Incorrect): Gastric lymphoma often presents as an infiltrative lesion, a mass, or multiple ulcers, not typically a single, shallow, punched-out ulcer.\nOption E (Dieulafoy lesion) (Incorrect): A Dieulafoy lesion is a vascular malformation, not an ulcer. It's characterized by an abnormally large submucosal artery that erodes through the mucosa, causing massive bleeding, but it doesn't present as a \"punched out ulcer.\"\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Peptic Ulcer | Chronic Peptic Ulcer | Malignant Ulcer (e.g., Adenocarcinoma) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Size** | Usually <1-2 cm | Often >1-2 cm | Variable, can be large |\n| **Depth** | Shallow, superficial | Deep, penetrates muscularis propria | Variable, often infiltrative |\n| **Edges** | Clean, sharp, \"punched out\" | Indurated, fibrotic, often undermined | Irregular, heaped-up, nodular, friable |\n| **Base** | Clean, smooth | Granulation tissue, fibrosis | Necrotic, irregular, often firm |\n| **Histology** | Acute inflammation, necrosis | Chronic inflammation, fibrosis, granulation tissue | Atypical cells, glandular distortion |\n| **Symptoms** | Acute onset, pain | Chronic/recurrent pain, complications | Weight loss, dysphagia, early satiety |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Shallow, punched-out ulcers without induration are typically acute.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, an acute peptic ulcer appears as a discrete, well-demarcated mucosal defect with a clean base and sharp, non-indurated margins, resembling a \"punched-out\" lesion. The surrounding mucosa may show mild inflammation but lacks significant edema or nodularity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017). It recommends biopsy for gastric ulcers to rule out malignancy and PPI therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute peptic ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Chronic peptic ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Adenocarcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Dieulafoy lesion | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The absence of fibrosis coupled with small size suggests a more acute ulcer. Management should inclu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
