  "answer": "D) Causes of avascular necrosis P ancreatitis L upus A lcohol S teroids T rauma I diopathic, infection C aisson disease, collagen vascular disease R adiation, rheumatoid arthritis A myloid G aucher disease S ickle cell disease Steroid containing therapy for myeloma may induce avascular necrosis, however the disease itself does not cause it. Caisson disease as may occur in deep sea divers is a recognised cause.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Myeloma doesn't kill bone, but its treatment might.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Myeloma. This question tests your knowledge of the direct causes of avascular necrosis (AVN), highlighting that while treatments for certain conditions (like steroids for myeloma) can cause AVN, the underlying disease itself may not be a direct cause.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAvascular necrosis (osteonecrosis) results from the death of bone cells due to an interruption of blood supply. Common causes like high-dose steroid use can lead to adipocyte hypertrophy and fat emboli, while sickle cell disease causes microvascular occlusion. Radiotherapy damages the microvasculature, and Caisson disease (decompression sickness) involves nitrogen bubble emboli, all directly compromising bone perfusion and leading to cellular death and eventual bone collapse.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Steroids are a well-established and common cause of avascular necrosis, often due to fat emboli, increased intraosseous pressure, or direct osteocyte toxicity.\nOption B (Incorrect): Sickle cell disease causes vaso-occlusive crises, leading to ischemia and infarction of bone tissue, making it a direct cause of AVN.\nOption C (Incorrect): Radiotherapy can damage the microvasculature of bone, leading to impaired blood supply and subsequent avascular necrosis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Caisson disease (decompression sickness) involves nitrogen bubbles forming in the blood, which can act as emboli and obstruct blood flow to bone, causing AVN.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Category | Specific Cause | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Traumatic** | Fracture, Dislocation | Direct disruption of blood vessels |\n| **Non-Traumatic** | Steroids | Fat emboli, adipocyte hypertrophy, osteocyte toxicity |\n| | Alcoholism | Fat emboli, increased intraosseous pressure |\n| | Sickle Cell Disease | Vaso-occlusion, microthrombi |\n| | Caisson Disease | Nitrogen bubble emboli |\n| | Radiotherapy | Vascular damage, endothelial injury |\n| | Lupus (SLE) | Vasculitis, steroid use |\n| | Gaucher Disease | Lipid-laden macrophages obstructing vessels |\n| | Pancreatitis | Fat emboli |\n| | Idiopathic | Unknown |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember PLASTIC RAGS for AVN causes; Myeloma itself is not on the list.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEarly avascular necrosis may show normal X-rays. MRI is the most sensitive imaging modality, revealing low signal on T1-weighted images and variable signal on T2-weighted images, often with a characteristic \"double line sign.\" Later stages show subchondral lucency (crescent sign), sclerosis, and eventual joint collapse.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Osteonecrosis of the Femoral Head (2019). Recommends MRI for diagnosis and various treatment options based on disease stage.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Steroids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sickle cell disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Myeloma | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Caisson disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Causes of avascular necrosis P ancreatitis L upus A lcohol S teroids T rauma I diopathic, infection ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
