  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When faces droop and glands swell, sarcoidosis rings the bell!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Sarcoidosis. This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the classic presentation of bilateral facial nerve palsy combined with bilateral parotid gland enlargement and systemic symptoms like lethargy, pointing towards a multisystem inflammatory condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSarcoidosis is a multisystem granulomatous disease characterized by non-caseating granulomas. Neurological involvement, particularly facial nerve palsy, is the most common cranial neuropathy in sarcoidosis and can often present bilaterally. Parotid gland involvement, known as Heerfordt's syndrome (uveoparotid fever), manifests as bilateral, firm, non-tender enlargement and is a key diagnostic clue when combined with neurological symptoms. The systemic nature of sarcoidosis explains the lethargy and multifocal presentation, making it the most likely cause for this constellation of symptoms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pleomorphic adenoma is a benign salivary gland tumor, typically presenting as a solitary, discrete, slow-growing mass, not bilateral parotid enlargement with bilateral facial nerve palsy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Cerebrovascular accident (stroke) can cause facial weakness, but it's usually unilateral and central, sparing the forehead, and would not cause bilateral parotid gland enlargement.\nOption D (Incorrect): Warthin's tumour is another benign salivary gland tumor, usually solitary, and not associated with bilateral facial nerve palsy or systemic symptoms like lethargy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Adenoid cystic carcinoma is a malignant salivary gland tumor that can cause facial nerve palsy due to perineural invasion, but it typically presents as a solitary, often painful mass, and usually unilateral, not bilateral parotid enlargement with bilateral facial nerve palsy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Parotid Gland | Facial Nerve Palsy | Other Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Sarcoidosis | Bilateral enlargement | Bilateral (commonest cranial neuropathy) | Lethargy, uveitis, pulmonary infiltrates, erythema nodosum |\n| Pleomorphic Adenoma | Unilateral, discrete mass | Rare (unless very large/malignant transformation) | Slow-growing, firm, mobile |\n| Warthin's Tumour | Unilateral, discrete mass | No | Often in smokers, cystic component |\n| Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma | Unilateral, discrete mass | Unilateral (perineural invasion) | Pain, aggressive, high recurrence |\n| Bell's Palsy | Normal | Unilateral (idiopathic) | Acute onset, viral prodrome |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilateral facial palsy + parotid enlargement = think sarcoidosis (Heerfordt's syndrome).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging of the parotid glands (ultrasound or MRI) would show diffuse, often bilateral, enlargement without a discrete mass. Chest X-ray or CT would likely reveal bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, a hallmark of sarcoidosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thoracic Society (ATS) Clinical Practice Guidelines: Diagnosis and Management of Sarcoidosis (2020). These guidelines recommend a comprehensive approach to diagnosis, including biopsy confirmation of non-caseating granulomas and exclusion of other granulomatous diseases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pleomorphic adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cerebrovascular accident | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Sarcoidosis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Warthins tumour | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Adenoid cystic carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Facial nerve palsy is the commonest neurological manifestation of sarcoid. It usually resolves. The ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
