  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stable impaction means early motion, not operation!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C because an impacted fracture of the surgical neck of the humerus is inherently stable. This stability allows for non-operative management with early mobilization, which is crucial for functional recovery and preventing stiffness.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nImpacted fractures of the surgical neck are characterized by the bone fragments being driven into each other, creating a stable construct. This intrinsic stability means that surgical intervention is rarely necessary. The primary goal of treatment is to maintain reduction (which is often already achieved by the impaction) and initiate early range of motion to prevent shoulder stiffness, a common complication of immobilization. A collar and cuff provides adequate support while allowing for pendulum exercises and gradual physiotherapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Reducing the fracture and applying a plate is an aggressive surgical intervention typically reserved for displaced, unstable, or comminuted fractures, not for a stable, impacted injury.\nOption B (Incorrect): Performing a hemiarthroplasty is a major reconstructive surgery indicated for highly comminuted fractures, severe displacement, or avascular necrosis of the humeral head, which is not the case for a simple impacted fracture.\nOption D (Incorrect): Applying an upper limb cast for 8 weeks would lead to significant shoulder stiffness and functional impairment, as prolonged immobilization is detrimental for stable proximal humerus fractures.\nOption E (Incorrect): An external fixator system is used for complex, open, or highly unstable fractures, often with significant soft tissue injury, and is entirely inappropriate for a stable, closed, impacted fracture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type (Proximal Humerus) | Stability | Typical Management | Key Consideration |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Impacted Surgical Neck | Stable | Collar & Cuff, early PT | Prevent stiffness |\n| Displaced Surgical Neck | Unstable | ORIF (plate/screws) | Achieve anatomical reduction |\n| 3-part/4-part | Unstable, comminuted | ORIF, Hemiarthroplasty, Reverse TSA | Preserve function, manage AVN risk |\n| Humeral Head Split | Unstable | ORIF, Hemiarthroplasty | Articular surface integrity |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Impacted surgical neck = stable, non-op, early motion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs (AP and lateral/scapular Y views), an impacted surgical neck fracture will show the humeral head driven into the shaft, often with varus angulation, but with minimal displacement of the articular surface. The fracture line will appear compressed or \"telescoped.\"\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Treatment of Proximal Humerus Fractures (2019) recommends non-operative management for minimally displaced or stable fractures, emphasizing early range of motion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Reduce the fracture and apply a plate to stabilize the fragments | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Perform a hemiarthroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Apply a collar and cuff system for three weeks and then commence physiother | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Apply an upper limb cast for 8 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Apply an external fixator system | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Impacted fractures of the surgical neck are stable injuries and usually heal without complication. I** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
