  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Your own tissue is always the best tissue.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Autograft. This question assesses fundamental knowledge of transplant terminology, specifically identifying the type of graft used when a patient's own tissue is transplanted within the same individual.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn autograft involves transplanting tissue from one part of an individual's body to another part of the same individual. In coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG), the long saphenous vein is commonly harvested from the patient's leg and then anastomosed to the coronary arteries to bypass stenotic lesions. This is a highly successful procedure due to the complete immunological compatibility between the donor and recipient sites, as they are the same person, thus eliminating the risk of immune rejection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Allograft) (Incorrect): An allograft involves transplanting tissue between genetically non-identical individuals of the same species. This would typically require immunosuppression to prevent rejection.\nOption B (Isograft) (Incorrect): An isograft involves transplanting tissue between genetically identical individuals (e.g., identical twins). This is not applicable when using a patient's own tissue.\nOption C (Xenograft) (Incorrect): A xenograft involves transplanting tissue between individuals of different species. This carries a very high risk of rejection and is not used for coronary bypass conduits.\nOption E (None of the above) (Incorrect): Autograft is the correct description.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Graft Type | Donor/Recipient Relationship | Immunological Rejection Risk |\n|---|---|---|\n| Autograft | Same individual | None |\n| Isograft | Genetically identical individuals (e.g., identical twins) | None |\n| Allograft | Genetically non-identical individuals of same species | High (requires immunosuppression) |\n| Xenograft | Different species | Very High (requires intense immunosuppression) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Auto = self. Autograft is always from the same patient.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the long saphenous vein is typically harvested from the leg, often endoscopically, and then prepared for anastomosis. During CABG, the harvested vein is seen being sutured proximally to the aorta and distally to the coronary artery beyond the stenosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization: Recommends the use of autologous conduits (e.g., saphenous vein, internal mammary artery) for CABG due to superior patency and survival outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Allograft | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Isograft | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Xenograft | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Autograft | ✅ Correct |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The long saphenous vein is one of the commonest autografts in surgery** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
