  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gluteus maximus split? Think inferior gluteal artery bleed!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Inferior gluteal artery. This vessel is consistently encountered and at risk during the posterior approach to the hip joint, as it courses on the deep surface of the gluteus maximus muscle, which is incised during this approach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe inferior gluteal artery is a direct branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac artery. It exits the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen, inferior to the piriformis muscle, and then descends between the gluteus maximus and the short external rotator muscles. Its intimate relationship with the deep surface of the gluteus maximus makes it highly susceptible to injury when the muscle is split or incised during a posterior approach to the hip, leading to brisk arterial bleeding as described in the scenario. Understanding this precise anatomical relationship is crucial for surgical safety and hemorrhage control.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Profunda femoris artery) (Incorrect): This artery is a major branch of the femoral artery in the anterior thigh compartment and is not typically encountered in the gluteal region during a posterior hip approach.\nOption B (External iliac artery) (Incorrect): The external iliac artery is a large vessel within the pelvis, proximal to the hip joint, and is not directly involved in the gluteal dissection during a posterior approach.\nOption C (Internal iliac artery) (Incorrect): While the inferior gluteal artery is a branch of the internal iliac artery, the internal iliac itself is a major pelvic vessel and not the direct source of bleeding in the gluteal field.\nOption D (Obturator artery) (Incorrect): The obturator artery supplies the adductor compartment of the thigh and parts of the hip joint, but it is not located in the gluteal region where gluteus maximus is divided.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery                 | Origin                 | Course/Location                                                              | Vulnerability in Hip Surgery                               |\n|------------------------|------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Inferior Gluteal Artery| Internal Iliac Artery  | Exits pelvis via greater sciatic foramen, deep to gluteus maximus            | High risk during posterior approach (gluteus maximus split)|\n| Superior Gluteal Artery| Internal Iliac Artery  | Exits pelvis via greater sciatic foramen, superior to piriformis             | Risk during superior gluteal dissection, less common in posterior approach |\n| Profunda Femoris Artery| Femoral Artery         | Descends in anterior/medial thigh, deep to adductor longus                   | Not typically encountered in gluteal dissection            |\n| Obturator Artery       | Internal Iliac Artery  | Exits pelvis via obturator canal, supplies adductor compartment              | Not typically encountered in gluteal dissection            |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Posterior hip approach = Inferior gluteal artery at risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after splitting the gluteus maximus fibers, brisk arterial bleeding from the deep aspect of the muscle would immediately indicate injury to the inferior gluteal artery. The vessel would need to be identified, ligated, or cauterized to achieve hemostasis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for Total Hip Arthroplasty (2014, updated). Recommends careful anatomical dissection and hemostasis during all surgical approaches to minimize complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Profunda femoris artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | External iliac artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Internal iliac artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Obturator artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Inferior gluteal artery | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The inferior gluteal artery runs on the deep surface of the gluteus maximus muscle. It is a branch o** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
