  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Match your test to your data's distribution!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe T-test is the most appropriate statistical test for data that follows a normal distribution. This is because the T-test is a parametric test, which relies on assumptions about the underlying distribution of the data, specifically normality.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nParametric tests, such as the T-test, are powerful statistical tools used when data meets certain assumptions, including normal distribution, homogeneity of variances, and interval or ratio scale measurement. When these assumptions are met, parametric tests offer greater statistical power to detect true differences or relationships. The T-test specifically compares the means of two groups, making it ideal for normally distributed continuous data.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Fishers exact test) (Incorrect): This is a non-parametric test used for analyzing categorical data in 2x2 contingency tables, particularly when expected cell counts are small.\nOption C (Spearmans rank test) (Incorrect): This is a non-parametric measure of the monotonic relationship between two ranked variables, not suitable for normally distributed continuous data.\nOption D (Mann Whitney U test) (Incorrect): This is a non-parametric alternative to the independent samples T-test, used when data is ordinal or not normally distributed.\nOption E (Bonferroni test) (Incorrect): This is a post-hoc correction method used to adjust p-values when multiple statistical tests are performed, not a primary test for comparing distributions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test Type | Data Distribution | Primary Use | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **T-test** | Normal (Parametric) | Compare means of two groups | Comparing mean blood pressure between two drug regimens |\n| **Mann-Whitney U** | Non-normal, Ordinal (Non-parametric) | Compare medians/distributions of two independent groups | Comparing pain scores (ordinal) between two treatment groups |\n| **Fisher's Exact Test** | Categorical (Non-parametric) | Analyze 2x2 contingency tables with small samples | Association between smoking and lung cancer in a small cohort |\n| **Spearman's Rank** | Ordinal, Non-normal (Non-parametric) | Measure monotonic correlation between ranked variables | Correlation between hours studied and exam rank |\n| **Bonferroni Correction** | N/A (Adjustment) | Control Type I error rate with multiple comparisons | Adjusting p-values after multiple post-hoc tests in ANOVA |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: T-test for normal data; non-parametric tests for non-normal or ordinal data.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to statistical methodology and does not involve imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nStatistical methodology is generally guided by principles of biostatistics rather than specific surgical society guidelines. No single guideline applies directly.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | T Test | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Fishers exact test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Spearmans rank test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mann Whitney U test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Bonferroni test | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A T Test is most suited to data which follows the normal distribution as the others are non parametr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
