  "question": "A 73 year old man presents with a tumour at the central aspect of the posterior third of the tongue. To which of the following lymph node groups is it most likely to metastasise?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Submental",
    "B": "Submandibular",
    "C": "Ipsilateral deep cervical nodes",
    "D": "Contralateral deep cervical nodes",
    "E": "Bilateral deep cervical nodes"
  },
  "answer": "E) Posterior third tumours of the tongue commonly metastasise to the bilateral deep cervical lymph nodes Tumours of the posterior third of the tongue will typically metastasise early and bilateral nodal involvement is well recognised, this is most often true of centrally located tumours and those adjacent to the midline as the lymph vessels may cross the median plane at this location.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Posterior tongue, central lesion? Think bilateral deep cervical nodes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Bilateral deep cervical nodes. Tumors located at the central aspect of the posterior third of the tongue are highly prone to early and bilateral metastasis due to the rich lymphatic network and the crossing of lymphatic vessels across the midline in this region.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lymphatic drainage of the tongue is highly organized yet interconnected. The posterior third of the tongue, particularly centrally located lesions, drains primarily to the deep cervical lymph nodes, specifically the jugulodigastric and jugulo-omohyoid groups. A critical anatomical feature is the extensive lymphatic anastomoses and crossing vessels near the midline in the posterior tongue. This allows for direct drainage to both ipsilateral and contralateral deep cervical nodes, making bilateral involvement the most likely and often earliest pattern of metastasis for these specific tumors.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Submental) (Incorrect): Submental nodes primarily drain the anterior tip of the tongue, lower lip, and chin, not the posterior third.\nOption B (Submandibular) (Incorrect): Submandibular nodes drain the anterior two-thirds of the tongue (excluding the tip), floor of mouth, and gingiva, not the primary drainage for the posterior third.\nOption C (Ipsilateral deep cervical nodes) (Incorrect): While ipsilateral deep cervical nodes are certainly involved, for a central posterior lesion, the most likely and characteristic pattern is bilateral involvement due to midline lymphatic crossing.\nOption D (Contralateral deep cervical nodes) (Incorrect): Contralateral nodes are involved, but not exclusively. The most likely scenario for a central posterior lesion is bilateral involvement, encompassing both ipsilateral and contralateral nodes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tongue Region | Primary Lymphatic Drainage |\n|---|---|\n| Anterior tip | Submental nodes |\n| Lateral anterior 2/3 | Ipsilateral submandibular and deep cervical nodes |\n| Central anterior 2/3 | Bilateral submandibular and deep cervical nodes |\n| Posterior 1/3 | Bilateral deep cervical nodes (jugulodigastric, jugulo-omohyoid) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Central posterior tongue = bilateral deep cervical nodes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), one would specifically look for enlarged, often necrotic, lymph nodes in levels II, III, and IV bilaterally. Intraoperatively, this high risk of bilateral involvement necessitates careful bilateral neck dissection, often extending to levels V and potentially I, even in clinically N0 necks, depending on the primary tumor characteristics.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (e.g., Version 1.2024). These guidelines emphasize comprehensive bilateral neck staging and often recommend bilateral neck dissection or definitive radiation for posterior tongue cancers due to the high risk of bilateral nodal metastasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Submental | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Submandibular | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ipsilateral deep cervical nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Contralateral deep cervical nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Bilateral deep cervical nodes | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Posterior third tumours of the tongue commonly metastasise to the bilateral deep cervical lymph node** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
