  "question": "A 23 year old lady is persistently vomiting following a laparoscopic appendicectomy for a perforated gangrenous appendicitis. Imaging shows some dilated small bowel loops. What is the most appropriate course of action?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Insertion of wide bore nasogastric tube",
    "B": "Insertion of narrow bore nasogastric tube",
    "C": "Administration of intravenous cyclizine",
    "D": "Administration of metoclopramide",
    "E": "Arrange a laparotomy"
  },
  "answer": "A) This patient is likely to have a paralytic ileus and the administration of anti emetic drugs in this situation achieves very little. It's important to decompress the stomach and this can be achieved with a wide bore nasogastric tube.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gut's asleep, a big tube's the key!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. This patient presents with persistent vomiting and dilated small bowel loops following appendicectomy, highly suggestive of a post-operative ileus. The most appropriate initial course of action is gastric decompression to relieve symptoms and prevent further complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPost-operative ileus is a common complication where bowel motility is temporarily impaired. The accumulation of gastric and intestinal contents leads to distension, nausea, and vomiting. A wide-bore nasogastric tube is crucial for effective gastric decompression, allowing for the removal of large volumes of fluid and air, thereby alleviating symptoms and reducing the risk of aspiration. Unlike narrow-bore tubes, its larger lumen prevents clogging and ensures efficient drainage. Administering antiemetics without addressing the underlying ileus is largely ineffective and delays appropriate management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): A narrow-bore nasogastric tube is primarily used for enteral feeding or medication administration, not for effective gastric decompression due to its small lumen.\nOption C (Incorrect): Administration of intravenous cyclizine, an antiemetic, will not resolve the underlying issue of bowel distension and ileus; it only masks symptoms and is largely ineffective in this context.\nOption D (Incorrect): Metoclopramide is a prokinetic agent, but it is generally contraindicated or ineffective in cases of established mechanical obstruction or significant ileus, and can potentially worsen symptoms if there's an unrecognized obstruction.\nOption E (Incorrect): Arranging a laparotomy is an overly aggressive initial step for suspected paralytic ileus. Conservative management with gastric decompression is the first-line approach; surgery is reserved for mechanical obstruction or failure of conservative management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Wide-bore NG tube | Narrow-bore NG tube | Antiemetics (e.g., cyclizine) | Prokinetics (e.g., metoclopramide) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Use | Gastric decompression, lavage | Enteral feeding, medication delivery | Symptomatic relief of nausea/vomiting | Enhance GI motility |\n| Efficacy for Ileus Decompression | High | Low/Ineffective | Low/Ineffective | Variable; potentially harmful in obstruction |\n| Lumen Size | Large | Small | N/A | N/A |\n| Risk in Ileus/Obstruction | Low (therapeutic) | Low (ineffective) | Masks symptoms, delays treatment | Potentially harmful if obstruction present |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For post-op ileus with vomiting, decompress the stomach first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray or CT, dilated small bowel loops with air-fluid levels are characteristic of ileus or obstruction. In paralytic ileus, gas is typically distributed throughout the small and large bowel, often without a distinct transition point. If a mechanical obstruction were present, imaging might show a clear transition point and collapsed bowel distal to the obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEnhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) Society Guidelines for Colorectal Surgery (2018) recommend early mobilization, judicious fluid management, and avoidance of opioids to minimize post-operative ileus, with nasogastric decompression reserved for symptomatic patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Insertion of wide bore nasogastric tube | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Insertion of narrow bore nasogastric tube | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Administration of intravenous cyclizine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Administration of metoclopramide | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Arrange a laparotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) This patient is likely to have a paralytic ileus and the administration of anti emetic drugs in this** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
