  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fulminant UC colectomy? Think end ileostomy, always.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is an end ileostomy. A subtotal colectomy involves the removal of the majority of the colon, leaving the terminal ileum as the most appropriate segment for fecal diversion. An end stoma is fashioned when the distal bowel is either resected or oversewn, as is the case with the rectal stump in this procedure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn fulminant ulcerative colitis requiring emergency surgery, a subtotal colectomy is performed, removing the entire colon up to the rectosigmoid junction. The ileum, being the most distal part of the small intestine, is then brought through the abdominal wall to create a stoma. An end ileostomy is the definitive diversion in this scenario, allowing for the complete diversion of the fecal stream while the rectal stump is either oversewn or stapled closed, often with a plan for future restorative proctocolectomy or proctectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (End colostomy): Incorrect. A subtotal colectomy removes the colon, so there is no colon remaining to fashion a colostomy.\nOption B (Loop colostomy): Incorrect. Similar to an end colostomy, the colon is resected, making a colostomy impossible.\nOption D (Loop ileostomy): Incorrect. While an ileostomy is correct, a loop ileostomy is typically a temporary diverting stoma, often used to protect a distal anastomosis (e.g., after an IPAA). For the primary stoma after a subtotal colectomy for fulminant UC, an end ileostomy is the most common and definitive choice.\nOption E (End jejunostomy): Incorrect. The jejunum is too proximal in the small intestine. An ileostomy is preferred for fecal diversion due to its more distal location, which maximizes fluid and nutrient absorption.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | End Stoma | Loop Stoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Configuration | Single opening, distal bowel resected/closed | Two openings (proximal/distal) from one loop |\n| Purpose | Permanent diversion or temporary with distal closure | Temporary diversion, often for anastomotic protection |\n| Effluent | Continuous, often more liquid (ileostomy) | Variable, depending on bowel segment |\n| Reversal | Requires re-anastomosis | Easier reversal, often intra-abdominal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Subtotal colectomy for fulminant UC = end ileostomy.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after resecting the colon from the ileocecal valve to the rectosigmoid junction, the terminal ileum is brought through a trephine in the right lower quadrant. It is then everted and matured to form a spouted end ileostomy. The rectal stump is typically oversewn or stapled closed and left in the pelvis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASCRS Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Surgical Management of Ulcerative Colitis (2020) recommend subtotal colectomy with end ileostomy as the preferred emergency procedure for fulminant colitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | End colostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Loop colostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | End ileostomy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Loop ileostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | End jejunostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) A sub total colectomy involves the removal of the entire right, transverse, left and part of the sig** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
