  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 FAP's reach extends beyond the colon; the duodenum is its next most common target.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Duodenal polyps. These are the most frequently encountered extra-colonic manifestation in patients with Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP), often reaching 100% prevalence with long-term follow-up.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuodenal polyps, particularly in the periampullary region, are a hallmark of FAP and carry a significant risk of malignant transformation, with duodenal cancer incidence ranging from 4-10%. This necessitates regular endoscopic surveillance (EGD with side-viewing endoscope) to detect and manage these lesions, preventing a potentially fatal outcome even after colectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gastric fundal polyps) (Incorrect): While common, occurring in about 50% of FAP patients, they are less frequent than duodenal polyps and generally have a lower malignant potential.\nOption B (Trichilemmomas) (Incorrect): These are benign skin tumors, but not a common or defining extra-colonic lesion of FAP. They are more associated with Cowden syndrome.\nOption D (Fibrocystic disease of the breast) (Incorrect): This is a common benign breast condition in the general population and is not specifically linked as a common extra-colonic manifestation of FAP.\nOption E (Skull osteomas) (Incorrect): Skull osteomas are characteristic of Gardner's syndrome, which is a phenotypic variant of FAP. While present, they are not the *commonest* extra-colonic lesion overall compared to duodenal polyps.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| FAP Extra-Colonic Manifestation | Prevalence | Clinical Significance |\n| :------------------------------ | :--------- | :-------------------- |\n| Duodenal Polyps                 | Up to 100% | High risk of malignancy (4-10% cancer) |\n| Gastric Fundal Polyps           | ~50%       | Generally benign, low malignant potential |\n| Desmoid Tumors                  | 10-20%     | Significant morbidity/mortality, difficult to treat |\n| Skull Osteomas                  | Gardner's variant | Benign, indicator of FAP variant |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: In FAP, always look for duodenal polyps; they are the most common extra-colonic lesion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopic visualization during an EGD would reveal multiple sessile or pedunculated polyps in the duodenum, especially concentrated in the periampullary region. Biopsies would confirm adenomatous changes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Genetic Testing and Management of Hereditary Gastrointestinal Cancer Syndromes (2015). It recommends upper endoscopy surveillance for FAP patients starting in their late teens or early 20s.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastric fundal polyps | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Trichilemmomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Duodenal polyps | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Fibrocystic disease of the breast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Skull osteomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Duodenal polyps occur in up to 100% of patients with FAP if follow up is continued for long enough. ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
