  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fix the trochanter, save the head, get them walking instead!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS) because intertrochanteric fractures are extracapsular, meaning the blood supply to the femoral head is typically preserved. DHS provides stable compression and allows for early mobilization, which is crucial for this active 60-year-old patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntertrochanteric fractures occur between the greater and lesser trochanters, outside the joint capsule. This location ensures the integrity of the medial femoral circumflex artery, which is vital for femoral head vascularity. A Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS) or a cephalomedullary nail (e.g., Gamma nail) is the gold standard for these fractures. The DHS allows controlled collapse and impaction at the fracture site, promoting healing through compression while providing stable fixation. This approach facilitates early weight-bearing and rehabilitation, minimizing complications associated with prolonged immobility in an active patient like the one described.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cemented hemiarthroplasty) (Incorrect): Hemiarthroplasty is typically reserved for displaced femoral neck fractures, especially in older, less active patients, where the blood supply to the femoral head is compromised. It is not indicated for intertrochanteric fractures where the femoral head is viable.\nOption B (Total hip replacement) (Incorrect): Total hip replacement is an extensive procedure usually reserved for displaced femoral neck fractures in active patients, failed internal fixation, or pre-existing severe hip arthritis. It is an overtreatment for a primary intertrochanteric fracture.\nOption D (Percutaneous pinning) (Incorrect): Percutaneous pinning offers less stability and compression compared to a DHS or cephalomedullary nail for intertrochanteric fractures. It is more commonly used for non-displaced femoral neck fractures or specific stable fracture patterns.\nOption E (Leg traction) (Incorrect): Leg traction is an outdated method for hip fracture management. It is associated with prolonged bed rest, increased complications (e.g., DVT, pneumonia, pressure ulcers), and does not provide definitive fixation, making it unsuitable for an active patient.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type | Location | Blood Supply to Femoral Head | Typical Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Femoral Neck (Intracapsular) | Within joint capsule | Often compromised | Hemiarthroplasty (older/less active) or THA (younger/active) for displaced; Percutaneous pinning for non-displaced |\n| Intertrochanteric (Extracapsular) | Between greater and lesser trochanters | Usually intact | Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS) or Cephalomedullary Nail |\n| Subtrochanteric | Below lesser trochanter | Usually intact | Cephalomedullary Nail (preferred) or Plate/Screws |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intertrochanteric fractures = extracapsular = preserved blood supply = internal fixation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, an intertrochanteric fracture appears as a break in the bone between the greater and lesser trochanters, often with comminution. Intraoperatively, a DHS involves placing a lag screw into the femoral head and neck, which then slides within a side plate fixed to the femoral shaft, allowing for controlled impaction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Hip Fractures in Older Adults (2020). Recommends internal fixation (DHS or intramedullary nail) for stable and unstable intertrochanteric fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cemented hemiarthroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Total hip replacement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dynamic hip screw | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Percutaneous pinning | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Leg traction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The blood supply to the femoral head may be intact and the fracture should heal with compression typ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
