  "question": "A 34-year old woman undergoes ultrasound examination of a breast cyst. Which of the following feature on ultrasound is consistent with this diagnosis? Select ONE answer only.",
  "options": {
    "A": "Irregular wall",
    "B": "Smooth anterior border",
    "C": "Black hypoechoic centres without internal echoes",
    "D": "Blood vessels running through them",
    "E": "Pulsatile."
  },
  "answer": "C) Cysts have typical features of hypoechoic centres, smooth walls and sharp edges. Ultrasound has a sensitivity of 75% and specificity of 97% in the diagnosis of breast cancer and is used as an adjunct to mammography in patients over 35. In patients under 35 it is often the primary radiological modality as the breasts are too dense for accurate mammographic interpretation.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Black, smooth, and echo-free: the simple cyst's ultrasound decree!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. A simple breast cyst on ultrasound is characterized by its anechoic (black) center, indicating fluid, and the absence of internal echoes, confirming its simple fluid-filled nature. These features are pathognomonic for a benign cyst.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSimple breast cysts are fluid-filled sacs that appear anechoic (black) on ultrasound because sound waves pass through the fluid without reflection, resulting in no internal echoes. The walls are typically thin and smooth, and there is often posterior acoustic enhancement due to the unimpeded transmission of sound through the fluid. This distinct appearance allows for confident diagnosis and differentiation from solid masses, which would exhibit internal echoes and varying degrees of vascularity. Ultrasound is a crucial modality for characterizing breast lesions, especially in younger women with dense breast tissue where mammography may be less sensitive.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Irregular wall is a suspicious feature, often indicative of a solid mass or a complicated cyst, and raises concern for malignancy.\nOption B (Incorrect): While simple cysts do have smooth walls, 'smooth anterior border' alone is not as specific or comprehensive a defining feature as the internal anechoic nature and lack of internal echoes. Malignant lesions can sometimes have smooth anterior borders but irregular posterior or internal features.\nOption D (Incorrect): Blood vessels running through a lesion indicate vascularity, which is characteristic of solid masses, particularly malignant ones, and not simple cysts which are avascular.\nOption E (Incorrect): Pulsatility suggests a vascular structure, such as an artery or an aneurysm, not a simple fluid-filled breast cyst.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Simple Cyst | Complicated Cyst | Solid Mass (Benign/Malignant) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Internal Echoes** | None (anechoic) | Low-level internal echoes, septations | Present, variable echogenicity |\n| **Wall** | Thin, smooth | Thin/thick, smooth/irregular | Variable, often irregular/spiculated (malignant) |\n| **Posterior Enhancement** | Present | Variable, often present | Variable, often shadowing (malignant) |\n| **Vascularity** | Absent | Absent or minimal | Present, often prominent (malignant) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Simple cysts are anechoic, avascular, and have smooth walls with posterior enhancement.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a simple breast cyst appears as a well-circumscribed, anechoic (black) lesion with a thin, imperceptible wall, no internal echoes, and often demonstrates posterior acoustic enhancement (a bright area behind the cyst).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACR BI-RADS Atlas 5th Edition (2013). This guideline provides standardized terminology and reporting for breast imaging, classifying simple cysts as BI-RADS 2 (benign finding).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Irregular wall | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Smooth anterior border | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Black hypoechoic centres without internal echoes | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Blood vessels running through them | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Pulsatile. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Cysts have typical features of hypoechoic centres, smooth walls and sharp edges. Ultrasound has a se** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
