  "answer": "A) Axillary clearance is divided into 3 levels: Level I: Lateral to pectoralis minor Level II: Upto medial border of pectoralis minor Level III: Beyond medial border of pectoralis minor.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pectoralis minor: the key to axillary node navigation.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A because Level II axillary clearance is precisely defined by its anatomical relationship to the pectoralis minor muscle. This level involves removing lymph nodes located deep to the pectoralis minor, extending the dissection up to its medial border.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAxillary lymph node dissection is a fundamental procedure in breast cancer management, and its extent is categorized into three levels based on the pectoralis minor muscle. This muscle serves as a crucial anatomical landmark. Level I nodes are found lateral and inferior to the pectoralis minor, Level II nodes are located deep (posterior) to the muscle, and Level III nodes are medial and superior to it. Therefore, clearing 'up to the medial border of pectoralis minor' accurately describes the extent of a Level II dissection, ensuring appropriate oncologic clearance of the central axillary compartment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Above pectoralis minor\" is vague and does not precisely define the boundary for Level II clearance, which is specifically the medial border.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Below pectoralis minor\" generally refers to Level I clearance, which is lateral and inferior to the muscle, not Level II.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"To the outer border of the first rib\" describes an extensive Level III or even supraclavicular dissection, far beyond the scope of a standard Level II clearance.\nOption E (Incorrect): \"Up to the medial border of pectoralis major\" is incorrect; the pectoralis minor muscle is the definitive anatomical landmark for classifying axillary lymph node levels, not the pectoralis major.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Axillary Level | Anatomical Location Relative to Pectoralis Minor |\n|---|---|\n| Level I | Lateral and inferior to pectoralis minor |\n| Level II | Deep (posterior) to pectoralis minor, up to its medial border |\n| Level III | Medial and superior to pectoralis minor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pectoralis minor: your compass for axillary levels.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after retracting the pectoralis major, the pectoralis minor muscle is identified. Level II clearance involves dissecting the lymph nodes situated deep to this muscle, meticulously clearing the tissue up to its medial border to ensure all central axillary nodes are removed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024). These guidelines provide detailed recommendations on the indications and extent of axillary lymph node dissection, emphasizing the importance of accurate staging and appropriate surgical management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Up to the medial border of pectoralis minor | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Above pectoralis minor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Below pectoralis minor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | To the outer border of the first rib | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Up to the medial border of pectoralis major. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Axillary clearance is divided into 3 levels: Level I: Lateral to pectoralis minor Level II: Upto med** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
