  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pheo: The 3 Ps of paroxysmal panic!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation of paroxysmal hypertension (190/110), severe headaches, and palpitations, especially when precipitated by exercise and overeating, is the classic triad for a catecholamine-secreting tumor. This clinical picture strongly points to Phaeochromocytoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhaeochromocytomas are rare neuroendocrine tumors arising from chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla or sympathetic paraganglia, leading to excessive catecholamine release (epinephrine, norepinephrine). This surge causes the characteristic symptoms of paroxysmal hypertension, palpitations, and severe headaches, often accompanied by sweating and anxiety. The 'rule of 10s' (10% bilateral, 10% malignant, 10% extra-adrenal) is a key feature. Pre-operative alpha-blockade followed by beta-blockade is critical to prevent a hypertensive crisis during surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cushing syndrome) (Incorrect): Caused by excess cortisol, leading to central obesity, moon facies, striae, and sustained hypertension, not typically paroxysmal catecholamine-driven symptoms.\nOption B (Gastrinoma) (Incorrect): A gastrin-producing tumor causing Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, characterized by severe peptic ulcer disease and diarrhea, not hypertension or palpitations.\nOption C (Neuroblastoma) (Incorrect): Primarily a malignant tumor of the sympathetic nervous system in children, presenting differently with an abdominal mass, bone pain, and periorbital ecchymosis, not the classic adult paroxysmal triad.\nOption E (Zollinger-Ellison syndrome.) (Incorrect): This is caused by a gastrinoma, leading to severe peptic ulcer disease and diarrhea, unrelated to the patient's hypertensive crisis and palpitations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Hormones | Classic Symptoms | Hypertension Pattern |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Phaeochromocytoma | Catecholamines (Epi, NE) | Palpitations, Headaches, Sweating (PHE), Anxiety | Paroxysmal or sustained |\n| Cushing Syndrome | Cortisol | Central obesity, Moon facies, Striae, Muscle weakness | Sustained |\n| Primary Hyperaldosteronism | Aldosterone | Hypokalemia, Muscle weakness, Polyuria | Sustained, often resistant |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think PHE (Palpitations, Headaches, Episodic sweating) for Pheo.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging typically involves CT or MRI of the abdomen to localize the adrenal or extra-adrenal tumor. Intraoperatively, careful handling of the tumor is crucial to prevent catecholamine release, and blood pressure must be meticulously managed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglioma (2014) recommends biochemical testing for diagnosis and imaging for localization.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cushing syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gastrinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Phaeochromocytoma | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Zollinger-Ellison syndrome. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Phaeochromocytomas are rare catecholamine-producing tumours which\narise from sympathetic paraganglia** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
