  "answer": "D) Lobular carcinoma is the second most common type of breast cancer\nbut can be mammographically occult. Both a fixed lump on clinical\nexamination and an irregular mass on imaging suggests malignancy\nrather than a benign lesion. A radial scar is most typically diagnosed on\nmammographic screening and usually impalpable.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lobular carcinoma: stealthy on mammogram, aggressive in tissue.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Lobular Carcinoma. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the clinical presentation of a painless fixed lump and an irregular mass on ultrasound, coupled with a mammographically occult finding, which is a classic characteristic of invasive lobular carcinoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInvasive lobular carcinoma (ILC) is notorious for its infiltrative growth pattern, where tumor cells invade in single-file strands without forming a significant desmoplastic reaction. This often leads to a lack of a distinct mass on mammography, making it 'mammographically occult.' However, this infiltrative nature causes architectural distortion and a palpable, fixed, irregular lump due to invasion into surrounding tissues, which is well-visualized as an irregular mass on ultrasound.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Benign Phyllodes) (Incorrect): While phyllodes tumors can be irregular, they are typically fast-growing and often present as a mobile, palpable mass. A fixed lump and mammographically occult nature point away from a benign lesion given the high suspicion for malignancy.\nOption B (Fibroadenoma) (Incorrect): Fibroadenomas are typically mobile, rubbery, well-circumscribed masses, and are usually visible on mammogram. The description of a 'fixed lump' and 'irregular mass' contradicts the typical presentation of a fibroadenoma.\nOption C (Intraductal Carcinoma) (Incorrect): Intraductal carcinoma (DCIS) is a non-invasive cancer often detected as microcalcifications on mammography, or sometimes as a mass. However, a fixed, irregular mass that is mammographically occult is more characteristic of an invasive carcinoma like lobular carcinoma.\nOption E (Radial Scar) (Incorrect): A radial scar is a benign lesion, often impalpable, and typically identified as a stellate lesion on mammography. It does not fit the description of a palpable, fixed, irregular mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Invasive Lobular Carcinoma | Fibroadenoma | DCIS (mass-forming) | Radial Scar |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Palpation** | Fixed, irregular lump | Mobile, rubbery, well-defined | Variable, can be mass | Often impalpable |\n| **Mammogram** | Often occult, architectural distortion | Well-circumscribed mass | Microcalcifications, mass | Stellate lesion, no central mass |\n| **Ultrasound** | Irregular, ill-defined mass, shadowing | Oval, well-circumscribed, homogeneous | Hypoechoic mass, microcalcifications | Spiculated lesion |\n| **Key Feature** | Infiltrative, single file cells | Benign, common in young women | Pre-invasive, confined to ducts | Benign, mimic of cancer |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mammographically occult, fixed, irregular mass = suspect lobular carcinoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, invasive lobular carcinoma often appears as an irregular, ill-defined hypoechoic mass with posterior shadowing or architectural distortion, reflecting its infiltrative growth. Its lack of a strong desmoplastic reaction often makes it difficult to detect on mammography, leading to its 'occult' nature.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (v1.2024) recommend comprehensive imaging and biopsy for suspicious breast masses, emphasizing the role of ultrasound in evaluating mammographically occult lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Benign Phyllodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fibroadenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intraductal Carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lobular Carcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Radial Scar. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Lobular carcinoma is the second most common type of breast cancer\nbut can be mammographically occult** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
