  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the brain goes bonkers from low sugar, think insulinoma!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Insulinoma because the patient presents with classic symptoms of hypoglycemia (light-headedness, disorientation, mood swings, aggression) that resolve with food, coupled with a documented low blood sugar of 1.8 mmol/l during an attack. This clinical picture perfectly aligns with Whipple's triad, which is pathognomonic for insulinoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInsulinomas are rare neuroendocrine tumors originating from pancreatic beta cells, leading to autonomous overproduction of insulin. This excess insulin causes profound hypoglycemia, which manifests as neuroglycopenic symptoms like confusion, mood changes, and aggression, as well as adrenergic symptoms like light-headedness. The resolution of symptoms with food (glucose intake) and documented low blood sugar during an episode are the key components of Whipple's triad, making insulinoma the most likely diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gastrinoma) (Incorrect): Gastrinomas cause Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, characterized by severe peptic ulcer disease due to excessive gastrin production, not hypoglycemia.\nOption B (Glucagonoma) (Incorrect): Glucagonomas produce excess glucagon, leading to hyperglycemia, necrolytic migratory erythema, and weight loss, not hypoglycemia.\nOption D (Phaeochromocytoma) (Incorrect): Phaeochromocytomas are adrenal tumors secreting catecholamines, causing paroxysmal hypertension, palpitations, sweating, and anxiety, not hypoglycemia.\nOption E (Zollinger-Ellison syndrome.) (Incorrect): Zollinger-Ellison syndrome is caused by a gastrinoma and presents with severe peptic ulceration and diarrhea, not symptoms of hypoglycemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Hormone Produced | Key Symptoms | Blood Glucose Effect |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Insulinoma | Insulin | Hypoglycemia (Whipple's triad), neuroglycopenic symptoms | Low |\n| Gastrinoma | Gastrin | Severe peptic ulcers, diarrhea (Zollinger-Ellison syndrome) | Normal |\n| Glucagonoma | Glucagon | Hyperglycemia, necrolytic migratory erythema, weight loss | High |\n| Phaeochromocytoma | Catecholamines | Paroxysmal hypertension, palpitations, sweating, anxiety | Variable (can cause hyperglycemia) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Whipple's triad + documented low blood sugar = Insulinoma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging for insulinoma often involves endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) for localization, which has high sensitivity for small pancreatic lesions. CT or MRI may also be used. Intraoperatively, careful palpation of the pancreas and intraoperative ultrasound are crucial for identifying these often small and elusive tumors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (ENETS) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Pancreatic Neuroendocrine Neoplasms (2016). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, localization, and management of insulinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastrinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Glucagonoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Insulinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Phaeochromocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Zollinger-Ellison syndrome. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Insulinomas are not common and occur in around 1 in a million of the\npopulation. They arise from ß i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
