  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't rely on X-rays; gallstones are often camera-shy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, 10%. This question tests your knowledge of gallstone composition and their visibility on plain abdominal X-rays, which is a common clinical scenario in surgical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstones are primarily classified into cholesterol stones (about 80%) and pigment stones (about 20%). Cholesterol stones are typically radiolucent because they lack significant calcium content. Pigment stones, particularly black pigment stones, are more likely to contain calcium bilirubinate and calcium carbonate, making them radio-opaque. Only a minority of gallstones, approximately 10-15%, contain enough calcium to be visible on a plain abdominal X-ray, making ultrasound the gold standard for diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): <1% is too low; a small but significant proportion of gallstones are indeed visible on X-ray.\nOption C (Incorrect): 30% is too high; the vast majority of gallstones are radiolucent.\nOption D (Incorrect): 50% is grossly incorrect; if half were visible, X-ray would be a much more primary diagnostic tool.\nOption E (Incorrect): >75% is far too high; this would imply most gallstones are calcified, which is not true.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gallstone Type | Primary Composition | Radiopacity on X-ray |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cholesterol | Cholesterol monohydrate | Radiolucent (80-90%) |\n| Black Pigment | Calcium bilirubinate, calcium phosphate | Radio-opaque (50-75%) |\n| Brown Pigment | Calcium bilirubinate, fatty acid soaps | Radiolucent (often infection-related) |\n| Mixed | Variable (cholesterol core, calcified rim) | Variable (often partially radio-opaque) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Only 1 in 10 gallstones show on X-ray; ultrasound is the real MVP.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a plain abdominal X-ray, calcified gallstones appear as radio-opaque, often faceted or laminated, opacities in the right upper quadrant, as described in the question. However, ultrasound is the imaging modality of choice for suspected cholelithiasis, demonstrating hyperechoic foci within the gallbladder lumen with characteristic posterior acoustic shadowing. CT scans can also detect gallstones, especially calcified ones, but are less sensitive for purely cholesterol stones than ultrasound.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Gallstone Disease (2016). This guideline recommends abdominal ultrasound as the primary imaging modality for the diagnosis of gallstones due to its high sensitivity and specificity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | <1% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 10% | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 30% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | >75%. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Around 10-15% of gallstones can be seen on plain imaging. These of** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
