  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When gallstones meet cancer, adenocarcinoma is usually the culprit.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Adenocarcinoma. This is the most common type of gallbladder malignancy, accounting for approximately 90% of all gallbladder cancers, and is strongly associated with chronic inflammation from gallstones, as suggested by the patient's history.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallbladder adenocarcinoma is the fifth most common gastrointestinal malignancy. Its strong association with cholelithiasis (gallstones) and chronic cholecystitis is a key diagnostic clue, with about 85% of cases having coexisting gallstones. The insidious onset of symptoms, often mimicking benign gallbladder disease (RUQ pain, nausea, vomiting), frequently leads to late diagnosis. Weight loss is a concerning sign of malignancy, indicating advanced disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Haemangioma) (Incorrect): Haemangiomas are benign vascular tumors rarely found in the gallbladder and are not a common type of gallbladder malignancy.\nOption C (Sarcoma) (Incorrect): Sarcomas are extremely rare mesenchymal tumors of the gallbladder, accounting for less than 1% of all gallbladder cancers.\nOption D (Squamous cell carcinoma) (Incorrect): While squamous cell carcinoma can occur in the gallbladder, it is far less common than adenocarcinoma, accounting for only about 10% of cases.\nOption E (Transitional cell carcinoma.) (Incorrect): Transitional cell carcinoma is a type of cancer that typically arises in the urinary tract (bladder, ureters, renal pelvis) and is not found in the gallbladder.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gallbladder Tumor Type | Prevalence/Characteristics | Association with Gallstones |\n|---|---|---|\n| Adenocarcinoma | ~90% of all gallbladder cancers, most common | Strong (85%) |\n| Squamous Cell Carcinoma | ~10% of all gallbladder cancers, rare | Possible |\n| Adenoma | Benign polyp, potential for malignant transformation | Possible |\n| Cholesterol Polyp | Benign, very common, no malignant potential | Yes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gallstones + Gallbladder tumor = Adenocarcinoma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a gallbladder mass may appear as a focal wall thickening, a polypoid lesion, or a mass replacing the gallbladder lumen. CT scan can further delineate the extent of the tumor, invasion into adjacent organs, and metastatic spread. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder may appear thickened, indurated, or have a visible mass, often with regional lymphadenopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (e.g., NCCN Guidelines Version 2.2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of gallbladder cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adenocarcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Haemangioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Sarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Squamous cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Transitional cell carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Around 85% of tumours of the gallbladder are associated with gallstones. The initial features can be** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
