  "answer": "B) Calot’s triangle, also known as the cystohepatic or hepatobiliary triangle\nis an anatomic space which is of great relevance when performing a\nlaparoscopic cholecystectomy. It is bounded by the common hepatic\nduct medially, cystic duct laterally and liver superiorly, and is used to\nlocate the cystic artery which runs within. Anomalies of the gallbladder or\nbiliary tree are found within 10% of subjects and are important during\nsurgery. They include:A long cystic duct travelling alongside the\ncommon hepatic duct. The gallbladder opening directly into the side of\nthe common bile duct i.e. the cystic duct is absent. Variation in the blood\nvessel arrangement supplying the gallbladder e.g. in 25% of people the\nright hepatic artery crosses in front of the common hepatic duct instead\nof behind it.",
