  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, cholangiogram it out; 10% of patients have a surprise!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, indicating that approximately 10% of patients have anomalies of the gallbladder and biliary tree. This proportion highlights the significant prevalence of anatomical variations that a surgeon must be prepared for during cholecystectomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCalot’s triangle is a critical anatomical landmark, bounded by the common hepatic duct medially, cystic duct laterally, and liver superiorly, housing the cystic artery. Recognizing and safely dissecting this area is paramount to prevent iatrogenic injury. Anomalies, present in about 10% of individuals, include variations like a long cystic duct running parallel to the common hepatic duct, an absent cystic duct where the gallbladder directly enters the common bile duct, or aberrant vascular anatomy such as the right hepatic artery crossing anterior to the common hepatic duct. Awareness of these variations is crucial for safe dissection and identification of structures, minimizing the risk of bile duct or vascular injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): <1% is far too low; biliary anomalies are more common than this.\nOption C (Incorrect): 40% is an overestimation of the prevalence of significant biliary anomalies.\nOption D (Incorrect): 75% is a significant overestimation; most patients have typical anatomy.\nOption E (Incorrect): >90% is a gross overestimation; the vast majority of patients do not have major biliary anomalies.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Anomaly Type | Description | Surgical Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| Long Cystic Duct | Travels alongside Common Hepatic Duct (CHD) | Risk of misidentification and injury to CHD |\n| Absent Cystic Duct | Gallbladder opens directly into Common Bile Duct (CBD) | Increased risk of direct CBD injury |\n| Aberrant Cystic Artery | Originates from different vessels or has unusual course | Risk of uncontrolled hemorrhage or injury to other vessels |\n| Right Hepatic Artery Variation | Crosses anterior to CHD (instead of posterior) | Risk of accidental ligation/transection during dissection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always anticipate anatomical variations in Calot's triangle; 10% of patients have them.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, aberrant anatomy in Calot's triangle may manifest as an unusually short or long cystic duct, a cystic duct entering the common bile duct at an atypical angle, or an unexpected course of the cystic artery or other vascular structures. Cholangiography (intraoperative or preoperative MRCP) can be invaluable to delineate the biliary tree and identify anomalies, especially when dissection is difficult or anatomy is unclear, helping to prevent bile duct injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Safe Cholecystectomy Task Force Guidelines (2019): Recommends critical view of safety (CVS) and emphasizes awareness of anatomical variations to prevent bile duct injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | <1% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 10% | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 40% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 75% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | >90% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Calot’s triangle, also known as the cystohepatic or hepatobiliary triangle\nis an anatomic space whic** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
