  "answer": "A) A ranula is a large mucus-containing cyst in the floor of the mouth. Ranula is Latin for a small frog, as the swelling is said to resemble the „belly of a frog‟. A ranula develops on one side of the floor of the mouth, and slowly enlarges to form a bluish fluctuant swelling beneath the sublingual mucosa that transilluminates. The cysts have thin walls and easily rupture. Treatment is by surgical excision, with care to avoid injury to the submandibular duct or lingual nerve.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Frog belly under tongue? Think ranula, not amphibian.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis is Ranula. The patient's presentation of a soft, tense, translucent swelling \"underneath her tongue\" in the floor of the mouth, with slow enlargement, is a classic description of a ranula.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA ranula is a pseudocyst resulting from extravasation or retention of mucin from the sublingual gland, or less commonly, the submandibular gland. Its characteristic bluish, translucent appearance and location in the floor of the mouth, often displacing the tongue, are key diagnostic features. The term 'ranula' itself comes from Latin for 'little frog,' describing its appearance. Treatment typically involves surgical excision or marsupialization.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Mucous retention cyst): Incorrect. While also mucus-filled, these are typically smaller, arise from minor salivary glands, and are less common in the floor of the mouth as a large swelling. A ranula is specifically associated with the sublingual gland.\nOption C (Pyogenic granuloma): Incorrect. This is a vascular, inflammatory lesion, typically red, friable, and often ulcerated, not a translucent, soft swelling.\nOption D (Stomatitis): Incorrect. Stomatitis refers to generalized inflammation of the oral mucosa, not a localized, discrete cystic swelling.\nOption E (Sublingual dermoid cyst): Incorrect. Dermoid cysts in the floor of the mouth are typically midline, feel doughy or rubbery, and do not transilluminate. They are congenital and contain ectodermal elements (hair, sebaceous material), not just mucus.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Ranula                                       | Mucous Retention Cyst (Mucocele)           | Sublingual Dermoid Cyst                      |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- |\n| **Origin**          | Sublingual gland (extravasation/retention)  | Minor salivary glands (retention)          | Congenital (trapped ectodermal elements)     |\n| **Location**        | Floor of mouth, unilateral, \"under tongue\"   | Lips, buccal mucosa, palate (minor glands) | Floor of mouth, often midline                |\n| **Appearance**      | Soft, tense, translucent, bluish, fluctuant  | Small, firm, bluish/clear, dome-shaped     | Doughy/rubbery, non-translucent, skin-colored |\n| **Transillumination** | Positive                                     | Positive (if superficial)                  | Negative                                     |\n| **Contents**        | Mucus                                        | Mucus                                      | Keratin, hair, sebaceous material            |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Translucent floor of mouth swelling = ranula until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or MRI, a ranula appears as a well-defined, unilocular, anechoic or hypointense (T1) / hyperintense (T2) cystic lesion in the floor of the mouth, often displacing the tongue superiorly. Intraoperatively, it is a thin-walled, bluish, fluid-filled sac.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific widely cited society guideline exists for ranula management; treatment is primarily surgical (excision or marsupialization).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ranula | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Mucous retention cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pyogenic granuloma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Stomatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sublingual dermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A ranula is a large mucus-containing cyst in the floor of the mouth. Ranula is Latin for a small fro** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
