  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fix the trochanter, replace the neck – know your hip fracture anatomy!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS) because intertrochanteric fractures are extracapsular, meaning the blood supply to the femoral head is typically preserved. This allows for biological healing with stable compression, which a DHS effectively provides, making it the optimal management for this type of fracture in a fit patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntertrochanteric fractures occur between the greater and lesser trochanters, outside the joint capsule. This anatomical location ensures the blood supply to the femoral head remains intact, making internal fixation a viable and preferred option. A Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS) works by allowing controlled collapse and impaction at the fracture site, promoting secondary bone healing through compression, which is crucial for these fractures. It provides stable fixation while permitting early mobilization, reducing complications associated with prolonged bed rest.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cemented hemiarthroplasty) (Incorrect): Hemiarthroplasty is typically reserved for displaced femoral neck fractures where the blood supply to the femoral head is compromised, leading to a high risk of avascular necrosis. It is overtreatment for an intertrochanteric fracture with intact blood supply.\nOption B (Total hip replacement) (Incorrect): Total hip replacement is also an arthroplasty procedure, generally indicated for severe osteoarthritis, avascular necrosis, or complex femoral neck fractures in active patients. It is an overly aggressive and unnecessary intervention for a treatable intertrochanteric fracture.\nOption D (Percutaneous pinning) (Incorrect): While percutaneous pinning can be used for certain stable fractures, it generally provides less robust fixation and compression compared to a DHS or intramedullary nail for intertrochanteric fractures, which are often comminuted and require strong mechanical stability.\nOption E (Leg traction) (Incorrect): Leg traction is a temporary measure for pain control and alignment, not a definitive treatment for hip fractures. Prolonged traction leads to significant complications like DVT, pressure sores, and pneumonia, especially in elderly patients.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Intertrochanteric Fracture | Femoral Neck Fracture |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------------- |\n| Location | Extracapsular (between trochanters) | Intracapsular (proximal to intertrochanteric line) |\n| Blood Supply | Femoral head blood supply usually intact | Femoral head blood supply often compromised |\n| Healing Potential | Good, often heals with internal fixation | High risk of non-union/AVN, especially displaced |\n| Typical Management | Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS), Intramedullary Nail (IMN) | Hemiarthroplasty, Total Hip Arthroplasty (THA), ORIF (young) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intertrochanteric fractures heal with compression; femoral neck fractures often need replacement.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn X-ray of an intertrochanteric fracture shows a break in the bone between the greater and lesser trochanters, often with comminution. Post-operatively, a DHS appears as a large lag screw inserted into the femoral head, connected to a side plate fixed to the femoral shaft with cortical screws, allowing for controlled impaction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) 2020 Clinical Practice Guideline for Management of Hip Fractures in Older Adults recommends internal fixation (e.g., DHS or IMN) for stable intertrochanteric fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cemented hemiarthroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Total hip replacement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dynamic hip screw | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Percutaneous pinning | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Leg traction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The blood supply to the femoral head may be intact and the fracture should heal with compression typ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
