  "id": 205920,
  "question": "A 17 year old lady presents with right iliac fossa pain and diagnosed as having acute appendicitis. You take her to theatre to perform a laparoscopic appendicectomy. During the procedure the scrub nurse distracts you and you inadvertently avulse the appendicular artery. The ensuing haemorrhage is likely to be supplied directly from which vessel?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Inferior mesenteric artery",
    "B": "Superior mesenteric artery",
    "C": "Ileo-colic artery",
    "D": "Internal iliac artery",
    "E": "None of the above"
  },
  "answer": "C) The appendicular artery is a branch of the ileocolic artery.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Know your anatomy; distractions can be costly!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Ileo-colic artery. This is because the appendicular artery, which supplies the appendix, is a direct branch of the ileocolic artery. Understanding the precise arterial anatomy is crucial for safe surgical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe appendicular artery is a terminal branch of the ileocolic artery. The ileocolic artery itself is the most inferior branch of the superior mesenteric artery (SMA). During an appendicectomy, identifying and ligating the appendicular artery is a critical step to prevent hemorrhage. Its location within the mesoappendix, originating from the ileocolic artery, makes it vulnerable to injury if not carefully isolated and secured. A thorough understanding of this specific vascular anatomy ensures proper hemostasis and prevents complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The inferior mesenteric artery supplies the hindgut (distal transverse colon to upper rectum) and does not directly supply the appendix.\nOption B (Incorrect): The superior mesenteric artery is the *origin* of the ileocolic artery, but the question asks for the *direct* vessel supplying the appendicular artery, which is the ileocolic artery itself.\nOption D (Incorrect): The internal iliac artery supplies pelvic organs, gluteal region, and perineum, not the appendix.\nOption E (Incorrect): Option C is the correct answer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery | Primary Supply Region | Key Branches (relevant) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Superior Mesenteric Artery (SMA) | Midgut (distal duodenum to distal transverse colon) | Ileocolic, Right Colic, Middle Colic, Jejunal, Ileal |\n| Inferior Mesenteric Artery (IMA) | Hindgut (distal transverse colon to upper rectum) | Left Colic, Sigmoidal, Superior Rectal |\n| Ileo-colic Artery | Terminal ileum, cecum, appendix, ascending colon | Appendicular, Anterior/Posterior Cecal, Ileal, Colic |\n| Internal Iliac Artery | Pelvic organs, gluteal region, perineum | Superior/Inferior Gluteal, Obturator, Uterine |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The appendicular artery is a direct branch of the ileocolic artery, from the SMA.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the appendicular artery is typically found within the mesoappendix, a fold of peritoneum connecting the appendix to the mesentery of the terminal ileum. It can be visualized as a distinct pulsatile vessel that needs to be carefully ligated or clipped before transecting the appendix. Avulsion would result in brisk arterial bleeding from the stump of the appendicular artery, requiring immediate control, often by identifying the source within the mesoappendix and ligating it, or tracing it back to its origin from the ileocolic artery if the avulsion is extensive.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020): These guidelines emphasize meticulous surgical technique and anatomical knowledge to prevent complications during appendicectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Inferior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Superior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ileo-colic artery | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Internal iliac artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The appendicular artery is a branch of the ileocolic artery.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
