  "id": 205924,
  "question": "A 63 year old man who smokes heavily presents with dyspepsia. He is tested and found to be positive for helicobacter pylori infection. One evening he has an episode of haematemesis and collapses. What is the most likely vessel to be responsible?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Portal vein",
    "B": "Short gastric arteries",
    "C": "Superior mesenteric artery",
    "D": "Gastroduodenal artery",
    "E": "None of the above"
  },
  "answer": "D) He is most likely to have a posteriorly sited duodenal ulcer. These can invade the gastroduodenal artery and present with major bleeding. Although gastric ulcers may invade vessels they do not tend to produce major bleeding of this nature.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bleeding duodenal ulcers + GDA = surgical emergency.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Gastroduodenal artery. This patient's presentation of dyspepsia, H. pylori infection, and massive hematemesis with collapse strongly suggests a bleeding peptic ulcer, specifically a posteriorly sited duodenal ulcer which commonly erodes into the gastroduodenal artery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPeptic ulcer disease, often exacerbated by H. pylori and smoking, can lead to ulceration of the duodenal wall. The duodenum's posterior wall is in close proximity to the gastroduodenal artery (GDA), a major branch of the common hepatic artery. When a duodenal ulcer, particularly one located posteriorly in the first part of the duodenum, erodes deeply, it can penetrate the arterial wall of the GDA, leading to a catastrophic hemorrhage. This arterial bleed is characterized by massive, pulsatile bleeding, often presenting as hematemesis and hypovolemic shock, as described in the patient's collapse.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Portal vein) (Incorrect): The portal vein is a large venous structure that carries blood from the GI tract to the liver. While portal hypertension can lead to variceal bleeding, a duodenal ulcer does not typically erode into the portal vein, and venous bleeding would generally be less pulsatile and less immediately life-threatening than arterial bleeding from the GDA.\nOption B (Short gastric arteries) (Incorrect): The short gastric arteries supply the fundus of the stomach. While gastric ulcers can bleed, they typically involve the left or right gastric arteries or the short gastric arteries, and while significant, a duodenal ulcer eroding into the gastroduodenal artery is a classic cause of massive, life-threatening hemorrhage.\nOption C (Superior mesenteric artery) (Incorrect): The superior mesenteric artery supplies the midgut (from the distal duodenum to the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon). It is not anatomically positioned to be directly eroded by a duodenal ulcer in the first part of the duodenum. Bleeding from the SMA would typically present as lower GI bleeding or mesenteric ischemia, not upper GI hematemesis from a duodenal ulcer.\nOption E (None of the above) (Incorrect): Option D is the most likely and anatomically correct vessel responsible for this presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of UGI Bleed | Most Likely Vessel(s) Involved | Clinical Presentation | Management Principle |\n|:-------------------|:--------------------------------|:----------------------|:---------------------|\n| Duodenal Ulcer     | Gastroduodenal Artery           | Massive hematemesis, shock | Endoscopic hemostasis, surgical ligation if refractory |\n| Gastric Ulcer      | Left/Right Gastric Arteries, Short Gastric Arteries | Hematemesis, melena | Endoscopic hemostasis, surgical repair |\n| Esophageal Varices | Esophageal Veins                | Massive hematemesis, liver disease | Band ligation, TIPS, pharmacotherapy |\n| Mallory-Weiss Tear | Mucosal arterioles/venules      | Hematemesis after retching | Supportive, endoscopic clips if persistent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Posterior duodenal ulcers erode the gastroduodenal artery, causing massive hemorrhage.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal a deep ulcer in the posterior wall of the duodenal bulb, often with a visible vessel (Forrest classification IIa or Ib) or active pulsatile bleeding (Forrest Ia). Intraoperatively, after a duodenotomy, the bleeding point would be identified and ligated, often requiring a suture ligation of the gastroduodenal artery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients with Acute Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021) recommends early endoscopy for diagnosis and hemostasis in patients with acute UGI bleeding, and H. pylori eradication for ulcer prevention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Portal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Short gastric arteries | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Superior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Gastroduodenal artery | ✅ Correct |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) He is most likely to have a posteriorly sited duodenal ulcer. These can invade the gastroduodenal ar** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
