  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anuria post-transplant? Think clot, then act fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Renal artery thrombosis. In a patient who suddenly becomes anuric shortly after a renal transplant, especially after initial good function, arterial thrombosis is a critical and highly time-sensitive diagnosis that must be excluded immediately, assuming a blocked catheter has been ruled out.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRenal artery thrombosis is a catastrophic complication occurring in 0.5-5% of renal transplants, often within the first 24-48 hours. It typically results from technical issues during anastomosis, hypercoagulable states, or severe hypotension. The sudden cessation of blood flow to the graft leads to rapid ischemia and infarction of the kidney, manifesting as abrupt anuria. This acute event requires immediate surgical exploration and thrombectomy to salvage the graft, as prolonged ischemia leads to irreversible damage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Renal artery stenosis typically presents later (weeks to months) with hypertension and/or progressive graft dysfunction, not sudden anuria.\nOption B (Incorrect): Renal vein thrombosis also causes sudden anuria but is often accompanied by graft swelling, tenderness, and hematuria. While serious, arterial thrombosis is often considered the most immediate and devastating cause of anuria in this acute setting, leading to rapid graft loss.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hyperacute rejection occurs minutes to hours post-reperfusion, usually in the operating room, due to pre-formed antibodies, leading to immediate graft failure. The patient had good urine output initially.\nOption E (Incorrect): Acute rejection typically manifests days to weeks post-transplant with rising creatinine, fever, and graft tenderness, not sudden anuria immediately post-op.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Early Post-Transplant Anuria | Onset | Key Features | Management |\n| :----------------------------------- | :---- | :----------- | :--------- |\n| Blocked Catheter                     | Immediate | No urine output, bladder distension | Catheter flush/replacement |\n| Renal Artery Thrombosis              | Sudden (hours) | Abrupt anuria, often no other signs initially, severe graft ischemia | Urgent surgical exploration/thrombectomy |\n| Renal Vein Thrombosis                | Sudden (hours-days) | Abrupt anuria, graft swelling, tenderness, hematuria | Anticoagulation, thrombectomy (if viable) |\n| Hyperacute Rejection                 | Minutes-Hours (intra-op) | Immediate graft mottling, failure to perfuse | Graft nephrectomy |\n| Acute Tubular Necrosis (ATN)         | Hours-Days | Oliguria/anuria, often delayed graft function, normal Doppler | Supportive care, dialysis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sudden anuria post-transplant = rule out blocked catheter, then urgent Doppler for arterial thrombosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn Doppler ultrasound, renal artery thrombosis would show absent blood flow signals within the renal artery and parenchyma. Intraoperatively, the graft would appear dusky, mottled, and flaccid, with no palpable pulsations in the renal artery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO (Kidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Care of Kidney Transplant Recipients (2009, updated 2020). It recommends prompt investigation of anuria/oliguria post-transplant, including Doppler ultrasound to assess vascular patency.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Renal artery stenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Renal vein thrombosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Renal artery thrombosis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Hyperacute rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Acute rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Sudden loss of urine output is most commonly due to a blocked catheter. However, if this is excluded** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
