  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the CBD is clear, but the liver's backed up, think nodes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Peri hilar lymphadenopathy. In a patient with a history of gastric carcinoma and new-onset jaundice 8 months post-distal gastrectomy, the most concerning and likely explanation for intrahepatic duct dilatation with a normal common bile duct is extrinsic compression from metastatic peri-hilar lymph nodes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastric carcinoma, even after curative resection, has a significant risk of recurrence and metastatic spread. The lymphatic drainage of the stomach includes nodes that can involve the porta hepatis. Metastatic lymphadenopathy in the peri-hilar region can compress the common hepatic duct or its branches, leading to upstream intrahepatic biliary dilatation without affecting the common bile duct distally. This presentation of painless obstructive jaundice is highly suspicious for recurrent or metastatic disease in a patient with a prior malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Fitz-Hugh Curtis syndrome is perihepatitis, typically associated with pelvic inflammatory disease, and does not cause obstructive jaundice or intrahepatic duct dilatation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Gilbert's syndrome is a benign, inherited disorder causing unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia due to impaired bilirubin conjugation, not obstructive jaundice with biliary dilatation.\nOption D (Incorrect): Mirizzi syndrome involves obstruction of the common hepatic duct by an impacted gallstone in the cystic duct or gallbladder neck. This would typically cause dilatation of the common bile duct, which is stated as normal in the question.\nOption E (Incorrect): Gallstones causing obstructive jaundice (choledocholithiasis) would typically be located in the common bile duct and cause dilatation of the common bile duct, which is explicitly stated as normal in this patient.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | CBD Caliber | Intrahepatic Ducts | Jaundice Type | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Peri-hilar Lymphadenopathy (Metastatic) | Normal | Dilated | Obstructive | Extrinsic compression of hepatic ducts |\n| Choledocholithiasis | Dilated | Dilated | Obstructive | Stone in CBD |\n| Mirizzi Syndrome | Dilated (proximal to obstruction) | Dilated | Obstructive | Gallstone compressing CHD |\n| Pancreatic Head Mass | Dilated | Dilated | Obstructive | Mass compressing distal CBD |\n| Gilbert's Syndrome | Normal | Normal | Unconjugated | Impaired bilirubin conjugation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-gastrectomy jaundice with normal CBD and dilated IH ducts = metastatic nodes until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, one would expect to see enlarged lymph nodes in the porta hepatis or peri-hilar region, encasing or compressing the common hepatic duct or its main branches, leading to the observed intrahepatic biliary dilatation. The common bile duct distal to this compression would appear normal in caliber.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., Version 2.2023). These guidelines recommend surveillance for recurrence, and new-onset jaundice in a post-gastrectomy patient warrants prompt investigation for metastatic disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Peri hilar lymphadenopathy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Fitz- Hugh Curtis syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gilberts syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mirizzi syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Gallstones | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Unfortunately metastatic disease is the most likely event. Peri hilar lymphadenopathy would be a com** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
