  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Calcitonin is the MTC compass for recurrence.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Calcitonin. This question accurately identifies the primary tumor marker used for surveillance of medullary thyroid cancer (MTC) recurrence, which is crucial for timely detection and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMedullary thyroid cancer originates from the parafollicular C-cells of the thyroid gland, which are responsible for producing calcitonin. Therefore, elevated serum calcitonin levels are a highly specific and sensitive marker for the presence of MTC. Following a total thyroidectomy for MTC, calcitonin levels should ideally become undetectable. Any subsequent rise in calcitonin indicates persistent or recurrent disease, making it the cornerstone of post-operative surveillance for this specific thyroid malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Free T3) (Incorrect): Free T3 is a measure of thyroid hormone function and is not a tumor marker for any thyroid cancer.\nOption B (Thyroglobulin) (Incorrect): Thyroglobulin is a tumor marker for differentiated thyroid cancers (papillary and follicular), not medullary thyroid cancer.\nOption D (Free T4) (Incorrect): Free T4 is a measure of thyroid hormone function and is not a tumor marker for any thyroid cancer.\nOption E (Thyroid stimulating hormone) (Incorrect): TSH is a pituitary hormone that stimulates thyroid function and growth; it is not a tumor marker for MTC, although it is monitored in patients on thyroid hormone replacement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Thyroid Cancer Type | Primary Tumor Marker(s) |\n|--------------------|-------------------------|\n| Medullary Thyroid Cancer | Calcitonin, CEA |\n| Papillary Thyroid Cancer | Thyroglobulin |\n| Follicular Thyroid Cancer | Thyroglobulin |\n| Anaplastic Thyroid Cancer | No specific tumor marker |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MTC = C-cells = Calcitonin. Simple.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., ultrasound, CT, MRI), recurrent MTC may appear as suspicious lymph nodes in the central or lateral neck compartments, or as local recurrence in the thyroid bed. Intraoperatively, MTC often presents as a firm, nodular mass, and careful central and lateral neck dissection is critical due to its propensity for early lymphatic spread.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Patients with Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015, updated 2023). These guidelines recommend routine measurement of serum calcitonin for MTC surveillance.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Free T3 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thyroglobulin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Calcitonin | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Free T4 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Thyroid stimulating hormone | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Calcitonin is clinically utilised to screen for medullary thyroid cancer recurrence. Thyroid functio** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
