  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the clavicle steps up, the ACJ is messed up!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Acromioclavicular joint dislocation. The classic presentation of a direct fall onto the shoulder, combined with a prominent clavicle and step deformity, is pathognomonic for ACJ disruption.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe acromioclavicular joint is stabilized by the acromioclavicular ligaments and the coracoclavicular ligaments (conoid and trapezoid). A direct fall onto the acromion drives the scapula inferiorly, while the clavicle remains superior, leading to disruption of these ligaments. This results in the characteristic \"step deformity\" where the clavicle appears prominent superiorly due to its detachment from the acromion, and the loss of normal shoulder contour.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Glenohumeral dislocation) (Incorrect): This typically presents with a loss of the normal rounded contour of the shoulder (squared-off appearance) and severe pain, often with the arm held in internal rotation, but not a prominent clavicle or step deformity.\nOption C (Sternoclavicular dislocation) (Incorrect): While also involving the clavicle, this injury presents with prominence or depression at the medial end of the clavicle, near the sternum, not laterally at the shoulder.\nOption D (Supraspinatus tear) (Incorrect): Rotator cuff tears are uncommon in young athletes from acute trauma and do not cause a step deformity or prominent clavicle. They typically present with pain and weakness, especially with abduction.\nOption E (Infraspinatus tear) (Incorrect): Similar to supraspinatus tears, infraspinatus tears are rare in this demographic and mechanism, and do not cause the described step deformity or clavicular prominence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | ACJ Dislocation | Glenohumeral Dislocation | Sternoclavicular Dislocation | Rotator Cuff Tear (Acute) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Mechanism | Direct fall onto acromion | Indirect force (e.g., abduction/external rotation) | Direct blow to medial clavicle or indirect force | Acute overload, rare in young athletes |\n| Key Sign | Prominent clavicle, step deformity, pain at ACJ | Squared-off shoulder, loss of deltoid contour | Prominence/depression at medial clavicle | Pain with movement, weakness, no deformity |\n| Age Group | Any, common in athletes | Any, common in athletes | Any, less common | Older adults (degenerative), rare acute in young |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prominent clavicle + step deformity = ACJ dislocation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn AP shoulder X-ray, often with bilateral views and/or weighted views, will show superior displacement of the clavicle relative to the acromion and widening of the ACJ space.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Acromioclavicular Joint Injuries (2014). It recommends clinical evaluation and plain radiographs for diagnosis and classification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acromioclavicular joint dislocation | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Glenohumeral dislocation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Sternoclavicular dislocation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Supraspinatus tear | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Infra spinatus tear | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Acromioclavicular joint (ACJ) dislocation normally occurs secondary to direct injury to the superior** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
