  "answer": "E) Acute rejection occurs between a week and 100 days following transplantation. The severity of rejection can be assessed by taking a needle biopsy of the allograft. Acute rejection is recognised by the presence of tubulitis and intimal arteritis. The Banff System can be used to classify acute rejection into mild, moderate, and severe. The category depends on the intensity of the infiltrate, and the severity of tubulitis and intimal arteritis. In this case there was also necrosis of muscle cells which means it is grade 3 and therefore severe acute rejection.",
  "chapter": "Review",
