  "question": "You are referred a patient by their general practitioner (GP). They underwent a renal transplantation 3 years ago. The patient has been complaining of headaches and dizzy spells. The GP reports an abrupt onset of unexplained hypertension. Select the most likely complication for this case.",
  "options": {
    "A": "Acute graft rejection",
    "B": "Chronic graft rejection",
    "C": "Delayed graft function",
    "D": "Lymphocele",
    "E": "Renal artery stenosis"
  },
  "answer": "E) Renal artery stenosis complicates 2–10% of renal transplants. It may be confirmed on Doppler ultrasound. It can be managed using percutaneous angioplasty and stent placement.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-transplant hypertension? Check the plumbing, not just the pump!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Renal artery stenosis. This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the abrupt onset of unexplained hypertension, headaches, and dizzy spells occurring 3 years post-renal transplantation, which are classic signs of renovascular hypertension.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRenal artery stenosis (RAS) is a common vascular complication following renal transplantation, affecting 2-10% of patients. It typically develops months to years post-transplant due to technical issues at anastomosis, intimal hyperplasia, or atherosclerosis. The stenosis leads to reduced blood flow to the allograft, activating the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system, resulting in severe, often refractory hypertension, which manifests clinically as headaches and dizzy spells. Diagnosis is often confirmed by Doppler ultrasound, and treatment involves percutaneous angioplasty with or without stenting.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Acute graft rejection) (Incorrect): Acute rejection typically presents with fever, graft tenderness, and rising creatinine, usually within the first year, not primarily with abrupt hypertension and headaches 3 years out.\nOption B (Chronic graft rejection) (Incorrect): Chronic rejection leads to a slow, progressive decline in graft function and hypertension, but the 'abrupt onset' described points away from this gradual process and towards a more acute vascular event like RAS.\nOption C (Delayed graft function) (Incorrect): Delayed graft function occurs immediately post-transplant, characterized by the need for dialysis in the first week, and is not a complication presenting 3 years later.\nOption D (Lymphocele) (Incorrect): A lymphocele is a collection of lymphatic fluid that can cause local compression symptoms (pain, swelling, ureteral obstruction) but does not typically cause systemic hypertension, headaches, and dizzy spells.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Typical Onset | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Renal Artery Stenosis | Months to years post-transplant | Abrupt hypertension, headaches, dizzy spells, graft dysfunction |\n| Acute Graft Rejection | Days to months post-transplant | Fever, graft tenderness, rising creatinine, oliguria |\n| Chronic Graft Rejection | Months to years post-transplant | Gradual decline in graft function, proteinuria, hypertension |\n| Delayed Graft Function | Immediately post-transplant | Need for dialysis in first week, poor urine output |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Abrupt post-transplant hypertension = think renal artery stenosis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDoppler ultrasound is the initial diagnostic modality of choice for renal artery stenosis, showing high-velocity flow and turbulence at the anastomotic site. Angiography provides definitive diagnosis and allows for intervention.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO Clinical Practice Guideline for the Care of Kidney Transplant Recipients (2009) recommends screening for renovascular complications in patients with new-onset or worsening hypertension post-transplant.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute graft rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chronic graft rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Delayed graft function | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphocele | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Renal artery stenosis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Renal artery stenosis complicates 2–10% of renal transplants. It may be confirmed on Doppler ultraso** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
  "verified_answer": "E"
