  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cloacal tubercle at 5 weeks: Genitalia's first peek!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E because at 5 weeks of gestation, the cloacal tubercle, which is the precursor to external genitalia, becomes evident. This marks a key developmental milestone for the urogenital system during this period.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuring the fifth week of embryonic development, significant morphological changes occur. The embryo becomes less C-shaped, and the head grows disproportionately large. Limb buds, which appeared in week 4, begin to differentiate into their distinct segments, and the nose starts to form as a flattened projection. The appearance of the cloacal tubercle is a crucial indicator of this stage, signifying the initial formation of the external genitalia before sexual differentiation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): At 5 weeks, the embryo is less markedly curved than in earlier stages (e.g., 4 weeks), where it is distinctly C-shaped.\nOption B (Incorrect): The elevations forming the rudiments of the auricula (ear) typically become visible around 6-7 weeks, not 5 weeks.\nOption C (Incorrect): The primitive segments (somites) number about 30 around the end of the 4th week, not typically at 5 weeks when many have already differentiated.\nOption D (Incorrect): While limb buds appear as projections earlier, at 5 weeks, the limbs are beginning to differentiate into segments, not just appearing as simple oval flattened projections.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gestational Age | Key Developmental Milestones |\n| :-------------- | :--------------------------- |\n| 4 Weeks         | C-shaped embryo, limb buds appear, neural tube closes, ~30 somites |\n| 5 Weeks         | Less curved, large head, limb differentiation, cloacal tubercle evident |\n| 6 Weeks         | Auricular hillocks, digital rays in hands, distinct eyes, heart chambers |\n| 7 Weeks         | Notches between digital rays, eyelids forming, distinct external ears |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early embryonic milestones are key for dating and anomaly detection.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn transvaginal ultrasound, a 5-week embryo would typically show a gestational sac with a yolk sac and a fetal pole measuring approximately 2-4 mm, often with visible cardiac activity. Gross examination of an aborted 5-week embryo would reveal a small, C-shaped structure with developing limb buds and a disproportionately large head, consistent with the described features.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 188 (2017) - Early Pregnancy Loss. This guideline discusses the diagnosis and management of early pregnancy loss, which often involves understanding embryonic development.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The embryo is markedly curved on itself | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The elevations that form the rudiments of the auricula are visible | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The primitive segments number about 30 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The limbs appear as oval flattened projections | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | The cloacal tubercle is evident | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) During the fifth week the embryo is less curved and the head is relatively large. Differentiation of** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
