  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Five days post-transplant and failing? Think accelerated, not just acute!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Accelerated rejection. This diagnosis is most likely given the timing of the patient's symptoms (5 days post-transplant) and the deterioration of renal function, which aligns with the typical presentation of accelerated rejection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAccelerated rejection typically manifests within the first week following renal transplantation, often between days 2 and 7. It is primarily a cell-mediated immune response, involving both delayed-type hypersensitivity and cytotoxic T-lymphocyte mechanisms. This form of rejection is characterized by a rapid decline in graft function and is generally considered irreversible, often leading to graft loss. The patient's discomfort and worsening renal function at 5 days post-op are classic indicators for this specific type of rejection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Acute rejection) (Incorrect): Acute rejection typically occurs weeks to months after transplantation, although it can occur earlier. Five days is a bit too early for the most common presentation of acute rejection, making accelerated rejection a more precise fit for the timeline.\nOption C (Chronic rejection) (Incorrect): Chronic rejection develops over months to years, characterized by a slow, progressive decline in graft function. Five days post-transplant is far too early for chronic rejection.\nOption D (Hyperacute rejection) (Incorrect): Hyperacute rejection occurs minutes to hours after transplantation due to pre-formed antibodies. The patient's symptoms appearing 5 days later rule out hyperacute rejection.\nOption E (Not undergoing rejection) (Incorrect): The patient's discomfort and, more importantly, the deterioration of renal function strongly suggest a pathological process, making rejection a highly probable diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Rejection | Timing | Mechanism | Prognosis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hyperacute | Minutes to hours | Pre-formed antibodies | Irreversible, immediate graft loss |\n| Accelerated | Days 2-7 | Cell-mediated (DTH, CTL) | Often irreversible, rapid graft loss |\n| Acute | Weeks to months | Cell-mediated, humoral | Often reversible with treatment |\n| Chronic | Months to years | Multifactorial (immune & non-immune) | Irreversible, slow graft loss |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rejection timing is key: minutes (hyperacute), days (accelerated), weeks (acute), months (chronic).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, findings might include increased renal transplant size, increased cortical echogenicity, and elevated resistive indices in the renal arteries, though these are non-specific. A biopsy would be definitive, showing interstitial inflammation and tubulitis, characteristic of cell-mediated rejection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Kidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes (KDIGO) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Care of Kidney Transplant Recipients (2009) provides comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis and management of allograft rejection, including the classification and treatment strategies for different types of rejection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Accelerated rejection | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Acute rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Chronic rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hyperacute rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Not undergoing rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Accelerated rejection develops up to a week after transplantation. It is generally due to cell-media** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
