  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, patch it out, especially in the frail!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Excision of ulcer. This approach is favored due to the patient's advanced age (85 years) and significant comorbidities (COAD, angina), which necessitate a less invasive surgical intervention to minimize operative stress and optimize recovery. The high lesser curve location also makes local excision feasible and safe.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFor an elderly patient with significant comorbidities presenting with a perforated gastric ulcer, the primary goal is to close the perforation with minimal physiological insult. Excision of the ulcer, followed by primary repair (often with an omental patch, e.g., Graham patch), is a conservative yet definitive approach. This minimizes operative time, anesthetic exposure, blood loss, and the overall surgical trauma compared to resectional procedures. The high lesser curve location is amenable to local excision without compromising major gastric vasculature or requiring extensive mobilization, further supporting this choice.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Total gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This is an extremely aggressive and morbid procedure, typically reserved for extensive gastric malignancy or intractable benign disease. It is wholly inappropriate for a perforated benign ulcer in an elderly, comorbid patient.\nOption B (Partial gastrectomy) (Incorrect): While less extensive than a total gastrectomy, a partial gastrectomy is still a major resectional procedure with significant morbidity and mortality risks. It is excessive for a simple perforation in a high-risk patient, especially when local repair is feasible.\nOption C (Oesophago-gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This is an even more extensive and morbid procedure than total gastrectomy, involving resection of the distal esophagus and stomach. It is completely unwarranted for a perforated gastric ulcer.\nOption E (Repeat endoscopy) (Incorrect): A perforated viscus requires immediate surgical intervention to close the defect and prevent ongoing peritonitis and sepsis. Endoscopy is diagnostic and therapeutic for uncomplicated ulcers or bleeding, but not for perforation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Factor | Conservative Repair (Excision/Graham Patch) | Partial Gastrectomy | Total Gastrectomy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Patient Status** | Unstable, elderly, high comorbidity | Stable, low comorbidity | Stable, low comorbidity |\n| **Ulcer Type** | Benign perforation | Benign (recurrent, complicated) or malignant | Extensive malignancy |\n| **Surgical Morbidity** | Low | Moderate to High | Very High |\n| **Operative Time** | Short | Moderate | Long |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: In high-risk patients with perforated peptic ulcers, prioritize conservative repair over resection.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, one would identify free air and purulent fluid in the peritoneal cavity. The perforated gastric ulcer would be visible as a defect, typically 0.5-2 cm, on the lesser curve of the stomach, often with inflamed, edematous edges. The surrounding gastric tissue would be inspected for viability and to ensure no major vessels are compromised by the excision.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Perforated Peptic Ulcer (2020) recommends simple closure (Graham patch) as the gold standard for perforated peptic ulcers, especially in unstable or high-risk patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Partial gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Oesophago-gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excision of ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Repeat endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) This patient’s age and significant co-morbidities suggest conservative\nsurgery (shorter anaesthetic,** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
