  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Half a cord, half a story: ipsi motor, contra pain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Brown-Sequard syndrome. This syndrome is characterized by ipsilateral motor paralysis and loss of proprioception/vibration, along with contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation, which perfectly matches the patient's presentation of unilateral motor loss and contralateral pain/temperature loss.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBrown-Sequard syndrome results from a hemisection of the spinal cord. The ipsilateral motor deficits are due to damage to the lateral corticospinal tract, which decussates in the medulla. Ipsilateral loss of proprioception and vibration is due to damage to the dorsal columns, which ascend ipsilaterally before decussating in the medulla. The contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation is due to damage to the spinothalamic tract, which decussates at or near the level of entry into the spinal cord and then ascends contralaterally. This unique pattern of deficits is a hallmark of this syndrome, which generally carries the best prognosis among spinal cord injuries.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Anterior cord syndrome involves bilateral loss of motor function, pain, and temperature sensation below the level of injury, while proprioception and vibration sensation are preserved.\nOption C (Incorrect): Central cord syndrome typically presents with greater motor weakness in the upper extremities than the lower extremities, often with variable sensory loss, and is common in hyperextension injuries.\nOption D (Incorrect): Neurologic shock is a distributive shock characterized by hypotension and bradycardia due to loss of sympathetic tone, not a specific pattern of sensory or motor deficits.\nOption E (Incorrect): Posterior cord syndrome is rare and involves loss of proprioception and vibration sensation below the level of injury, with preserved motor function and pain/temperature sensation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Motor Deficit | Pain/Temp Sensation | Proprioception/Vibration |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Brown-Sequard | Ipsilateral loss | Contralateral loss | Ipsilateral loss |\n| Anterior Cord | Bilateral loss | Bilateral loss | Preserved |\n| Central Cord | UE > LE weakness | Variable loss | Variable loss |\n| Posterior Cord | Preserved | Preserved | Bilateral loss |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ipsilateral motor, contralateral pain/temp = Brown-Sequard.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (CT/MRI) would show C4/C5 dislocation and potentially cord edema or contusion. Intraoperatively, a hemitransection of the spinal cord might be observed, though often the injury is a contusion or compression rather than a complete anatomical transection. The question does not contain an image.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAANS/CNS Guidelines for the Management of Acute Cervical Spine and Spinal Cord Injuries (2013)\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anterior cord syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Brown-Sequard syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Central cord syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Neurologic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Posterior cord syndrome. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Brown-Sequard syndrome is caused by complete cord hemitransection.\nOn examination patients have loss** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
