  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the foot drops, check the fibula's top!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies a common fibular nerve injury. The classic presentation of foot drop (difficulty dorsiflexing the ankle) combined with sensory deficits in the dorsum of the foot, following trauma to the lateral knee, is pathognomonic for common fibular nerve damage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe common fibular (peroneal) nerve is particularly vulnerable to injury as it wraps superficially around the neck of the fibula. Trauma to this area, such as a direct blow or fracture, can compress or stretch the nerve. Its motor branches supply the muscles responsible for ankle dorsiflexion (tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus, extensor hallucis longus) and foot eversion (fibularis longus and brevis). Sensory innervation includes the lateral aspect of the leg and the dorsum of the foot via its superficial and deep fibular nerve branches, respectively. The patient's symptoms perfectly align with these deficits.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The femoral nerve innervates the quadriceps femoris (knee extension) and provides sensation to the anterior thigh and medial leg via the saphenous nerve. Its injury would present with inability to extend the knee and different sensory deficits.\nOption B (Incorrect): The saphenous nerve is a purely sensory branch of the femoral nerve, supplying the medial aspect of the leg and foot. It has no motor function and its sensory distribution does not match the patient's symptoms.\nOption D (Incorrect): The obturator nerve primarily innervates the adductor muscles of the thigh and provides sensation to a small area on the medial thigh. Its injury would manifest as difficulty with hip adduction and different sensory loss.\nOption E (Incorrect): The sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the body, giving rise to both the tibial and common fibular nerves. While a common fibular nerve injury is a component of a sciatic nerve injury, a full sciatic nerve lesion would cause much more extensive motor and sensory deficits, including hamstring weakness and more widespread foot/leg paralysis and sensory loss, which is not described here. The localized trauma points to a more distal, specific nerve injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Key Motor Function | Key Sensory Distribution |\n|---|---|---|\n| Common Fibular (Peroneal) | Ankle dorsiflexion, foot eversion | Lateral leg, dorsum of foot |\n| Tibial | Ankle plantarflexion, foot inversion | Sole of foot |\n| Femoral | Knee extension, hip flexion | Anterior thigh, medial leg |\n| Obturator | Hip adduction | Medial thigh |\n| Sciatic | Hamstring flexion, all lower leg/foot muscles | Posterior thigh, entire lower leg/foot (except medial leg) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Foot drop + lateral knee trauma = common fibular nerve injury until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (X-ray, CT), one might look for a fibular head or neck fracture, which is a common cause of common fibular nerve injury. Intraoperatively, the nerve may appear contused, stretched, or even transected at its vulnerable point around the fibular neck.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Peripheral Nerve Injuries (2016) recommends early diagnosis and appropriate management, including surgical exploration for specific injury types.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Femoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Saphenous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Common fibular nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Obturator nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sciatic nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The common fibular nerve is frequently injured as it passes around the neck of the fibula. Classical** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
