  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a post-splenectomy fever get under your diaphragm!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Subphrenic abscess. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's presentation of left-sided chest and abdominal pain, fever, decreased air entry, dullness to percussion, and left upper quadrant tenderness 7 days post-splenectomy, which are classic signs of an infected collection in the subphrenic space.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenectomy often leaves a raw surface and potential space for fluid collection. Post-operative hematomas are common in the subphrenic space, and these can readily become infected, leading to an abscess. The diaphragm's proximity explains the referred pain to the chest, pleuritic pain (worse on inspiration), and sympathetic pleural effusion, manifesting as decreased air entry and dullness at the left lung base. The systemic inflammatory response causes the fever and localized tenderness.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Overwhelming post-splenectomy sepsis) (Incorrect): While a severe complication, OPSI typically presents with more diffuse signs of systemic shock, rapid deterioration, and less localized findings like dullness and decreased air entry, which point to a specific collection.\nOption B (Pancreatic fistula) (Incorrect): A pancreatic fistula would typically present with abdominal pain, elevated drain amylase, and potentially a fluid collection, but less commonly with significant pleuritic chest pain, decreased air entry, and dullness to percussion unless it's a very large collection irritating the diaphragm.\nOption C (Portal vein thrombosis) (Incorrect): Portal vein thrombosis post-splenectomy usually presents with abdominal pain, ascites, and potentially signs of portal hypertension, but not typically with pleuritic chest pain, fever, and localized signs of a subphrenic collection.\nOption D (Splenosis) (Incorrect): Splenosis refers to autotransplantation of splenic tissue, which is usually asymptomatic and a late complication, not an acute infectious process presenting 7 days post-op.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Presentation | Diagnosis | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Subphrenic Abscess | Fever, LUQ pain, pleuritic chest pain, decreased breath sounds, dullness, leukocytosis | CT scan with IV contrast | Percutaneous drainage, antibiotics |\n| OPSI | Rapid onset fever, chills, hypotension, DIC, multi-organ failure | Blood cultures, clinical picture | Aggressive antibiotics, supportive care, ICU |\n| Pancreatic Fistula | Abdominal pain, fluid collection, high drain amylase | CT scan, drain fluid analysis | NPO, TPN, somatostatin analogs, drainage |\n| Portal Vein Thrombosis | Abdominal pain, ascites, GI bleeding, splenomegaly (if chronic) | Doppler ultrasound, CT venography | Anticoagulation, thrombolysis (rarely) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fever + LUQ pain + pleurisy post-splenectomy = Subphrenic abscess until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast would reveal a well-defined, often rim-enhancing fluid collection in the left subphrenic space, potentially with gas bubbles, and often an associated left pleural effusion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Intra-abdominal Infections (2017) recommends percutaneous drainage as the first-line treatment for well-localized intra-abdominal abscesses, including subphrenic abscesses, when technically feasible.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Overwhelming post-splenectomy sepsis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pancreatic fistula | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Portal vein thrombosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Splenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Subphrenic abscess | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Post-operative haematomas are common post-splenectomy. They may collect in the subphrenic space, and** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
