  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't saphenize the saphenous nerve!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the saphenous nerve. Its close anatomical relationship with the great saphenous vein makes it highly vulnerable to injury during varicose vein surgery, leading to the described pain and paraesthesia in the medial leg and foot.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe saphenous nerve is a purely sensory branch of the femoral nerve. It accompanies the great saphenous vein (GSV) down the medial aspect of the leg, providing cutaneous innervation to the skin of the medial leg and foot. During procedures like saphenectomy or endovenous ablation of the GSV, the nerve can be directly transected, stretched, or entrapped by scar tissue, resulting in neuropathic pain, numbness, or paraesthesia in its distribution. This specific distribution of symptoms (medial leg and foot) is pathognomonic for saphenous nerve injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The femoral nerve is a large nerve supplying motor innervation to the anterior thigh muscles and sensory innervation to the anterior thigh. Its injury would cause quadriceps weakness and sensory loss in the anterior thigh, not the medial leg/foot.\nOption C (Incorrect): The common fibular (peroneal) nerve supplies motor innervation to the muscles of the anterior and lateral compartments of the leg (dorsiflexors and evertors) and sensory innervation to the anterolateral leg and dorsum of the foot. Injury typically occurs at the fibular head and causes foot drop and lateral leg numbness.\nOption D (Incorrect): The obturator nerve primarily supplies motor innervation to the adductor muscles of the thigh and a small sensory area on the medial thigh. Its injury would cause adductor weakness and sensory loss in the medial thigh, not the medial leg/foot.\nOption E (Incorrect): The sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the body, supplying motor and sensory innervation to the posterior thigh and all of the leg and foot (via its branches, tibial and common fibular nerves). Injury would result in widespread motor and sensory deficits, far more extensive than described.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Sensory Distribution | Motor Distribution | Common Injury Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Saphenous nerve | Femoral nerve | Medial leg and foot | None (purely sensory) | Varicose vein surgery (GSV) |\n| Common fibular nerve | Sciatic nerve | Anterolateral leg, dorsum of foot | Dorsiflexors, evertors of foot | Trauma to fibular head, prolonged compression |\n| Sural nerve | Tibial & Common fibular | Lateral foot, posterior calf | None (purely sensory) | Lateral ankle surgery, small saphenous vein surgery |\n| Tibial nerve | Sciatic nerve | Sole of foot, posterior calf | Plantarflexors, intrinsic foot muscles | Trauma to popliteal fossa, tarsal tunnel syndrome |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial leg paresthesia post-varicose vein surgery = saphenous nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring saphenectomy or endovenous ablation, the saphenous nerve is often seen running in close proximity, or even adherent, to the great saphenous vein, particularly in the distal thigh and leg. Surgeons must meticulously dissect the vein to avoid nerve traction, transection, or thermal injury during ablation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2022 American Venous Forum (AVF) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Varicose Veins recommends careful nerve identification and preservation during surgical interventions for varicose veins to minimize neurological complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Femoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Saphenous nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Common fibular nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Obturator nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sciatic nerve. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The saphenous nerve enters the adductor canal but leaves the canal without passing through the adduc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
