  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Biconvex bleed, rapid decline: EDH is a surgical emergency!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"Biconvex looking bleeding on CT scan,\" because extradural haematomas are classically lens-shaped due to the dura mater's tight adherence to the skull, preventing spread across suture lines. This distinct radiological appearance is crucial for immediate diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nExtradural haematomas typically arise from arterial bleeding, most commonly from the middle meningeal artery, often associated with a skull fracture. The dura mater is firmly attached to the inner table of the skull, especially at the suture lines, which restricts the haematoma's expansion, forcing it inward and creating its characteristic biconvex or lenticular shape on CT scans. This contrasts sharply with subdural haematomas, which are venous and crescent-shaped, spreading more freely over the brain surface. Early recognition is vital as rapid expansion can lead to a swift rise in intracranial pressure (ICP), compromising cerebral perfusion as per the Monro-Kellie hypothesis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Extradural haematomas are usually associated with a fracture, not an absence of one. While not always present, it's a common finding.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bleeding into the ventricles is an intraventricular haemorrhage, a different type of intracranial bleed, not an extradural haematoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Extradural haematomas do not cross suture lines because the dura is tightly adherent to the cranium at these points, containing the bleed.\nOption E (Incorrect): A crescentic shape of the bleed on CT is characteristic of a subdural haematoma, not an extradural haematoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Extradural Haematoma (EDH) | Subdural Haematoma (SDH) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Shape on CT | Biconvex (lenticular) | Crescentic |\n| Crosses Sutures | No | Yes |\n| Typical Vessel | Middle Meningeal Artery (arterial) | Bridging Veins (venous) |\n| Common Cause | Trauma with skull fracture | Trauma (often minor in elderly) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EDH is biconvex, arterial, and doesn't cross sutures.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an extradural haematoma appears as a hyperdense, biconvex (lens-shaped) collection of blood located between the inner table of the skull and the dura mater. It characteristically does not cross cranial suture lines.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBrain Trauma Foundation (BTF) Guidelines for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury (e.g., 4th Edition, 2016). They recommend prompt recognition and surgical evacuation of EDH causing mass effect.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Absence of a fracture on plain X rays | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Biconvex looking bleeding on CT scan | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Bleeding into the ventricles on CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Bleeding that crosses suture lines | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Crescentic shape of the bleed on CT. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Extradural haematomas are biconvex; do not cross suture lines, as the dura is very adherent to the c** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
