  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the bleed returns, scope again before the knife discerns.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Repeat endoscopy. This patient presents with rebleeding after initial endoscopic management of a duodenal ulcer, but remains hemodynamically stable, making repeat endoscopy the most appropriate next step according to current guidelines.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRepeat endoscopy is the preferred initial management for rebleeding in a hemodynamically stable patient with a peptic ulcer, especially given her significant comorbidities. This approach allows for re-evaluation of the bleeding site and further endoscopic hemostasis, which is less invasive than surgery. If repeat endoscopy fails, then surgical intervention, such as underrunning the ulcer, would be considered, prioritizing the minimum safe procedure due to her poor cardiac history and renal impairment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Total gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This is an overly aggressive and morbid procedure for a bleeding duodenal ulcer, especially in a patient with significant comorbidities, and is not indicated as a primary treatment for rebleeding.\nOption B (Partial gastrectomy) (Incorrect): While less extensive than a total gastrectomy, this is still a major surgical procedure and is not the first-line treatment for rebleeding in a stable patient. It carries significant risks for this patient.\nOption C (Oesophago-gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This is an extremely extensive and morbid procedure typically reserved for esophageal or gastric cancers, not for a bleeding duodenal ulcer.\nOption D (Excision of ulcer) (Incorrect): Direct excision of a duodenal ulcer can be technically challenging and risks duodenal stricture or injury to vital structures. Underrunning the ulcer is a more common surgical approach if endoscopy fails, but surgery is not the initial step for a stable rebleed.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Step | Indication | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Initial Endoscopy | Acute upper GI bleed | Diagnose, risk stratify, and provide hemostasis |\n| Repeat Endoscopy | Rebleeding, hemodynamically stable | Less invasive, allows for further hemostasis, avoids surgery |\n| Surgical Intervention | Failed repeat endoscopy, massive bleed, hemodynamic instability | Definitive control when endoscopic methods are insufficient |\n| Interventional Radiology | Hemodynamic instability, failed endoscopy, high surgical risk | Alternative to surgery, especially for diffuse bleeding or specific vessel embolization |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stable rebleed? Scope it again before you cut.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn repeat endoscopy, one would look for the original ulcer site, evidence of active bleeding (spurting, oozing), or a visible vessel. If surgery were performed, the surgeon would identify the duodenal ulcer and perform an underrunning suture ligation to control the bleeding vessel.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNICE guidelines (June 2012) recommend repeat endoscopy for post-endoscopic rebleeding in stable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Partial gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Oesophago-gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excision of ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Repeat endoscopy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) New NICE guidelines (June 2012) suggest that in the case of post-endoscopic rebleeding, patients sho** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
