  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When medical and scopes fail, cut out the bleed!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Partial gastrectomy. This patient presents with a refractory, actively bleeding benign gastric ulcer despite an 8-week course of omeprazole and failed repeat endoscopic attempts, evidenced by significant blood loss requiring 6 units of transfusion. Surgical intervention is indicated, and partial gastrectomy offers a definitive solution for this persistent problem.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPartial gastrectomy involves the surgical removal of the portion of the stomach containing the ulcer, typically followed by a Billroth I or Billroth II reconstruction. For a benign gastric ulcer that has failed medical and endoscopic management and is actively bleeding, this approach ensures complete excision of the lesion, thereby eliminating the source of hemorrhage and preventing recurrence. The evidence suggests that partial gastrectomy may offer lower morbidity and mortality rates compared to simple ulcer excision for complex or actively bleeding benign ulcers, providing a more robust and definitive treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Total gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This is an overly aggressive and morbid procedure for a known benign gastric ulcer. Total gastrectomy is reserved for extensive malignancies or diffuse gastric pathologies, not a localized benign lesion.\nOption C (Oesophago-gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This involves resection of both the esophagus and stomach, an even more extensive and inappropriate procedure for a benign gastric ulcer.\nOption D (Excision of ulcer) (Incorrect): While it removes the ulcer, simple local excision may be associated with higher recurrence rates or technical difficulties in achieving definitive hemostasis for actively bleeding ulcers. Partial gastrectomy is often preferred for its more definitive nature and potentially lower morbidity/mortality in such cases.\nOption E (Repeat endoscopy) (Incorrect): The patient has already undergone repeat endoscopy which showed an active bleed and required 6 units of blood. This indicates that endoscopic therapy has failed or is insufficient, and further repeat endoscopy without surgical intervention is not the most appropriate definitive treatment for a refractory, actively bleeding ulcer in an unstable patient.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Surgical Option | Indication (Benign Ulcer) | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n| :-------------- | :------------------------ | :--------- | :------------ |\n| Local Excision | Small, non-bleeding, easily accessible ulcers; biopsy | Minimally invasive; preserves gastric volume | Higher recurrence; difficult for active bleed; less definitive |\n| Partial Gastrectomy | Refractory, bleeding, large, or complicated benign ulcers; suspicion of malignancy | Definitive removal; lower recurrence; addresses underlying pathology; potentially lower morbidity/mortality than local excision for complex cases | More invasive than local excision; potential for anastomotic complications; altered gastric physiology |\n| Total Gastrectomy | Extensive malignancy; diffuse gastric disease | Complete removal of stomach | High morbidity/mortality; severe nutritional deficiencies; complex reconstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Refractory bleeding benign gastric ulcer = partial gastrectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal a gastric ulcer on the greater curvature with active bleeding (e.g., spurting, oozing, visible vessel). Intraoperatively, after laparotomy, the stomach would be mobilized, and the ulcer identified by palpation or transillumination. A wedge or distal gastrectomy would be performed to encompass the ulcer, followed by reconstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients with Acute Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021). This guideline recommends surgical intervention for patients with ongoing bleeding despite repeated endoscopic attempts or for those who are hemodynamically unstable despite maximal medical and endoscopic therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Partial gastrectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Oesophago-gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excision of ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Repeat endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) This patient’s ulcer is known to be benign. Despite best medical therapy his ulcer has not healed an** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
