  "answer": "B) The breast lies on the pectoralis major, serratus anterior and external oblique muscles. It is a modified apocrine sweat gland. The mammary gland is mainly supplied by the lateral thoracic artery, by branches that curl around the border of pectoralis major. In addition, there is a blood supply from the internal thoracic artery, intercostal and thoracoacromial arteries. The main lymphatic drainage is to the axillary and infraclavicular nodes in 75% of cases whereas the majority of the medial breast drains to nodes which lie along the internal thoracic artery. The gland contains approximately 15-20 main ducts that open separately on the summit of the nipple. Screening mammograms involve craniocaudal and mediolateral oblique views which are double read by consultant radiologists.",
