  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Breast blood supply: Lateral and Internal Mammary are your main arteries!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B is correct because the breast's primary arterial supply is indeed from the lateral thoracic artery and the internal mammary artery. Understanding this vascular anatomy is fundamental for surgical planning, especially in procedures like mastectomy and reconstructive surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe mammary gland receives a rich blood supply from several sources. The lateral thoracic artery, a branch of the axillary artery, supplies the lateral aspect of the breast, often curling around the border of the pectoralis major muscle. The internal mammary (or internal thoracic) artery, a branch of the subclavian artery, provides perforating branches that supply the medial aspect of the breast. Additionally, intercostal arteries and the thoracoacromial artery contribute to the overall vascularity. This extensive arterial network ensures adequate perfusion to the breast tissue and is critical knowledge for surgeons to minimize complications like flap necrosis during breast reconstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The mammary gland contains approximately 15-20 main lactiferous ducts, not just 15, and they drain separately at the nipple.\nOption C (Incorrect): Screening mammograms typically involve craniocaudal (CC) and mediolateral *oblique* (MLO) views, not a true mediolateral view, to best visualize breast tissue.\nOption D (Incorrect): The breast is a modified *apocrine* sweat gland, not a sebaceous gland.\nOption E (Incorrect): The predominant lymphatic drainage of the breast (approximately 75%) is to the *axillary* and infraclavicular nodes. While the medial breast can drain to internal thoracic nodes, it is not the predominant drainage for the entire gland.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Description |\n|---|---|\n| Gland Type | Modified apocrine sweat gland |\n| Main Arterial Supply | Lateral thoracic artery, Internal mammary artery |\n| Predominant Lymphatic Drainage | Axillary nodes (75%) |\n| Lactiferous Ducts | 15-20 main ducts |\n| Screening Mammography Views | Craniocaudal (CC) and Mediolateral Oblique (MLO) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Master breast vascular and lymphatic anatomy for safe surgical practice.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring a mastectomy, the surgeon meticulously identifies and ligates the perforating branches from the internal mammary artery medially and branches from the lateral thoracic artery laterally. On angiography, the rich vascular network supplying the breast can be clearly visualized, aiding in preoperative planning for complex reconstructions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer Screening and Diagnosis (2023) provide comprehensive recommendations for imaging modalities and interpretation in breast cancer management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Contains 15 main lactiferous ducts that drain separately at the nipple | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Is mainly supplied by the lateral thoracic artery and internal mammary arte | ✅ Correct |\n| C | In this age group is best visualised by a combination of crainiocaudal and  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Is a modified sebaceous gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Predominantly drains to the internal thoracic nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The breast lies on the pectoralis major, serratus anterior and external oblique muscles. It is a mod** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
