  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For a healthy adult's wrist, six weeks is the magic number for mending bones.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 6 weeks. This is the expected healing time for an undisplaced upper limb fracture in a healthy adult, aligning with general orthopedic principles.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFracture healing is a complex biological process involving inflammation, soft callus formation, hard callus formation, and remodeling. For adults, a general rule of thumb is 6-8 weeks for upper limb fractures and 12-16 weeks for lower limb fractures. These times are halved in children due to their higher metabolic rate and greater osteogenic potential. Factors influencing healing include fracture type and site, blood supply, soft tissue interposition, movement at the fracture site, and patient comorbidities like anemia, chronic illness, or steroid use. An undisplaced fracture in a healthy individual typically follows these general timelines.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 1 week is far too short for any significant bone healing to occur, even in children.\nOption B (Incorrect): 3 weeks is generally too short for complete healing of an adult upper limb fracture, though early callus may be visible.\nOption D (Incorrect): 12 weeks is typically the healing time for lower limb fractures in adults, or for more complex/displaced upper limb fractures, not a simple undisplaced distal radius/ulna fracture.\nOption E (Incorrect): 16 weeks is usually reserved for complex lower limb fractures or those with significant complications, not a straightforward upper limb injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type/Location | Adult Healing Time | Child Healing Time |\n|------------------------|--------------------|--------------------|\n| Upper Limb             | 6-8 weeks          | 3-4 weeks          |\n| Lower Limb             | 12-16 weeks        | 6-8 weeks          |\n| Undisplaced            | Faster             | Faster             |\n| Displaced/Comminuted   | Slower             | Slower             |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Upper limb fractures in adults heal in 6-8 weeks; lower limb in 12-16 weeks. Halve for kids.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, an undisplaced distal radius and ulna fracture would show a clear fracture line without significant angulation, translation, or rotation. Follow-up X-rays would demonstrate progressive callus formation and eventual bridging of the fracture gap.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Treatment of Distal Radius Fractures (2020) provides evidence-based recommendations for management, including expected healing and rehabilitation timelines.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1 week | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 3 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 6 weeks | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 12 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 16 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 6 weeks. As a general rule, upper limb fractures in adults take 6–8 weeks to heal, while lower limb ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
