  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Wilms tumor: The kidney's silent, unilateral childhood surprise.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Nephroblastoma. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's age, the presence of a large, unilateral abdominal mass, and its specific location not crossing the midline.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNephroblastoma, also known as Wilms tumor, is the most common renal malignancy in children, typically presenting between 2 and 3 years of age. It originates from embryonic renal cells and classically presents as a firm, smooth, unilateral abdominal mass that does not cross the midline, consistent with its kidney origin. While often found incidentally, it can cause abdominal pain and distension. Diagnosis is primarily via ultrasound and CT, with treatment involving nephrectomy, chemotherapy, and sometimes radiotherapy. Its association with specific genetic anomalies like WT1 gene deletion and conditions such as aniridia further characterizes this tumor.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Hepatoblastoma) (Incorrect): This tumor originates from the liver and typically presents as a right upper quadrant mass, which would not fit the description of a left-sided mass.\nOption B (Lipoma) (Incorrect): While lipomas can occur, a large, symptomatic intra-abdominal mass causing distension and pain in a 3-year-old is highly unlikely to be a simple benign lipoma.\nOption D (Neuroblastoma) (Incorrect): Neuroblastoma, originating from neural crest cells, often presents as an abdominal mass but classically crosses the midline and can have associated calcifications or systemic symptoms, which are not described here.\nOption E (Polycystic kidney) (Incorrect): Polycystic kidney disease typically involves bilateral kidney enlargement due to multiple cysts and is not usually described as a single, large, unilateral mass in this context, although it can be associated with Wilms tumor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Nephroblastoma (Wilms Tumor) | Neuroblastoma | Hepatoblastoma |\n| :---------------- | :--------------------------- | :-------------------------------- | :---------------------------------- |\n| **Origin** | Kidney | Neural crest (adrenal, sympathetic) | Liver |\n| **Typical Age** | 2-3 years | < 5 years (often < 2) | < 3 years |\n| **Location** | Kidney (flank) | Adrenal, retroperitoneal | Liver (RUQ) |\n| **Crosses Midline?** | No | Yes (often) | No (usually confined to liver lobe) |\n| **Other Features** | Smooth, firm mass; aniridia assoc. | Irregular, firm mass; calcifications; systemic symptoms | Elevated AFP; jaundice (rare) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A unilateral, non-midline abdominal mass in a toddler is Wilms until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound and CT, a Wilms tumor appears as a large, well-circumscribed renal mass. Intraoperatively or on gross pathology, it is typically pale grey with areas of hemorrhage and necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Wilms Tumor Guidelines (2021): Recommends risk-stratified treatment based on histology and stage, often involving nephrectomy, chemotherapy, and radiation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hepatoblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Nephroblastoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Polycystic kidney | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Nephroblastoma. A nephroblastoma, also known as Wilms tumour, is formed by the embryonic precursor t** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
