  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A positive test isn't always positive!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, 50%. This is because the Positive Predictive Value (PPV) quantifies the probability that a patient who tests positive for a disease actually has the disease, which is a crucial metric for interpreting diagnostic test results.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Positive Predictive Value (PPV) is calculated as the number of true positives divided by the total number of positive test results (true positives + false positives). In this scenario, 15 patients truly had cancer among the 30 who tested positive. This ratio directly reflects the clinical utility of a positive test result, indicating how reliable a positive finding is in confirming the presence of the disease. A higher PPV means a positive test is more likely to be accurate.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 25% would imply a different ratio, not derived from the given data for PPV.\nOption C (Incorrect): 75% would imply 15/20, which is the sensitivity of the test (True Positives / (True Positives + False Negatives)), not the PPV.\nOption D (Incorrect): 90% is not derivable from the given numbers for PPV.\nOption E (Incorrect): 100% would mean all positive tests were true positives (15/15), which is not the case here as 30 people tested positive.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Metric | Formula | Clinical Interpretation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Positive Predictive Value (PPV) | True Positives / (True Positives + False Positives) | Probability that a positive test result is truly positive. |\n| Negative Predictive Value (NPV) | True Negatives / (True Negatives + False Negatives) | Probability that a negative test result is truly negative. |\n| Sensitivity | True Positives / (True Positives + False Negatives) | Ability of the test to correctly identify those with the disease (true positive rate). |\n| Specificity | True Negatives / (True Negatives + False Positives) | Ability of the test to correctly identify those without the disease (true negative rate). |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PPV = True Positives / All Positives.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nN/A\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 25% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 50% | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 75% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 90% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 100% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) 50%. The positive predictive value (PPV) describes the probability that a condition can be confirmed** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
