  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, blame E. coli for uncomplicated UTIs!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Escherichia coli. This organism is overwhelmingly the most common cause of uncomplicated urinary tract infections (UTIs) or cystitis in young, otherwise healthy women, presenting with classic symptoms of frequency and dysuria.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUncomplicated cystitis, as described in this 24-year-old woman, is primarily caused by uropathogenic Escherichia coli (UPEC) in approximately 75-90% of cases. UPEC strains possess virulence factors like fimbriae (e.g., P fimbriae, Type 1 fimbriae) that allow them to adhere to uroepithelial cells, colonize the bladder, and resist flushing by urine flow. The shorter urethra in women facilitates the ascent of bacteria from the perineum into the bladder, making them more susceptible to UTIs compared to men. The symptoms of dysuria (stinging sensation) and frequency are classic indicators of bladder inflammation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Candida albicans is a fungus and typically causes UTIs in immunocompromised individuals, those with indwelling catheters, or as a result of disseminated candidiasis, not usually uncomplicated cystitis in a healthy young woman.\nOption C (Incorrect): Herpes simplex virus causes genital herpes, characterized by painful vesicular lesions, and while it can cause dysuria, it's not the primary cause of bacterial cystitis symptoms like frequency and stinging without visible lesions.\nOption D (Incorrect): Proteus mirabilis is a common cause of UTIs, known for producing urease which leads to alkaline urine and struvite stone formation, but it is significantly less common than E. coli in uncomplicated cases.\nOption E (Incorrect): Pseudomonas aeruginosa is typically associated with complicated UTIs, often in hospitalized patients, those with indwelling catheters, or structural abnormalities of the urinary tract, not uncomplicated cystitis in a healthy individual.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organism | Typical Presentation | Key Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Escherichia coli | Uncomplicated cystitis, young women | Most common (75-90%), fecal flora, virulence factors (fimbriae) |\n| Proteus mirabilis | Complicated UTI, recurrent infections | Urease producer, alkaline urine, struvite stones |\n| Pseudomonas aeruginosa | Complicated UTI, catheter-associated | Nosocomial, antibiotic resistance, immunocompromised |\n| Candida albicans | Fungal UTI, immunocompromised | Catheterized patients, diabetes, broad-spectrum antibiotic use |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: E. coli is the undisputed king of uncomplicated UTIs in healthy women.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor uncomplicated cystitis, imaging is generally not indicated. If recurrent or complicated, ultrasound or CT might be used to rule out structural abnormalities or stones. No image was provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) Guidelines 2011 (updated 2021 for asymptomatic bacteriuria) recommends empirical treatment for uncomplicated cystitis with agents like nitrofurantoin, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, or fosfomycin, based on local resistance patterns.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Candida albicans | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Escherichia coli | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Herpes simplex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Proteus mirabilis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Pseudomonas aeruginosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Escherichia coli. Cystitis usually presents with dysuria, frequency of urine, suprapubic discomfort ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
