  "answer": "C) Infective tenosynovitis describes the infection of the tendon sheath, usually caused by direct penetrating trauma. The cardinal features of tendon sheath infections are summarized by Kanavel signs: (1) tenderness over the flexor sheath; (2) pain on passive extension; (3) flexed posture of the digit; and (4) fusiform swelling of the digit. The tendon sheaths of the thumb and little finger communicate with the radial and ulna bursa respectively, so infection of these sheaths will spread to the respective bursa. In at least 50% of people there is communication between the ulna and radial bursa, providing a further route of spread for infection (horseshoe tenosynovitis). Treatment may initially be with a period of intravenous antibiotics but drainage must not be delayed if there is no improvement.",
