  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a head injury give you a gut feeling... of blood!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Cushing ulcer. This is the most likely cause of upper gastrointestinal bleeding (vomiting blood) in a patient with a significant head injury, as it directly links neurological trauma to acute peptic ulceration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCushing ulcers are acute peptic ulcers that develop in the setting of increased intracranial pressure (ICP), such as after a traumatic brain injury. The mechanism involves stimulation of the vagus nerve within the brain, leading to hypersecretion of gastric acid, which then causes ulceration, typically in the stomach antrum or duodenum. This phenomenon is also known as Rokitansky-Cushing Syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A Curling ulcer is an acute duodenal ulcer that occurs a few days following severe burns, not head injury.\nOption C (Incorrect): A Decubitus ulcer is another name for a pressure sore, which develops on the skin due to prolonged pressure and immobility, unrelated to GI bleeding from head injury.\nOption D (Incorrect): A Dendritic ulcer is a painful corneal ulcer caused by herpes simplex type 1, affecting the eye, not the gastrointestinal tract.\nOption E (Incorrect): A Martorell’s ulcer is an ischaemic ulcer of the leg above the ankle, occurring secondary to hypertension, unrelated to GI bleeding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ulcer Type | Associated Condition | Location/Description |\n| :--------- | :------------------- | :------------------- |\n| Cushing    | Raised ICP/Head Injury | Stomach/Duodenum (acute peptic) |\n| Curling    | Severe Burns         | Duodenum (acute peptic) |\n| Decubitus  | Immobility/Pressure  | Skin over bony prominences |\n| Dendritic  | Herpes Simplex Virus | Cornea (branched appearance) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Head trauma + GI bleed = Cushing ulcer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal acute, often multiple, superficial or deep ulcers, typically in the gastric antrum or duodenum, which may be actively bleeding. These ulcers can range from erosions to deep perforations.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGuidelines for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury, 4th Edition (2016) from the Brain Trauma Foundation. These guidelines recommend stress ulcer prophylaxis in patients with severe TBI.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Curling ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cushing ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Decubitus ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Dendritic ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Martorell’s ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ANSWER IS B – Cushing ulcer. A Cushing ulcer is the development of acute peptic ulceration in the se** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
