  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Insulin shifts K+; don't let your patient's heart skip a beat!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nPerioperative insulin use, particularly in diabetic patients undergoing major surgery like a Femoral Popliteal Bypass, can lead to hypokalemia. This is a critical electrolyte imbalance to monitor and manage, as insulin actively shifts potassium from the extracellular to the intracellular space.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInsulin facilitates the entry of glucose into cells, but it also promotes the intracellular uptake of potassium by stimulating the Na+/K+-ATPase pump. In the perioperative setting, patients are often NPO, stressed, and may receive intravenous fluids and insulin infusions. The administration of exogenous insulin, especially in patients who may already have depleted potassium stores or are receiving potassium-free fluids, can rapidly lower serum potassium levels. This shift can lead to cardiac arrhythmias, muscle weakness, and other serious complications, necessitating careful monitoring and proactive potassium supplementation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Chlorpropamide is a long-acting sulfonylurea with a significant risk of hypoglycemia, especially in NPO patients. It should generally be held 1-2 days prior to surgery to prevent this complication. \nOption C (Incorrect): This option is incomplete. However, aiming for overly strict blood glucose control (e.g., below 110 mg/dL) perioperatively has been shown to increase the risk of hypoglycemia and adverse outcomes. Current guidelines typically recommend maintaining blood glucose between 140-180 mg/dL for most surgical patients.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Medication Class | Mechanism of Action | Perioperative Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sulfonylureas (e.g., Chlorpropamide, Glyburide) | Stimulate insulin release from pancreas | Hold 1-2 days pre-op due to hypoglycemia risk |\n| Metformin | Decreases hepatic glucose production, increases insulin sensitivity | Hold 24-48 hours pre-op due to lactic acidosis risk (especially with contrast/renal dysfunction) |\n| SGLT2 Inhibitors (e.g., Empagliflozin) | Increase renal glucose excretion | Hold 3-4 days pre-op due to risk of euglycemic DKA |\n| Insulin (Basal/Bolus) | Replaces/supplements endogenous insulin | Adjust dose, often switch to IV insulin infusion for tight control, monitor glucose and electrolytes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Insulin drives potassium into cells; anticipate hypokalemia with perioperative use.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable for this question, as no imaging or intraoperative scenario is described.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Diabetes Association (ADA) Standards of Medical Care in Diabetes (e.g., 2024) and Society of Hospital Medicine (SHM) Perioperative Glucose Management Guidelines (e.g., 2021). These guidelines recommend individualized glycemic targets, typically 140-180 mg/dL for most critically ill and surgical patients, and emphasize careful monitoring of electrolytes, especially potassium, with insulin therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chlorpropamide can usually be given on the day of surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypokalaemia may occur secondary to peri-operative insulin use | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It is important to maintain the blood sugar belo | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
