  "answer": "B) The tibial nerve is the large terminal branch of the sciatic nerve. It runs through the popliteal fossa, at first lying on the lateral side, then crossing medial to the popliteal artery. It leaves the fossa by passing deep to gastrocnemius and soleus. The tibial nerve supplies the knee joint, popliteus, and the posterior compartment muscles of the leg and the foot.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tibial nerve's sural branch: your posterior leg's skin sensation.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B because the tibial nerve gives rise to the medial sural cutaneous nerve in the popliteal fossa. This branch then contributes to the formation of the sural nerve, which is the main cutaneous nerve of the posterior leg and the primary cutaneous contribution of the tibial nerve in this region.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe tibial nerve, a terminal branch of the sciatic nerve, traverses the popliteal fossa, initially superficial and lateral to the popliteal artery. Within this fossa, it gives off several branches, including articular branches to the knee joint, muscular branches to the deep posterior compartment muscles, and most notably, the medial sural cutaneous nerve. This medial sural cutaneous nerve descends between the heads of the gastrocnemius and typically joins with the peroneal communicating branch (from the common peroneal nerve) to form the sural nerve. The sural nerve provides cutaneous innervation to the posterolateral aspect of the leg and the lateral border of the foot.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Articular branches supply joints, not skin, therefore they are not cutaneous branches. \nOption C (Incorrect): The common peroneal nerve is a separate terminal branch of the sciatic nerve, not a branch of the tibial nerve. \nOption D (Incorrect): The medial plantar nerve is a terminal branch of the tibial nerve, but it arises distal to the popliteal fossa, typically in the foot. \nOption E (Incorrect): The posterior femoral cutaneous nerve is a branch of the sacral plexus and innervates the posterior thigh, not a branch of the tibial nerve.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Course in Popliteal Fossa | Main Cutaneous Supply |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tibial Nerve | Sciatic Nerve | Descends vertically, superficial to popliteal artery | Medial sural cutaneous nerve (contributes to sural nerve) |\n| Common Peroneal Nerve | Sciatic Nerve | Descends along lateral border of popliteal fossa, winds around fibular neck | Lateral sural cutaneous nerve, peroneal communicating branch |\n| Sural Nerve | Medial sural cutaneous (tibial) + Peroneal communicating (common peroneal) | Descends between gastrocnemius heads | Posterolateral leg, lateral foot |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the sural nerve's dual origin for posterior leg sensation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring surgical exploration of the popliteal fossa, the tibial nerve is typically found superficial and lateral to the popliteal artery and vein. Its branches, including the medial sural cutaneous nerve, can be identified emerging from its main trunk. Nerve blocks targeting the tibial nerve in the popliteal fossa would anesthetize its cutaneous distribution, including the area supplied by the sural nerve.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNot applicable for basic anatomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Articular branch to the knee joint | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gives off the sural nerve as a branch | ✅ Correct |\n| C | The common peroneal nerve is a branch of the tibial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The medial plantar nerve is a branch of tibial nerve in the popliteal fossa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | The posterior femoral cutaneous nerve. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The tibial nerve is the large terminal branch of the sciatic nerve. It runs through the popliteal fo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
