  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fat or no fat, that is the jejunum/ileum question.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 'Less fat at the mesenteric border'. This feature is a key anatomical distinction, as the jejunum typically has a thinner mesentery with less fat compared to the ileum, which has a thicker, more adipose-laden mesentery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe small intestine, comprising the duodenum, jejunum, and ileum, exhibits distinct anatomical features along its length that reflect its specialized functions. The jejunum, primarily responsible for nutrient absorption, is characterized by a thicker muscular wall, a wider lumen, and more prominent plicae circulares (circular folds) to maximize surface area. Its mesentery is generally thinner and less fatty, allowing for longer vasa recta and fewer arterial arcades. In contrast, the ileum, involved in vitamin B12 and bile salt absorption, has a thinner wall, a narrower lumen, fewer and shorter plicae circulares, and a mesentery that is typically thicker and contains more fat, leading to shorter vasa recta and more numerous arterial arcades.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The jejunum has a thicker wall than the ileum, not a thinner one.\nOption B (Incorrect): The jejunum has more prominent and numerous circular folds (plicae circulares) than the ileum, not fewer.\nOption D (Incorrect): The jejunum has fewer aggregated lymphatic follicles (Peyer’s patches) compared to the ileum, where they are more abundant, especially distally.\nOption E (Incorrect): The jejunum typically has fewer arterial arcades and longer vasa recta, whereas the ileum has more numerous arterial arcades and shorter vasa recta.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Jejunum | Ileum |\n| :-------------------- | :------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------ |\n| Wall thickness | Thicker | Thinner |\n| Mesenteric fat | Less | More |\n| Plicae circulares | More (taller, more numerous) | Fewer (shorter, less numerous) |\n| Peyer's patches | Fewer | More |\n| Arterial arcades | Fewer, longer vasa recta | More, shorter vasa recta |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Jejunum is 'leaner' (less fat) and 'meaner' (thicker wall, more folds).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the jejunum appears redder and thicker-walled with a less fatty, more translucent mesentery containing long, straight arterial branches (vasa recta). The ileum appears paler, thinner-walled, with a more opaque, fatty mesentery and shorter, more numerous arterial arcades. The presence of Peyer's patches is more evident in the ileum upon close inspection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific surgical guideline applies to this fundamental anatomical differentiation; however, principles of surgical anatomy are foundational to all surgical practice.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A thinner wall | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fewer circular folds | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Less fat at the mesenteric border | ✅ Correct |\n| D | More aggregated lymphatic follicles (Peyer’s patches) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | More arterial arcades. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The jejunum has a thicker wall, less mesenteric fat, more plicae circulares, a wider lumen, fewer Pe** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
