  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spinal cord blood supply: Know your Adamkiewicz from your conus!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies a crucial anatomical detail regarding the spinal cord's blood supply. The conus medullaris serves as a vital anastomotic site between the anterior and posterior spinal arteries, which is essential for understanding spinal cord perfusion and vulnerability to ischemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe spinal cord's blood supply is complex, with the anterior spinal artery (ASA) supplying the anterior two-thirds and the paired posterior spinal arteries (PSA) supplying the posterior one-third. The ASA is primarily fed by the great radicular artery of Adamkiewicz, typically arising from T8-T12. The anastomosis between the ASA and PSAs at the conus medullaris provides a critical collateral network, which can be a protective mechanism against ischemia, particularly in the distal cord. Understanding these anastomoses is paramount for procedures like TEVAR, where spinal cord ischemia is a feared complication.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The artery of Adamkiewicz commonly arises from a posterior intercostal artery between T8 and T12, not T3 and T7.\nOption C (Incorrect): The anterior spinal artery arises from the vertebral arteries, not the internal carotid arteries.\nOption D (Incorrect): The anterior spinal artery is an unpaired vessel formed by the union of two vertebral artery branches, although it supplies the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord.\nOption E (Incorrect): The posterior spinal arteries supply the posterior one-third of the spinal cord, while the anterior spinal artery supplies the anterior two-thirds.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Anterior Spinal Artery | Posterior Spinal Arteries | Artery of Adamkiewicz |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Vertebral arteries (unite) | Vertebral arteries | Aorta (via intercostal/lumbar artery) |\n| Number | Single, unpaired | Paired | Single (dominant radicular) |\n| Supply | Anterior 2/3 of spinal cord | Posterior 1/3 of spinal cord | Feeds distal ASA, T8-L2 cord |\n| Key Anastomosis | With PSAs at conus medullaris | With ASA at conus medullaris | Connects aorta to ASA |\n| Clinical Relevance | Major motor tracts | Sensory tracts | Critical for distal cord perfusion |\n| Typical Location | Runs in anterior median fissure | Runs along posterior root entry zones | T8-T12 (most common) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Conus medullaris is the spinal cord's vascular crossroads.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring TEVAR, spinal angiography or CT angiography can be used preoperatively to identify the artery of Adamkiewicz, though it's not always feasible or routinely performed. Intraoperatively, careful monitoring of spinal cord function (e.g., motor evoked potentials) is crucial, and CSF drainage is a prophylactic measure to improve spinal cord perfusion pressure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Thoracic Aortic Disease (2020) recommend cerebrospinal fluid drainage for high-risk TEVAR patients to reduce spinal cord ischemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The artery of Adamkiewicz commonly arises from a posterior intercostal arte | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The conus medullaris is the site of anastomosis of the anterior spinal arte | ✅ Correct |\n| C | The internal carotid arteries give rise to the anterior spinal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The paired anterior spinal arteries supply the anterior two-thirds of the s | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | The posterior spinal arteries supply the posterior two-thirds of the spinal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The artery of Adamkiewicz (i.e. the ‘greater radicular artery’) usually arises from a left intercos-** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
