  "id": 206069,
  "question": "A 68-year-old previously healthy woman is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance in an unconscious state, after having slipped on ice and hitting her head on the pavement. After initial resuscitation, a CT scan of her brain demonstrates a recent right-sided extradural haematoma. However, it also demonstrates the incidental fi nding of a space-occupying lesion in the left temporal lobe with an enhancing ring around an area of presumed necrosis. The radiologist is concerned that this incidental fi nding is suggestive of malignancy. What type of malignancy is this lesion most likely to represent?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Astrocytoma",
    "B": "Ependymoma",
    "C": "Glioblastoma multiforme",
    "D": "Meningioma",
    "E": "Oligodendroglioma"
  },
  "answer": "C) Glioblastoma multiforme is the most common and most aggressive type of primary brain tumour in humans, involving glial cells and accounting for over 50% of all parenchymal brain tumours and about 20% of all intracranial tumours. They have a peak incidence between 55–65 years of age. The CT fi ndings described in this scenario are also typical of glioblastoma (i.e. a ‘ring-enhancing’ lesion, although this is not specifi c; other pathologies such as abscesses, metastases, tumefactive multiple sclerosis, etc. may demonstrate similar appearances). The site of this patient’s tumour excludes a meningioma, as it is reported to be in the temporal lobe and is therefore intrinsic. Ependymomas are tumours arising from the ependyma, a tissue of the central nervous system; they usually arise in the fourth ventricle. Astrocytomas account for about 10% of primary brain tumours in adults but are more common in children. Oligodendrogliomas occur primarily in adults (9%) of all primary brain and central nervous system tumours) but are also found in chil-dren (4%).",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 GBM: The ring of death for the brain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Glioblastoma multiforme (GBM). This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the patient's age (68 years old) and the classic CT findings of a ring-enhancing lesion with presumed necrosis in the temporal lobe, which are hallmarks of this aggressive primary brain tumor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGlioblastoma multiforme is the most common and aggressive primary brain tumor in adults, accounting for over 50% of all parenchymal brain tumors. It typically presents in patients aged 55-65 years. On imaging, GBM classically appears as a ring-enhancing lesion with a necrotic core, reflecting its rapid, infiltrative growth and central ischemia. Its intrinsic location within the temporal lobe parenchyma further supports this diagnosis, distinguishing it from extrinsic lesions like meningiomas.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Astrocytoma) (Incorrect): While GBM is a high-grade astrocytoma, the term 'astrocytoma' alone often refers to lower-grade lesions, which typically do not present with such aggressive ring enhancement and necrosis in an elderly patient.\nOption B (Ependymoma) (Incorrect): Ependymomas are tumors arising from ependymal cells, most commonly found in the fourth ventricle, not typically in the temporal lobe parenchyma.\nOption D (Meningioma) (Incorrect): Meningiomas are typically extra-axial (arising from the meninges) and extrinsic to the brain parenchyma. The lesion described is in the temporal lobe, implying an intrinsic parenchymal location.\nOption E (Oligodendroglioma) (Incorrect): Oligodendrogliomas are less common than GBM and, while they can occur in adults, the described aggressive ring-enhancing pattern with necrosis is more characteristic of GBM.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Typical Location | Imaging Features | Key Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Glioblastoma Multiforme (GBM) | Cerebral hemispheres (e.g., temporal lobe) | Ring-enhancing lesion with necrotic core | Most common, aggressive primary adult brain tumor; peak incidence 55-65 years |\n| Meningioma | Extra-axial (dura, falx, tentorium) | Homogeneous enhancement, dural tail sign | Benign, slow-growing; more common in women |\n| Ependymoma | Fourth ventricle, spinal cord | Variable enhancement, often calcified | More common in children; can cause hydrocephalus |\n| Astrocytoma (low-grade) | Cerebral hemispheres | Non-enhancing or mild enhancement | Less aggressive than GBM, often infiltrative |\n| Oligodendroglioma | Frontal lobe | Calcifications common, variable enhancement | Often slow-growing, can be associated with seizures |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ring-enhancing lesion + elderly patient = think GBM first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a Glioblastoma multiforme typically presents as an irregular, thick-walled, ring-enhancing lesion with a central hypodense (necrotic) core. There may also be surrounding vasogenic edema. This appearance is highly suggestive of an aggressive, high-grade tumor.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Classification of Tumours of the Central Nervous System (5th Edition, 2021) recommends molecular and histological criteria for GBM diagnosis and grading.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Astrocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ependymoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Glioblastoma multiforme | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Meningioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Oligodendroglioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Glioblastoma multiforme is the most common and most aggressive type of primary brain tumour in human** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
