  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Preserve the head when the neck's just slightly off-kilter!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, cannulated screw fixation. This is the optimal treatment for an undisplaced intracapsular femoral neck fracture in an active, otherwise healthy elderly patient, aiming to preserve the femoral head and maintain their pre-injury mobility.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCannulated screw fixation offers internal fixation while preserving the native femoral head and joint, which is crucial for an independently mobile patient without pre-existing osteoarthritis. The undisplaced nature of the fracture allows for stable reduction and fixation, minimizing the risk of avascular necrosis compared to displaced fractures. This approach maintains the patient's pre-injury mobility and functional status, allowing for earlier mobilization and better long-term outcomes in this specific patient demographic.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Cemented Thompson’s hemiarthroplasty is typically reserved for displaced femoral neck fractures in less active or frail elderly patients, or those with significant comorbidities, as it replaces only the femoral head and neck.\nOption C (Incorrect): Dynamic hip screws (DHS) are primarily used for extracapsular hip fractures (e.g., intertrochanteric fractures), not intracapsular femoral neck fractures.\nOption D (Incorrect): Non-surgical management for an active patient with a femoral neck fracture carries a high risk of non-union, avascular necrosis, and prolonged immobility, leading to significant morbidity and mortality.\nOption E (Incorrect): Total hip replacement (THR) would be more appropriate for displaced femoral neck fractures, younger patients, or those with pre-existing osteoarthritis, as it replaces both the femoral head and acetabulum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type | Patient Profile | Treatment | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Undisplaced Intracapsular Femoral Neck | Active, healthy elderly | Cannulated Screw Fixation | Preserves native joint, low AVN risk, maintains function |\n| Displaced Intracapsular Femoral Neck | Young/Active Elderly | Total Hip Replacement (THR) | Higher AVN risk with fixation, better long-term function |\n| Displaced Intracapsular Femoral Neck | Frail/Less Active Elderly | Hemiarthroplasty | Simpler surgery, adequate for lower functional demands |\n| Extracapsular (Intertrochanteric) | Any | Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS) or Intramedullary Nail | Stable fixation for extracapsular patterns |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Undisplaced femoral neck in active elderly? Fix it, don't replace it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPlain radiography would show a subtle cortical break or trabecular impaction in the femoral neck, without significant displacement of the femoral head relative to the acetabulum. This would typically be classified as a Garden I or Garden II fracture.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Hip Fractures in Older Adults (2020). Recommends internal fixation for undisplaced femoral neck fractures in physiologically younger patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cannulated screw fi xation | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Cemented Thompson’s hemiarthroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dynamic hip screw | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Non-surgical management | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Total hip replacement | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) It is common that patients with fractured femoral necks, who are also eligible for surgery, would pr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
