  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't confuse cushions with varices; haemorrhoids are not a sign of portal hypertension!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe statement that portal hypertension may result in haemorrhoids is incorrect. While portal hypertension can cause anorectal varices, these are distinct from true haemorrhoids, which are pathological enlargements of the normal anal cushions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTrue haemorrhoids originate from the three normal anal cushions (left lateral, right anterior, right posterior) located in the submucosa of the anal canal. These cushions are composed of connective tissue, smooth muscle, and a rich arteriovenous plexus. Their pathological enlargement and displacement, often due to straining and increased intra-abdominal pressure, lead to symptomatic haemorrhoids. Anorectal varices, on the other hand, are dilated submucosal veins that develop as a portosystemic shunt in patients with portal hypertension and are not derived from the anal cushions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Haemorrhoids are indeed formed by the expansion and displacement of the normal endoanal cushions, which are vascular structures in the anal canal.\nOption C (Incorrect): The primary blood supply to internal haemorrhoids, which are the most common type, is from the superior rectal artery, a branch of the inferior mesenteric artery.\nOption D (Incorrect): Internal haemorrhoids are located above the dentate line and are covered by columnar epithelium proximally and transitional epithelium distally.\nOption E (Incorrect): External haemorrhoids are located below the dentate line and are covered by anoderm (squamous epithelium), with transitional epithelium sometimes found near the dentate line.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Haemorrhoids | Anorectal Varices |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Enlarged anal cushions | Dilated portosystemic collateral veins |\n| **Pathophysiology** | Displacement/engorgement of normal cushions | Portal hypertension |\n| **Location** | Above/below dentate line | Often diffuse, can be above/below dentate line |\n| **Clinical Significance** | Bleeding, prolapse, pain, itching | Bleeding, often associated with liver disease |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Portal hypertension causes varices, not true haemorrhoids from anal cushions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring anoscopy or proctoscopy, internal haemorrhoids appear as distinct, often prolapsing, vascular cushions covered by mucosa. They are typically located in the left lateral, right anterior, and right posterior positions. Anorectal varices, if present, might appear as more diffuse, bluish, dilated veins, often without the distinct cushion morphology of true haemorrhoids, and may be associated with signs of liver disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018). These guidelines differentiate haemorrhoids from other anorectal conditions and outline treatment strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Haemorrhoids are formed by the expansion of the endoanal cushions | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Portal hypertension may result in haemorrhoids | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Blood supply is mainly from the superior rectal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Internal haemorrhoids are lined by columnar and transitional epithelium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | External haemorrhoids are lined by transitional and squamous epithelium | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Anorectal vascular cushions are normally present in the anal canal. They commonly form three promine** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
