  "id": 206072,
  "question": "The following are the blood results of a 70-year-old man: Sodium: 128 mmol/L Potassium: 4 mmol/L Urea: 5 mmol/L Creatinine: 89 mmol/L Glucose: 13 mmol/L What is the serum osmolality (mOsmol/kg)?",
  "options": {
    "A": "290",
    "B": "288",
    "C": "282",
    "D": "269",
    "E": "275"
  },
  "answer": "C) The intracellular and extracellular compartments are separated by cell membranes which are extremely permeable to water but less so to electrolytes. Sodium pumps in the cell membrane pump sodium out of the cell. This means that the distribution of water between the two com- partments is largely determined by the osmotic effect of electrolytes in the extracellular fl uid and the proteins within the cell. Osmotic pressure is the pressure required to prevent osmosis and is directly proportional to the concentration of osmotically active particles in the solution. ‘Osmoles’ refers to the number of osmotically active particles in a solution; it is the standard unit of osmotic pressure. Osmolality is the number of osmoles of solute per kilogram solvent (mOsmol/kg). Osmolarity is the number of osmoles of solute per litre solution (mOsmol/L). Plasma osmolality (mOsmol/kg) is estimated by: 2(Na + K) + urea + glucose, which in this case, is approximately equal to 282 mOsmol/kg.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get lost in the fluid; calculate osmolality to find your way!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct because it accurately reflects the calculated serum osmolality using the standard formula: 2(Na + K) + Urea + Glucose, which is a critical measure of fluid balance in a 70-year-old man.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSerum osmolality is a measure of the solute concentration per kilogram of solvent in the blood, primarily determined by sodium, glucose, and urea. Sodium and its accompanying anions are the largest contributors to extracellular osmolality, hence the multiplication by two in the formula. This calculation helps assess hydration status and diagnose conditions like hypernatremia, hyponatremia, and hyperosmolar states, guiding appropriate fluid and electrolyte management. The calculated value of 2(128 + 4) + 5 + 13 = 282 mOsmol/kg directly matches option C.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This value is higher than the correct calculation, suggesting an error in applying the formula or arithmetic.\nOption B (Incorrect): This value is higher than the correct calculation, indicating a miscalculation of the osmotically active particles.\nOption D (Incorrect): This value is lower than the correct calculation, likely due to an omission or incorrect coefficient in the formula.\nOption E (Incorrect): This value is lower than the correct calculation, indicating an error in the summation of the osmolytes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Calculated Osmolality                               | Measured Osmolality                                  | Osmolal Gap                                                              |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Definition**      | Estimated from major osmolytes (Na, Glucose, Urea)  | Directly measured by freezing point depression       | Difference between measured and calculated osmolality                    |\n| **Formula**         | 2(Na + K) + Urea + Glucose (all in mmol/L)          | N/A                                                  | Measured Osmolality - Calculated Osmolality                              |\n| **Clinical Use**    | Quick assessment, screening for osmolal gap         | Gold standard for true osmolality                    | Detects presence of unmeasured osmolytes (e.g., ethanol, methanol, ethylene glycol) |\n| **Normal Range**    | 275-295 mOsmol/kg                                   | 275-295 mOsmol/kg                                    | < 10 mOsmol/kg                                                           |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Osmolality: Double Na, add Glucose and Urea.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable to this lab calculation question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Perioperative Fluid Management 2023. These guidelines emphasize careful fluid and electrolyte management, including monitoring serum osmolality in specific clinical scenarios.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 290 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 288 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 282 | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 269 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 275 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The intracellular and extracellular compartments are separated by cell membranes which are extremely** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
