  "answer": "C) This patient has sustained a tibial plafond fracture (also known as a tibial pilon fracture) at the distal tibia and involving the ankle joint. As is the case with tibial plateau fractures, these injuries occur close to the joint surface and must be treated with the joint cartilage surface in mind. The various management options for tibial plafond fractures include casting, external fi xation, limited internal fi xation, internal fi xation, and ankle fusion. In this case, external fi xation is the treatment of choice and this involves insertion of a distal pin in the region of the medial calcaneum, where the medial plantar nerve runs and this may potentially be damaged. The medial plantar nerve is the larger of the two terminal divisions of the tibial nerve and accompanies the medial plantar artery along its course.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Medial calcaneal pins: mind the medial plantar nerve!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Medial plantar nerve. The described pin placement for external fixation of a tibial pilon fracture involves inserting a pin from the medial aspect of the calcaneum, approximately 2.5 cm superior and anterior to the heel. This specific location places the pin directly in the anatomical vicinity of the medial plantar nerve, making it highly susceptible to iatrogenic injury.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe medial plantar nerve is a terminal branch of the tibial nerve, which itself is a major component of the sciatic nerve. It courses along the medial side of the sole of the foot, deep to the abductor hallucis muscle, and provides sensory innervation to the medial three and a half digits and the adjacent sole, as well as motor innervation to several intrinsic foot muscles. Its close proximity to the medial calcaneum means that any surgical intervention, such as the described external fixator pin placement, carries a significant risk of direct trauma or compression, leading to sensory deficits or motor weakness in its distribution.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Deep fibular (peroneal) nerve) (Incorrect): This nerve is located in the anterior compartment of the leg and then crosses the ankle joint to supply the dorsum of the foot. It is not in the vicinity of a medially placed calcaneal pin.\nOption B (Lateral plantar nerve) (Incorrect): While also a branch of the tibial nerve and located in the sole of the foot, the lateral plantar nerve runs more laterally. The pin is explicitly described as being inserted from the medial aspect of the calcaneum, making the medial plantar nerve the primary concern.\nOption D (Saphenous nerve) (Incorrect): The saphenous nerve is a sensory nerve that supplies the skin along the medial side of the leg and ankle. It is generally more superficial and anterior to the calcaneum, making it less likely to be directly impaled by a calcaneal pin.\nOption E (Superficial fibular (peroneal) nerve) (Incorrect): This nerve is located in the lateral compartment of the leg and supplies sensation to the dorsum of the foot. It is not near the calcaneum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Course/Location | Common Injury Mechanism/Location |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Medial Plantar Nerve** | Tibial Nerve | Medial sole of foot, deep to abductor hallucis | Calcaneal pin placement, tarsal tunnel syndrome |\n| Lateral Plantar Nerve | Tibial Nerve | Lateral sole of foot | Less common with medial calcaneal pin, tarsal tunnel syndrome |\n| Deep Fibular Nerve | Common Fibular Nerve | Anterior leg, dorsum of foot | Anterior compartment syndrome, ankle fracture, tight shoelaces |\n| Superficial Fibular Nerve | Common Fibular Nerve | Lateral leg, dorsum of foot | Ankle sprains, lateral compartment syndrome, tight footwear |\n| Saphenous Nerve | Femoral Nerve | Medial leg and ankle (sensory) | Medial ankle surgery, saphenous vein harvest, direct trauma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial calcaneal pin = Medial plantar nerve risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring external fixator pin placement, fluoroscopy is often used to confirm appropriate bone purchase and avoid neurovascular structures. Intraoperatively, careful dissection and palpation can help identify and protect the medial plantar nerve, which lies deep to the abductor hallucis muscle on the medial aspect of the calcaneum. Post-operatively, nerve injury may manifest as numbness or paresthesia in the medial sole and toes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nOrthopaedic Trauma Association (OTA) Classification and Treatment of Pilon Fractures (e.g., OTA/AO Foundation guidelines). These guidelines emphasize careful surgical planning and technique to minimize complications, including neurovascular injury, during external fixation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Deep fi bular (peroneal) nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lateral plantar nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Medial plantar nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Saphenous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Superfi cial fi bular (peroneal) nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) This patient has sustained a tibial plafond fracture (also known as a tibial pilon fracture) at the ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
