  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the shoulder freezes up, and X-rays are clear, think capsulitis!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Adhesive capsulitis. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the patient's age (54-year-old), diffuse pain on almost all active and passive movements, significant restriction, and normal plain radiographs, all classic features of a \"frozen shoulder.\"\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdhesive capsulitis, or frozen shoulder, is characterized by a progressive loss of both active and passive range of motion due to capsular inflammation and fibrosis, typically affecting individuals aged 40-60. The pain is diffuse and present across all planes of movement, distinguishing it from tendinopathies which often have specific painful arcs or movements. Its association with diabetes and the characteristic normal plain radiographs further solidify the diagnosis, as other conditions like calcific tendonitis would show radiographic changes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Acute calcific tendonitis would typically present with calcification visible on plain radiographs, which are stated as normal in this case.\nOption B (Incorrect): Supraspinatus tendonitis usually causes pain in a specific arc of abduction (60-120 degrees) and often spares passive range of motion, unlike the diffuse pain and restricted active and passive movements described.\nOption D (Incorrect): A rotator cuff tear, especially a significant one, might show some abnormalities on plain radiographs (e.g., high-riding humeral head in chronic cases) or would be suspected with specific weakness patterns, though pain and restriction can occur. The diffuse restriction of both active and passive motion is more characteristic of adhesive capsulitis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Subacromial bursitis often presents with pain similar to tendonitis, typically with a painful arc and less global restriction of both active and passive range of motion compared to adhesive capsulitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Adhesive Capsulitis | Supraspinatus Tendonitis | Calcific Tendonitis | Rotator Cuff Tear |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Age** | 40-60 years | Any adult age | 30-60 years | >40 years, often older |\n| **Pain Pattern** | Diffuse, all movements | Painful arc (60-120° abduction) | Acute, severe, localized | Pain with overhead, weakness |\n| **Movement Restriction** | Active & Passive, severe | Active, often normal passive | Active, often normal passive | Active, weakness, +/- passive |\n| **Radiographs** | Normal | Normal | Calcification present | May be normal, or show high-riding humeral head (chronic) |\n| **Associated Factors** | Diabetes, thyroid disease | Overuse, impingement | Unknown, metabolic | Trauma, degeneration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Global restriction of active AND passive shoulder motion with normal X-rays = frozen shoulder.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPlain radiographs are typically normal in adhesive capsulitis, serving to rule out other pathologies. In contrast, calcific tendonitis would show distinct calcifications, and chronic rotator cuff tears might reveal superior migration of the humeral head.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Adhesive Capsulitis of the Shoulder (2014, reaffirmed 2019). It recommends patient education, activity modification, and physical therapy as initial treatments.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute calcifi c tendonitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Supraspinatus tendonitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Adhesive capsulitis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Rotator cuff tear | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Subacromial bursitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Adhesive capsulitis (frozen shoulder) is characterized by a progression through pain, stiff ness, an** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
