  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the stomach grows a lump, think 'adeno' first, it's the king of the gut.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. This question correctly identifies adenocarcinoma as the most likely pathological finding for a large exophytic growth in the distal stomach, reflecting its overwhelming prevalence among gastric malignancies. The clinical presentation of anemia and a mass strongly points towards a malignant process.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastric adenocarcinoma accounts for over 90% of all gastric cancers. It commonly presents in older individuals with symptoms like anemia due to chronic blood loss from the tumor, and can manifest as a palpable or endoscopically visible mass, often exophytic or fungating. The distal stomach, particularly the antrum and pylorus, is a frequent site for these tumors, making adenocarcinoma the statistically dominant and clinically expected diagnosis in this scenario.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Squamous cell carcinoma of the stomach is exceedingly rare, typically arising from metaplastic squamous epithelium or as part of an adenosquamous carcinoma, and is not the most likely primary diagnosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Gastric lymphoma, while the second most common gastric malignancy, accounts for only 1-5% of cases and often presents as diffuse thickening or ulceration rather than a purely exophytic mass, making it less likely than adenocarcinoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Leiomyosarcoma is a rare mesenchymal tumor of the stomach, often presenting as a submucosal mass or GIST, and is far less common than adenocarcinoma.\nOption E (Incorrect): Rhabdomyosarcoma is an extremely rare and aggressive soft tissue sarcoma, virtually unheard of as a primary gastric tumor in adults.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gastric Adenocarcinoma | Gastric Lymphoma | GIST (Gastrointestinal Stromal Tumor) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Prevalence** | >90% of gastric cancers | 1-5% of gastric cancers | ~1% of gastric tumors |\n| **Origin** | Glandular epithelium | Lymphoid tissue (MALT, diffuse large B-cell) | Interstitial cells of Cajal (mesenchymal) |\n| **Typical Appearance** | Exophytic, ulcerated, infiltrative mass | Diffuse thickening, ulceration, polypoid | Submucosal mass, often exophytic or endophytic |\n| **Location** | Antrum, pylorus, cardia | Any part, often diffuse | Any part, often fundus/body |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastric mass in an adult = adenocarcinoma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal a large, irregular, fungating or polypoid mass protruding into the gastric lumen, often with central ulceration or friability. Biopsies are crucial for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., 2024). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment of gastric adenocarcinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Squamous cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Adenocarcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Leiomyosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Rhadomyosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Most gastric malignancies are adenocarcinomas** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
