  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let GCA steal their sight; act fast, treat right!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis is Giant Cell Arteritis (GCA). The patient's age, new-onset headache, deteriorating vision, and classic symptom of scalp tenderness (pain when combing hair) are highly indicative of GCA, a medical emergency requiring prompt treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGiant Cell Arteritis is a systemic granulomatous vasculitis primarily affecting large and medium-sized arteries, particularly branches of the carotid artery such as the superficial temporal and ophthalmic arteries. The inflammation and potential occlusion of the ophthalmic artery can lead to ischemic optic neuropathy and irreversible vision loss, making prompt diagnosis and high-dose corticosteroid treatment critical. Scalp tenderness and jaw claudication are due to ischemia of the affected arteries in those regions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Wegeners granulomatosis) (now Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis): Incorrect. This is a small-to-medium vessel vasculitis typically involving the upper and lower respiratory tracts and kidneys, not presenting with the classic GCA symptoms.\nOption C (Polyarteritis nodosa): Incorrect. This is a necrotizing vasculitis of medium-sized arteries, typically sparing the pulmonary circulation and not presenting with the specific headache, vision loss, and scalp tenderness pattern of GCA.\nOption D (Takayasu's arteritis): Incorrect. This is a large vessel vasculitis affecting the aorta and its branches, typically seen in younger women (<50 years old) and presenting with symptoms like claudication and pulseless disease, not GCA's specific presentation.\nOption E (Buergers disease): Incorrect. Thromboangiitis obliterans is a small and medium-sized vessel vasculitis strongly associated with smoking, primarily affecting the limbs and leading to ischemia and gangrene of digits, not headaches or vision loss.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Giant Cell Arteritis (GCA) | Takayasu's Arteritis | Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (GPA) |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Vessel Size** | Large & Medium | Large | Small & Medium |\n| **Typical Age/Sex** | >50 years, F>M | <50 years, F>M | Any age, M=F |\n| **Key Symptoms** | Headache, jaw claudication, scalp tenderness, vision loss, polymyalgia rheumatica | Arm/leg claudication, pulseless disease, hypertension, bruits | Upper/lower respiratory (sinusitis, hemoptysis), renal (glomerulonephritis), skin, eye |\n| **Diagnostic Test** | Temporal artery biopsy, US | Angiography (CT/MR), PET | ANCA (c-ANCA/PR3-ANCA), biopsy (granulomas) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: New headache + vision loss + scalp tenderness in elderly = GCA. Treat urgently!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound of the temporal arteries may show a 'halo sign' (hypoechoic wall thickening). Temporal artery biopsy revealing transmural inflammation with giant cells is diagnostic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2023 ACR/EULAR Classification Criteria for Giant Cell Arteritis. Recommends prompt initiation of high-dose glucocorticoids upon suspicion to prevent irreversible vision loss.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Giant cell arteritis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Wegeners granulomatosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Polyarteritis nodosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Takayasu's arteritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Buergers disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Temporal arteritis may present acutely with symptoms of headache and\nvisual loss, or with a less acu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
