  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 UC is a superficial affair; obstruction is a deeper problem.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C because large bowel obstruction is an uncommon complication of ulcerative colitis (UC), which primarily causes superficial mucosal inflammation. While toxic megacolon can occur, it is a distinct entity from mechanical obstruction and is a functional rather than a structural blockage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUlcerative colitis is characterized by continuous, superficial inflammation limited to the colonic mucosa, typically starting in the rectum and extending proximally. This superficial nature, along with the absence of transmural inflammation and stricture formation (common in Crohn's disease), makes mechanical large bowel obstruction rare. Toxic megacolon, a life-threatening complication, involves acute colonic dilation due to severe inflammation, but it's a functional rather than a mechanical obstruction, and its pathophysiology differs from a true mechanical obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Superficial mucosal inflammation is the hallmark pathological feature of ulcerative colitis, differentiating it from Crohn's disease.\nOption B (Incorrect): Long-standing ulcerative colitis, especially with extensive disease, carries a well-documented and significant risk of dysplasia and colorectal cancer, necessitating surveillance.\nOption D (Incorrect): Haemorrhage, often presenting as bloody diarrhea, is a very common symptom and complication of ulcerative colitis due to the friable and ulcerated mucosa.\nOption E (Incorrect): Ulcerative colitis characteristically spares the anal canal and perianal region, unlike Crohn's disease which frequently involves these areas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ulcerative Colitis (UC) | Crohn's Disease (CD) |\n| :---------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Inflammation Depth** | Mucosal and submucosal | Transmural |\n| **Distribution** | Continuous, starts rectum, extends proximally | Skip lesions, any part of GI tract (mouth to anus) |\n| **Anal Canal Sparing** | Yes | No (fistulas, abscesses common) |\n| **Strictures/Obstruction** | Rare (except toxic megacolon) | Common (due to transmural inflammation and fibrosis) |\n| **Dysplasia Risk** | High in long-standing, extensive disease | Present, but generally lower than UC for colorectal cancer |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: UC is superficial and continuous; obstruction is rare, but megacolon is a distinct, severe complication.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy in UC reveals continuous erythema, friability, granularity, and ulcerations, typically starting in the rectum. On plain abdominal X-ray, toxic megacolon appears as colonic dilation (>6 cm) with loss of haustral markings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guidelines: Ulcerative Colitis in Adults (2019). Recommends regular surveillance colonoscopy for dysplasia in long-standing UC.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Superficial mucosal inflammation in the colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Significant risk of dysplasia in long standing disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Epsiodes of large bowel obstruction during acute attacks | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Haemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Disease sparing the anal canal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Large bowel obstruction is not a feature of UC, patients may develop megacolon. However, this is a d** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
