  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Parietal cells: the stomach's acid factory!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Parietal cells. These specialized cells are directly responsible for the secretion of hydrochloric acid (HCl) into the stomach lumen, which is crucial for digestion and defense against pathogens.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nParietal cells, also known as oxyntic cells, are located in the gastric glands of the stomach fundus and body. Their primary function is the secretion of gastric acid (HCl) and intrinsic factor. The acid secretion is mediated by the H+/K+-ATPase proton pump located on the apical membrane of the parietal cell, which actively exchanges hydrogen ions for potassium ions. This process is stimulated by acetylcholine, gastrin, and histamine, acting on muscarinic, CCK-B, and H2 receptors, respectively.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Chief cells) (Incorrect): Chief cells secrete pepsinogen, the inactive precursor to pepsin, which is activated by gastric acid.\nOption C (Brunners Glands) (Incorrect): Brunner's glands are located in the submucosa of the duodenum and secrete an alkaline mucus to protect the duodenal lining from acidic chyme.\nOption D (G Cells) (Incorrect): G cells, found primarily in the gastric antrum, secrete gastrin. Gastrin stimulates parietal cells to release gastric acid, but G cells do not directly release the acid themselves.\nOption E (None of the above) (Incorrect): This is incorrect as parietal cells are directly responsible for gastric acid release.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cell Type/Gland | Location | Primary Secretion/Function |\n|---|---|---|\n| Parietal Cells | Gastric glands (fundus/body) | Hydrochloric Acid (HCl), Intrinsic Factor |\n| Chief Cells | Gastric glands (fundus/body) | Pepsinogen |\n| G Cells | Gastric antrum | Gastrin (stimulates acid release) |\n| Brunner's Glands | Duodenum (submucosa) | Alkaline mucus (protects duodenum) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Parietal cells pump acid; G cells prompt acid.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a peptic ulcer appears as a break in the gastric or duodenal mucosa, often with a white base due to fibrin. Active bleeding may be seen as oozing, spurting, or a visible vessel. Imaging like CT may show signs of perforation (free air) or obstruction in complicated cases.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017) recommends H. pylori eradication and NSAID cessation as primary treatments.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chief cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Parietal cells | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Brunners Glands | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | G Cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Parietal cells are responsible for the release of gastric acid. Brunners glands are found in the duo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
