  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Heparin can make your potassium soar, so always keep an eye on that K+!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Heparin. Both unfractionated and low-molecular weight heparin can cause hyperkalemia, a critical electrolyte imbalance. This occurs due to heparin's inhibitory effect on aldosterone secretion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHeparin induces a reversible state of hypoaldosteronism by inhibiting aldosterone synthesis or release from the adrenal cortex. Aldosterone normally promotes sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the renal tubules. By reducing aldosterone levels, heparin impairs the kidney's ability to excrete potassium, leading to its accumulation in the blood and subsequent hyperkalemia. This effect is typically dose-dependent and can manifest after several days of therapy, necessitating careful electrolyte monitoring in patients on prolonged heparin regimens.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Ciprofloxacin) (Incorrect): Ciprofloxacin is a fluoroquinolone antibiotic and is not known to directly cause hyperkalemia.\nOption C (Salbutamol) (Incorrect): Salbutamol (albuterol) is a beta-2 adrenergic agonist that causes an intracellular shift of potassium, leading to hypokalemia. It is, in fact, a recognized treatment for hyperkalemia.\nOption D (Levothyroxine) (Incorrect): Levothyroxine is a thyroid hormone replacement and does not directly cause hyperkalemia.\nOption E (Codeine phosphate) (Incorrect): Codeine is an opioid analgesic and antitussive, and it is not associated with causing hyperkalemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Drug Class/Drug | Effect on Potassium | Mechanism | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Heparin | Hyperkalemia | Inhibits aldosterone secretion | Monitor K+ in prolonged use |\n| ACE Inhibitors/ARBs | Hyperkalemia | Block renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system | Common cause of drug-induced hyperkalemia |\n| Spironolactone/Eplerenone | Hyperkalemia | Aldosterone antagonists (K+-sparing diuretics) | Used in heart failure, monitor K+ |\n| Salbutamol (Albuterol) | Hypokalemia | Beta-2 agonist, shifts K+ intracellularly | Used to treat hyperkalemia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Heparin inhibits aldosterone, leading to hyperkalemia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Health-System Pharmacists (ASHP) Therapeutic Guidelines on Anticoagulation (2018): These guidelines recommend monitoring electrolytes, including potassium, in patients receiving heparin, especially those at risk for electrolyte imbalances.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Heparin | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Ciprofloxacin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Salbutamol | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Levothyroxine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Codeine phosphate | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Both unfractionated and low-molecular weight heparin can cause\nhyperkalaemia. This is thought to be ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
