  "id": 206124,
  "question": "A 25-year-old man who has been morbidly obese for the past five years\nis reviewed in the surgical bariatric clinic. In this patient, release of which\nof the following hormones would increase appetite?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Leptin",
    "B": "Thyroxine",
    "C": "Adiponectin",
    "D": "Ghrelin",
    "E": "Serotonin"
  },
  "answer": "D) Obesity hormones\nleptin decreases appetite\nghrelin increases appetite\nWhilst thyroxine can increase appetite it does not fit with the clinical\npicture being described.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ghrelin: The stomach's signal to feast, not fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Ghrelin. Ghrelin is a potent orexigenic hormone, meaning it stimulates appetite, and its release would increase hunger in a patient with morbid obesity. Understanding the interplay of appetite-regulating hormones is crucial in managing obesity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGhrelin, often dubbed the 'hunger hormone,' is primarily produced by P/D1 cells in the fundus of the stomach. Its levels typically rise before meals, signaling hunger to the brain, and decrease after eating. In morbidly obese individuals, ghrelin's role in appetite stimulation is particularly relevant, as its dysregulation can contribute to persistent hunger and difficulty with weight management. Bariatric procedures like sleeve gastrectomy, which remove a significant portion of the fundus, often lead to a reduction in ghrelin levels, contributing to decreased appetite and weight loss.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Leptin is an adipokine produced by adipose tissue that signals satiety to the brain, thus decreasing appetite. Its levels are often high in obese individuals, but they can develop leptin resistance.\nOption B (Incorrect): Thyroxine (thyroid hormone) increases metabolic rate and can indirectly increase appetite due to higher energy expenditure. However, it is not the primary hormone directly responsible for increasing appetite in the context of the described clinical picture of obesity.\nOption C (Incorrect): Adiponectin is an adipokine that enhances insulin sensitivity and has anti-inflammatory effects. It does not directly increase appetite; rather, its levels are often lower in obese individuals, contributing to insulin resistance.\nOption E (Incorrect): Serotonin has a complex role in appetite regulation, but generally, increased serotonin activity in the brain is associated with satiety and reduced food intake, not increased appetite.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Primary Source | Effect on Appetite | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ghrelin | Stomach (fundus) | Increases | 'Hunger hormone,' targeted by bariatric surgery |\n| Leptin | Adipose tissue | Decreases | 'Satiety hormone,' often high in obesity (resistance) |\n| Adiponectin | Adipose tissue | No direct effect | Improves insulin sensitivity, lower in obesity |\n| Thyroxine | Thyroid gland | Indirectly increases | Increases metabolism, not primary appetite regulator |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ghrelin makes you 'growl' for food; Leptin makes you 'lean' away from it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question does not include an image. Intraoperatively during a sleeve gastrectomy, the fundus of the stomach, which is the primary source of ghrelin, is resected. This surgical alteration directly impacts ghrelin production and contributes to the post-operative reduction in appetite.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) and The Obesity Society (TOS) Guidelines for the Perioperative Nutritional, Metabolic, and Nonsurgical Support of Patients Undergoing Bariatric Surgery (2016). These guidelines emphasize the hormonal changes, including ghrelin reduction, that contribute to weight loss post-bariatric surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Leptin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thyroxine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Adiponectin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ghrelin | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Serotonin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Obesity hormones\nleptin decreases appetite\nghrelin increases appetite\nWhilst thyroxine can increase ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
