  "id": 206138,
  "question": "You are counselling a young lady who has come into your clinic enquiring about testing for familial breast cancer. She has a mother who developed the disease at 65 and a grandmother who developed it at 43. Which of the following statements is correct regarding the genetics of inherited cancers? Select one answer only.",
  "options": {
    "A": "Retinoblastoma is a condition associated with hereditary blindness. It is caused by germline mutations in the Rb1 gene oh Ch 13 in the majority of cases",
    "B": "BRCA I and BRCA II are genes responsible for inherited breast cancer. They are both associated with an approximate 80% lifetime risk of breast cancer but BRCA I is also associated with an increased risk of developing ovarian cancer whilst BRCA II is not",
    "C": "Familial Adenomatous Polyposis is a condition which increases the risk of colorectal carcinoma hugely. The APC (adenomatous polyposis coli) gene is found on Ch5 and is mutated in a large proportion of this condition",
    "D": "Li-Fraumeni syndrome is an autosomal recessive condition caused by mutations in the P53 gene",
    "E": "Hereditary non-polyposis colon cancer (Lynch syndrome) is an autosomal dominant condition associated with microsatellite instability which gives carries a 45% lifetime risk of colorectal cancer."
  },
  "answer": "C) The RB1 gene is a tumour suppressor gene on Ch13. In inherited RB (30%) there is a germline inactivation of the RB1 gene followed by a somatic mutation in the retinal cells later (two hit hypothesis). This condition is usually bilateral. In the more common non-heredited RB both of the mutations are somatic and this tends to be unilateral. BRCA I (Ch17) is associated with 80% risk of breast cancer and 50% risk of ovarian cancer over a lifetime whereas the risk of ovarian cancer from BRCA II (Ch13) is 25%. BRCA II is also associated with tumours involving the ovaries, fallopian tubes, prostate and pancreas together with malignant melanoma. Li Fraumeni is an autosomal dominant condition associated with mutations in the TP53 gene (Ch 17) which encodes for the p53 protein. It is associated with osteosarcoma, breast cancer, brain cancer, leukaemia and adrenocortical cancer. Lynch syndrome, is associated with colorectal cancer (80% lifetime risk), ovarian, endometrial, stomach, small intestine, hepatobiliary, upper urinary, brain and skin cancers. IT is due to DNA mismatch repair impairment.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Inherited cancer genetics: know your genes, know your risks.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) is indeed a condition that significantly increases the risk of colorectal carcinoma, and it is primarily caused by mutations in the APC (adenomatous polyposis coli) gene located on chromosome 5.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFAP is a classic example of an autosomal dominant inherited cancer syndrome, characterized by the development of hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps in the colon and rectum, which inevitably progress to colorectal cancer if left untreated. The APC gene acts as a tumor suppressor, playing a critical role in cell adhesion, migration, and the Wnt signaling pathway. A germline mutation in one allele of the APC gene, followed by a somatic 'second hit' mutation in the remaining normal allele, leads to uncontrolled cell proliferation and polyp formation, consistent with Knudson's two-hit hypothesis for tumor suppressor genes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While Retinoblastoma is associated with hereditary blindness and germline mutations in the Rb1 gene on Ch 13, the statement implies this is the majority of cases, whereas inherited RB is about 30%, and non-hereditary is more common. Also, it doesn't fully explain the two-hit hypothesis in the context of hereditary vs. non-hereditary forms.\nOption B (Incorrect): BRCA1 and BRCA2 are indeed responsible for inherited breast cancer. However, BRCA1 is associated with an approximate 80% lifetime risk of breast cancer and a 50% risk of ovarian cancer, while BRCA2 is associated with an 80% lifetime risk of breast cancer and a 25% risk of ovarian cancer, along with other cancers like prostate and pancreatic. The statement incorrectly claims BRCA2 is not associated with an increased risk of ovarian cancer.\nOption D (Incorrect): Li-Fraumeni syndrome is an autosomal dominant condition, not autosomal recessive, and is caused by germline mutations in the TP53 gene (Ch 17), which encodes the p53 tumor suppressor protein.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hereditary non-polyposis colon cancer (Lynch syndrome) is an autosomal dominant condition associated with microsatellite instability. However, it carries a significantly higher lifetime risk of colorectal cancer, up to 80%, not 45%, and is also associated with a broad spectrum of other cancers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Gene(s) | Inheritance | Key Features/Risks |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) | APC (Ch 5) | Autosomal Dominant | Hundreds of colorectal polyps, nearly 100% CRC risk, desmoids, osteomas |\n| Hereditary Breast/Ovarian Cancer | BRCA1 (Ch 17), BRCA2 (Ch 13) | Autosomal Dominant | High lifetime risk of breast (80%) and ovarian (BRCA1: 50%, BRCA2: 25%) cancers |\n| Li-Fraumeni Syndrome | TP53 (Ch 17) | Autosomal Dominant | Early-onset sarcomas, breast cancer, brain tumors, adrenocortical carcinoma |\n| Lynch Syndrome (HNPCC) | MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, PMS2, EPCAM | Autosomal Dominant | High lifetime risk of CRC (up to 80%), endometrial, ovarian, gastric, urinary tract cancers |\n| Retinoblastoma | RB1 (Ch 13) | Autosomal Dominant (hereditary) | Retinal tumors, often bilateral in hereditary form, two-hit hypothesis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know the gene, inheritance, and key cancer risks for common inherited cancer syndromes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, FAP presents with innumerable polyps carpeting the colonic mucosa. Intraoperatively, a total colectomy with ileorectal anastomosis or ileal pouch-anal anastomosis is often performed to prevent inevitable colorectal cancer.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colorectal Cancer Screening (2023) recommends genetic counseling and testing for individuals with a personal or family history suggestive of FAP, and specific surveillance protocols for affected individuals.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Retinoblastoma is a condition associated with hereditary blindness. It is c | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | BRCA I and BRCA II are genes responsible for inherited breast cancer. They  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Familial Adenomatous Polyposis is a condition which increases the risk of c | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Li-Fraumeni syndrome is an autosomal recessive condition caused by mutation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hereditary non-polyposis colon cancer (Lynch syndrome) is an autosomal domi | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The RB1 gene is a tumour suppressor gene on Ch13. In inherited RB (30%) there is a germline inactiva** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
