  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Early detection saves lives; screening protocols matter.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, which accurately describes the operational aspects of the UK breast screening service, specifically the use of two-view mammograms double-read by two consultant radiologists. This rigorous approach is fundamental to the program's effectiveness in early cancer detection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe UK breast screening program employs a standardized protocol of two-view mammography (craniocaudal and mediolateral oblique) for each breast. The crucial element of double-reading by two independent consultant radiologists significantly enhances sensitivity and specificity, reducing false positives and negatives. This systematic, quality-controlled interpretation process is a cornerstone of effective population-based screening, ensuring high diagnostic accuracy before further investigations are initiated.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Screening is a dedicated, nationally organized service delivered through specific screening units, not by all hospitals with a breast unit. Treatment is referred to local breast units.\nOption B (Incorrect): The current age range for routine screening invitation in the UK is 50-70 years, with an extension to 47-73 years being implemented, not 55-75 years.\nOption C (Incorrect): Screen-detected breast cancers tend to have a *lower* proportion of invasive cancers, are often smaller, lower grade, lymph node negative, and ER positive, indicating a better prognosis compared to symptomatic cancers.\nOption D (Incorrect): Screening is undertaken every 3 years for eligible women in the UK, not every 2 years.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | UK Breast Screening Program |\n|---|---|\n| **Age Range** | 50-70 years (extending to 47-73) |\n| **Frequency** | Every 3 years |\n| **Imaging** | 2-view mammograms |\n| **Interpretation** | Double-read by 2 consultant radiologists |\n| **Service Delivery** | Nationally organized, locally delivered by dedicated screening units |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: UK breast screening is 50-70, every 3 years, 2-view mammograms, double-read.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMammography is the primary imaging modality for breast cancer screening, typically involving craniocaudal (CC) and mediolateral oblique (MLO) views of each breast to visualize breast tissue comprehensively.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNHS Breast Screening Programme (NHS BSP) Guidelines (latest iteration): Recommends routine mammographic screening for women aged 50-70 every three years, with ongoing age extension.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Screening is carried out by all hospitals with a breast unit in the UK | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Screening for breast cancer is for women between the ages of 55 – 75 in the | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Screen detected breast cancers tend to have a higher proportion of invasive | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Screening is undertaken every 2 years for post-menopausal women | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Screening is undertaken using 2 view mammograms double read by 2 consultant | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Screening is a nationally regionally distributed and locally delivered service. Women between the ag** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
