  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 SCC: Sun-exposed, scaly, spreads to nodes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B. Squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) has a significantly higher propensity for systemic metastasis compared to basal cell carcinoma (BCC), although the overall metastatic rate for SCC remains relatively low. This distinction is crucial for prognosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSCC is the second most common non-melanomatous skin cancer, primarily linked to chronic sun exposure and immunosuppression. While BCC rarely metastasizes beyond local invasion, SCC, particularly high-risk variants, can spread to regional lymph nodes and, less commonly, distant sites. This difference in metastatic potential underscores the importance of early diagnosis and appropriate treatment for SCC, as it can impact patient survival. The primary route of metastasis for SCC is lymphatic, not hematogenous.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): SCC of the skin is the second commonest cutaneous malignancy, following basal cell carcinoma (BCC), which is the most common.\nOption C (Incorrect): The link between SCC and chronic sun exposure is very strong and well-established, similar to, if not more aggressive in presentation, than BCC. The statement that it is 'less convincing' is false.\nOption D (Incorrect): A characteristic ulcerated lesion with rolled edges is a classic description of basal cell carcinoma (BCC), not squamous cell carcinoma (SCC). SCC can ulcerate but typically presents as a scaly, erythematous plaque or nodule.\nOption E (Incorrect): Metastasis from SCC is predominantly via the lymphatic route to regional lymph nodes, not commonly by the hematogenous route.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) | Basal Cell Carcinoma (BCC) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Prevalence | Second commonest cutaneous malignancy | Commonest cutaneous malignancy |\n| Metastatic Potential | Higher rate than BCC (still low overall) | Very low rate, primarily local invasion |\n| Typical Presentation | Growing lump, scaly surface, flat reddish plaque, ulceration | Pearly papule, rolled edges, telangiectasias, central ulceration |\n| Metastatic Route | Lymphatic | Extremely rare, usually local invasion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: SCC metastasizes more than BCC, primarily via lymphatics.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDermoscopy of SCC may show white circles, keratin, and polymorphic vessels. Clinically, an SCC lesion often appears as an erythematous, scaly, indurated plaque or nodule, which may ulcerate, but typically lacks the rolled borders characteristic of BCC.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Basal Cell and Squamous Cell Skin Cancers (2024) recommend risk stratification for SCC to guide management, including lymph node evaluation for high-risk lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | SCC of the skin represents the commonest cutaneous malignancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | SCC produces systemic metastases more commonly than basal cell carcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| C | The link between SCC and chronic sun exposure is less convincing than that  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | They form a characteristic ulcerated lesion with rolled edges | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Metastases is more commonly by the haematogenous route. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) SCC are the second commonest type of skin cancer after BCC (20% of non-melanomatous skin cancers) an** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
