  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Deltoid sensory loss? Think axillary nerve, always!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The axillary nerve is the correct answer because it provides sensory innervation to the 'regimental badge' area, which includes the skin overlying the deltoid insertion. Injury to the humerus, especially proximally, can directly affect this nerve.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe axillary nerve, a branch of the posterior cord of the brachial plexus (C5, C6), wraps around the surgical neck of the humerus. It innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles (motor) and supplies sensory innervation to the skin over the inferior aspect of the deltoid muscle, often referred to as the 'regimental badge' area. This anatomical course makes it particularly vulnerable to fractures of the surgical neck of the humerus, shoulder dislocations, and direct trauma to the shoulder, precisely matching the clinical presentation of a sensory deficit at the deltoid insertion point.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Radial. The radial nerve primarily innervates the posterior compartment of the arm and forearm and provides sensory innervation to the posterior arm, forearm, and dorsum of the hand. While vulnerable to mid-shaft humeral fractures, its sensory distribution does not cover the deltoid insertion.\nOption C (Incorrect): Musculocutaneous. The musculocutaneous nerve innervates the anterior compartment of the arm (biceps, brachialis) and provides sensory innervation to the lateral forearm. Its distribution is not near the deltoid insertion.\nOption D (Incorrect): Median. The median nerve primarily innervates the anterior forearm muscles and some hand muscles, providing sensory innervation to the lateral palm and digits. It is not involved in the shoulder or deltoid region.\nOption E (Incorrect): Subscapular. The subscapular nerves are motor nerves supplying the subscapularis and teres major muscles. They do not have a cutaneous sensory distribution.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Spinal Roots | Motor Innervation | Sensory Innervation | Common Injury Site |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Axillary | C5, C6 | Deltoid, Teres Minor | Regimental badge area (inferior deltoid) | Surgical neck of humerus, shoulder dislocation |\n| Radial | C5-T1 | Posterior arm/forearm | Posterior arm/forearm, dorsum hand | Mid-shaft humerus (spiral groove) |\n| Musculocutaneous | C5-C7 | Biceps, Brachialis, Coracobrachialis | Lateral forearm | Proximal humerus, direct trauma to arm |\n| Median | C5-T1 | Most anterior forearm, thenar | Lateral palm, digits 1-3.5 | Supracondylar humerus, carpal tunnel |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sensory deficit over the deltoid insertion points directly to axillary nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray or CT, a fracture of the surgical neck of the humerus or a shoulder dislocation would be evident, indicating potential compromise of the axillary nerve. Intraoperatively, the nerve would be identified inferior to the humeral head, wrapping posteriorly around the surgical neck, and could appear contused, stretched, or transected.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Shoulder Dislocations (2019) recommend careful neurovascular assessment, including axillary nerve function, both pre- and post-reduction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Axillary | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Musculocutaneous | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Median | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Subscapular | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
