  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Portal vein: The liver's main highway for blood, not just a side road.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Portal vein. Surgical occlusion of the portal vein will result in the greatest reduction in hepatic blood flow because the portal vein provides approximately 70% of the liver's total blood supply.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe liver has a unique dual blood supply: the hepatic artery and the portal vein. While the hepatic artery delivers oxygenated blood, it accounts for only about 30% of the total hepatic blood flow. The portal vein, conversely, carries nutrient-rich, deoxygenated blood from the gastrointestinal tract, spleen, and pancreas, contributing a substantial 70% of the liver's blood supply. This high volume of portal venous flow is crucial for the liver's metabolic and detoxification functions, making its occlusion the most impactful on overall hepatic perfusion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The common hepatic artery supplies only about 30% of the liver's blood flow, significantly less than the portal vein's contribution.\nOption C (Incorrect): The right hepatic artery is a branch of the common hepatic artery, supplying only a portion of the liver, and thus contributes even less to the total blood flow than the common hepatic artery itself.\nOption D (Incorrect): The coeliac axis is the origin of the common hepatic artery, but its occlusion would affect multiple organs (stomach, spleen, pancreas) and only indirectly reduce hepatic arterial flow, which is still a smaller component than the portal vein.\nOption E (Incorrect): The left hepatic artery is also a branch of the common hepatic artery, supplying only a segment of the liver, and its occlusion would have a minimal impact on overall hepatic blood flow compared to the portal vein.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Vessel | % Total Hepatic Blood Flow | % Total Hepatic Oxygen Supply | Primary Function |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Portal Vein | ~70% | ~50% | Delivers nutrient-rich blood from GI tract for processing |\n| Hepatic Artery | ~30% | ~50% | Delivers oxygenated blood to liver parenchyma |\n| Hepatic Veins | N/A (Drainage) | N/A | Drains deoxygenated blood from liver to IVC |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Portal vein is the liver's main blood supplier, not the artery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, clamping the portal triad (Pringle maneuver) temporarily occludes both the hepatic artery and portal vein. On Doppler ultrasound, portal vein thrombosis or occlusion would show absent or significantly diminished flow within the portal vein lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance on the Management of Portal Vein Thrombosis in Cirrhosis (2021). This guideline discusses the implications and management of portal vein occlusion in specific patient populations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Portal vein | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Common hepatic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right hepatic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Coeliac axis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Left hepatic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The portal vein transports 70% of the blood supply to the liver, while the hepatic artery provides 3** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
