  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Strip the vein, not the nerve; medial ankle numbness is saphenous.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Saphenous nerve injury. This patient's symptoms of numbness superior to the ankle following long saphenous vein stripping are classic for iatrogenic injury to the saphenous nerve, which runs in close proximity to the vein.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe saphenous nerve is the largest cutaneous branch of the femoral nerve. It accompanies the long saphenous vein (LSV) down the medial aspect of the thigh and leg. Below the knee, it becomes superficial and runs anterior to the medial malleolus, supplying sensation to the skin on the medial side of the leg and foot, including the area superior to the ankle. Stripping of the LSV, particularly below the knee, carries a significant risk of damaging this nerve due to its intimate anatomical relationship, leading to the described sensory deficit.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Sural nerve injury) (Incorrect): The sural nerve is associated with the short saphenous vein (SSV) and supplies sensation to the lateral aspect of the ankle and foot, not the medial superior ankle.\nOption B (Femoral nerve injury) (Incorrect): The femoral nerve is a large motor and sensory nerve of the thigh, located deep in the groin. Injury is rare during superficial varicose vein surgery and would present with quadriceps weakness and anterior thigh numbness, not isolated ankle numbness.\nOption D (Common peroneal nerve injury) (Incorrect): The common peroneal nerve winds around the head of the fibula and supplies motor function to the anterior and lateral compartments of the leg, and sensation to the dorsum of the foot. Injury would typically cause foot drop and numbness in a different distribution.\nOption E (Superficial peroneal nerve injury) (Incorrect): The superficial peroneal nerve supplies sensation to the dorsum of the foot, sparing the first web space. Its injury would not typically cause numbness superior to the ankle.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Associated Vein | Sensory Distribution | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Saphenous nerve | Long Saphenous Vein | Medial leg, ankle, foot | Most common nerve injury with LSV stripping |\n| Sural nerve | Short Saphenous Vein | Lateral leg, ankle, foot | Risk with SSV surgery or lateral ankle incisions |\n| Superficial peroneal nerve | N/A | Dorsum of foot (except 1st web space) | Risk with lateral leg incisions, compartment syndrome |\n| Common peroneal nerve | N/A | Lateral leg, dorsum of foot (motor & sensory) | Risk with fibular head trauma, prolonged compression |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Numbness medial ankle post-stripping = saphenous nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring saphenous vein stripping, the saphenous nerve is often seen as a thin, white, glistening structure running parallel to the long saphenous vein, especially below the knee. It can be inadvertently avulsed or transected during the stripping process, particularly if the stripper is passed too close to the vein wall or if the vein is adherent to the nerve.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2022 European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) Guidelines on the Management of Chronic Venous Disease. These guidelines recommend endovenous thermal ablation over stripping for primary varicose veins to reduce nerve injury risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sural nerve injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Femoral nerve injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Saphenous nerve injury | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Common peroneal nerve injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Superficial peroneal nerve injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The sural nerve is related to the short saphenous vein. The saphenous nerve is related to the long s** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
