  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Flex your muscles, not your errors: Musculocutaneous is for flexion!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C because the question asks for the *except* statement, meaning the false statement. Damage to the musculocutaneous nerve primarily impairs elbow *flexion*, as it innervates the primary flexor muscles, not extension.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe musculocutaneous nerve is a terminal branch of the lateral cord of the brachial plexus. It is responsible for motor innervation of the coracobrachialis, biceps brachii, and brachialis muscles, all of which are powerful elbow flexors. Its sensory component, the lateral antebrachial cutaneous nerve, provides sensation to the lateral forearm. Therefore, injury to this nerve would result in weakness of elbow flexion and sensory loss in the lateral forearm.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The musculocutaneous nerve indeed arises from the lateral cord of the brachial plexus, making this a true statement.\nOption B (Incorrect): The lateral antebrachial cutaneous nerve, a continuation of the musculocutaneous nerve, provides sensory innervation to the lateral side of the forearm, making this a true statement.\nOption D (Incorrect): The musculocutaneous nerve is the sole motor supply to the biceps brachii muscle, making this a true statement.\nOption E (Incorrect): After piercing the coracobrachialis, the musculocutaneous nerve typically runs between the biceps brachii and brachialis muscles, making this a true statement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Brachial Plexus Cord | Key Motor Function | Key Sensory Distribution |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Musculocutaneous | Lateral | Elbow flexion (biceps, brachialis, coracobrachialis) | Lateral forearm |\n| Radial | Posterior | Elbow, wrist, finger extension | Posterior arm, forearm, dorsum of hand |\n| Median | Lateral & Medial | Forearm pronation, wrist/finger flexion, thumb opposition | Lateral palm, digits 1-3.5 |\n| Ulnar | Medial | Intrinsic hand muscles (most), wrist/finger flexion | Medial 1.5 digits, medial palm |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Musculocutaneous nerve damage means no biceps, no brachialis, no elbow flexion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a musculocutaneous nerve injury might show denervation changes (edema, fatty atrophy) in the biceps, brachialis, and coracobrachialis muscles. Intraoperatively, the nerve can be identified piercing the coracobrachialis muscle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) 2011 Clinical Practice Guideline: The Treatment of Brachial Plexus Injuries. Recommends early surgical exploration and repair for complete brachial plexus injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It arises from the lateral cord of the brachial plexus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It provides cutaneous innervation to the lateral side of the forearm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | If damaged, then extension of the elbow joint will be impaired | ✅ Correct |\n| D | It supplies the biceps muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It runs beneath biceps | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) It supplies biceps, brachialis and coracobrachialis. If damaged then elbow flexion will be impaired.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
