  "id": 206204,
  "question": "A 21 year old man undergoes surgical removal of an impacted 3rd molar. Post operatively, he is noted to have anaesthesia on the anterolateral aspect of the tongue. What is the most likely explanation?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Injury to the hypoglossal nerve",
    "B": "Injury to the inferior alveolar nerve",
    "C": "Injury to the lingual nerve",
    "D": "Injury to the mandibular branch of the facial nerve",
    "E": "Injury to the glossopharyngeal nerve"
  },
  "answer": "C) The lingual nerve is closely related to the third molar and up to 10% of\npatients undergoing surgical extraction of these teeth may subsequently\ndevelop a lingual neuropraxia. The result is anaesthesia of the ipsilateral\nanterior aspect of the tongue. The inferior alveolar nerve innervates the\nteeth themselves.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Mind the lingual nerve, or your patient's tongue will feel numb and weird!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, injury to the lingual nerve. This is the most likely explanation because the lingual nerve provides general sensation to the anterolateral aspect of the tongue and is anatomically vulnerable during surgical extraction of impacted mandibular third molars.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lingual nerve is a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3). It courses anteriorly and medially to the inferior alveolar nerve, lying in close proximity to the medial aspect of the mandibular third molar. As it descends, it passes beneath the submandibular duct and then loops superiorly to supply general sensation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, the floor of the mouth, and the lingual gingiva. Its superficial position and close relationship to the surgical field during third molar extraction make it susceptible to direct trauma, compression, or stretching, leading to neuropraxia or axonotmesis, manifesting as anesthesia or paresthesia in its distribution.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Injury to the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) would result in motor deficits of the tongue, such as deviation or weakness, not sensory loss.\nOption B (Incorrect): Injury to the inferior alveolar nerve (IAN) would cause anesthesia or paresthesia of the lower lip, chin, and mandibular teeth, not the anterior tongue.\nOption D (Incorrect): Injury to the mandibular branch of the facial nerve (CN VII) primarily affects the motor function of facial muscles. While the chorda tympani (a branch of CN VII) carries taste sensation from the anterior tongue, it does not provide general sensation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Injury to the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) would affect general sensation and taste from the posterior one-third of the tongue, as well as the pharynx and tonsils, not the anterolateral aspect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Primary Function | Clinical Relevance to 3rd Molar Extraction |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lingual Nerve (CN V3) | General sensation to anterior 2/3 of tongue, floor of mouth, lingual gingiva | Most common nerve injury during 3rd molar extraction, causing anesthesia/paresthesia of anterior tongue |\n| Inferior Alveolar Nerve (CN V3) | General sensation to mandibular teeth, lower lip, chin | Second most common nerve injury during 3rd molar extraction, causing anesthesia/paresthesia of lower lip/chin |\n| Hypoglossal Nerve (CN XII) | Motor innervation to intrinsic and extrinsic tongue muscles | Injury causes tongue deviation/weakness, rare in 3rd molar extraction |\n| Glossopharyngeal Nerve (CN IX) | General sensation & taste to posterior 1/3 of tongue, pharynx | Injury affects posterior tongue sensation, rare in 3rd molar extraction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anesthesia of the anterior tongue after 3rd molar extraction = Lingual nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the lingual nerve is not typically visualized directly during routine third molar extraction unless specifically dissected. However, its anatomical position medial and superficial to the mandible, often near the lingual plate, makes it vulnerable. Surgeons must be mindful of lingual flap reflection and bone removal to avoid direct trauma or compression. Pre-operative imaging (e.g., panoramic radiograph, CBCT) helps assess the proximity of the inferior alveolar nerve to the roots, but the lingual nerve's position is less reliably predicted by standard imaging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Oral and Maxillofacial Surgeons (AAOMS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Impacted Third Molars (2016) recommends careful surgical technique to minimize nerve injury, including lingual nerve protection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Injury to the hypoglossal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Injury to the inferior alveolar nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Injury to the lingual nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Injury to the mandibular branch of the facial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Injury to the glossopharyngeal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The lingual nerve is closely related to the third molar and up to 10% of\npatients undergoing surgica** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
