  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ovarian cysts can be a real pain in the medial thigh!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Obturator nerve. A large ovarian cyst, being a pelvic mass, can compress structures within the true pelvis, and the obturator nerve is particularly vulnerable due to its course along the lateral pelvic wall, leading to referred pain in its distribution, which includes the medial aspect of the thigh.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe obturator nerve originates from the lumbar plexus (L2-L4) and descends through the psoas major muscle, emerging from its medial border. It then courses along the lateral pelvic wall, inferior to the common iliac vessels and lateral to the ureter, before exiting the pelvis through the obturator canal to enter the medial compartment of the thigh. Its primary function is motor innervation to the adductor muscles of the thigh and sensory innervation to the skin of the medial thigh. A large ovarian cyst can exert direct pressure on the obturator nerve as it traverses the pelvic sidewall, causing neuropathic pain that radiates distally along its sensory distribution to the medial thigh.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Sciatic) (Incorrect): The sciatic nerve innervates the posterior thigh and leg, not the medial thigh. It is also located more posteriorly and inferiorly in the pelvis, making direct compression by an ovarian cyst less likely to cause isolated medial thigh pain.\nOption B (Genitofemoral) (Incorrect): The genitofemoral nerve primarily supplies sensation to the anterior thigh (femoral branch) and genitalia (genital branch). While it is in the pelvic region, its distribution does not typically account for pain isolated to the medial thigh from an ovarian cyst.\nOption D (Ilioinguinal) (Incorrect): The ilioinguinal nerve provides sensation to the inguinal region, upper medial thigh, and external genitalia. While it has a small medial thigh component, it is generally located higher and more anteriorly, and compression by an ovarian cyst is less likely to manifest as primary medial thigh pain compared to obturator nerve involvement.\nOption E (Femoral cutaneous) (Incorrect): The lateral femoral cutaneous nerve (often referred to as femoral cutaneous) supplies sensation to the lateral aspect of the thigh. Compression of this nerve would cause lateral thigh pain (meralgia paresthetica), not medial thigh pain.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Primary Innervation Area | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Obturator** | L2-L4 | Medial thigh (motor & sensory) | Compressed by pelvic masses, obturator hernias |\n| Sciatic | L4-S3 | Posterior thigh, entire leg/foot (motor & sensory) | Sciatica, piriformis syndrome |\n| Genitofemoral | L1-L2 | Anterior thigh (femoral branch), genitalia (genital branch) | Pain after hernia repair, appendectomy |\n| Lateral Femoral Cutaneous | L2-L3 | Lateral thigh (sensory) | Meralgia Paresthetica, compression at inguinal ligament |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial thigh pain with a pelvic mass? Think obturator nerve compression.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (CT or MRI), a large ovarian cyst would be visualized as a mass in the adnexa. Compression of the obturator nerve would be evident as the cyst abuts or displaces the nerve, which can be identified along the lateral pelvic wall, often near the obturator foramen. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would observe the ovarian cyst directly impinging upon the obturator nerve as it traverses the pelvic sidewall.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 174 (2016) on Management of Adnexal Masses. It recommends evaluation of adnexal masses, including imaging, to assess for malignancy and potential mass effect on surrounding structures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sciatic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Genitofemoral | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Obturator | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Ilioinguinal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Femoral cutaneous | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The cutaneous branch of the obturator nerve is frequently absent.\nHowever, the obturator nerve is a ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
