  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Rectal varices bleed, terlipressin saves.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with signs of portal hypertension (dilated abdominal wall veins) and acute lower GI bleeding from rectal varices, confirmed by proctoscopy. IV terlipressin is the most appropriate initial medical treatment to reduce portal pressure and control the hemorrhage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTerlipressin is a synthetic analogue of vasopressin that acts on V1 receptors in the splanchnic circulation, causing vasoconstriction. This reduces portal venous inflow and consequently lowers portal pressure, which is critical for controlling bleeding from varices (esophageal or rectal) in patients with portal hypertension. It is a first-line medical therapy for acute variceal hemorrhage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Excisional haemorrhoidectomy) (Incorrect): This procedure is for symptomatic hemorrhoids, which are distinct from rectal varices. Rectal varices are portosystemic collaterals due to portal hypertension, and surgical excision carries a high risk of severe bleeding and is not indicated for acute variceal hemorrhage.\nOption C (Injection sclerotherapy) (Incorrect): While sclerotherapy can be used for some varices, the explanation notes a high risk of precipitating further hemorrhage when attempting to inject rectal varices, especially in an acute bleeding setting. It is generally not the first-line treatment for acutely bleeding rectal varices.\nOption D (Proctectomy) (Incorrect): Proctectomy is the surgical removal of the rectum. This is a major, highly invasive procedure and is far too aggressive for the initial management of bleeding rectal varices. It would only be considered in extremely rare, refractory cases after all less invasive options have failed.\nOption E (Rectal pack insertion) (Incorrect): A rectal pack might provide temporary tamponade but does not address the underlying portal hypertension or definitively stop the bleeding. It is a temporizing measure at best, carries risks of mucosal injury, and is not a definitive treatment for bleeding rectal varices.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Rectal Varices | Hemorrhoids | Esophageal Varices |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Etiology** | Portal hypertension | Normal venous plexus dilation | Portal hypertension |\n| **Location** | Rectum (proximal to dentate line) | Anal canal (above/below dentate line) | Distal esophagus |\n| **Bleeding Risk** | High, life-threatening | Usually self-limiting | High, life-threatening |\n| **Initial Tx (Acute Bleed)** | IV Terlipressin, TIPS, endoscopic banding | Conservative, banding, sclerotherapy | IV Terlipressin/Octreotide, Endoscopic Banding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bleeding rectal varices = portal hypertension. Treat medically first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nProctoscopy would reveal large, tortuous, bluish, submucosal veins in the rectal wall, often proximal to the dentate line, with active bleeding or stigmata of recent hemorrhage (e.g., adherent clots). These are distinct from the typical appearance of internal hemorrhoids.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance: The Role of Endoscopy in the Management of Variceal Hemorrhage (2021) recommends vasoactive drugs (terlipressin or octreotide) as initial therapy for acute variceal bleeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | IV terlipressin | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Excisional haemorrhoidectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Injection sclerotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Proctectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Rectal pack insertion | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Rectal varices are a recognised complication of portal hypertension. In the first instance they can ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
