  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When stones are absent, but the gallbladder is inflamed, think acalculous.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Acute acalculous cholecystitis. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's critical illness (septic shock), right upper quadrant tenderness, and crucially, the absence of gallstones and a normal calibre bile duct on imaging, especially in a diabetic patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute acalculous cholecystitis is an acute inflammation of the gallbladder in the absence of gallstones or cystic duct obstruction. It typically occurs in critically ill patients, those with severe trauma, burns, prolonged fasting, or underlying conditions like diabetes, where gallbladder stasis, ischemia, and inflammation are precipitated by systemic illness. The absence of stones despite classic symptoms of cholecystitis points directly to this diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Acute calculous cholecystitis requires the presence of gallstones, which were explicitly ruled out by imaging.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cholangitis typically presents with jaundice, fever, and right upper quadrant pain (Charcot's triad), often with dilated bile ducts due to obstruction, none of which are present here.\nOption D (Incorrect): Mirizzi syndrome involves a gallstone impacting the cystic duct or gallbladder neck, causing extrinsic compression of the common hepatic duct, which is inconsistent with the absence of stones and a normal calibre bile duct.\nOption E (Incorrect): Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction is a functional disorder causing biliary pain or pancreatitis, not an acute inflammatory process leading to septic shock and gallbladder inflammation without stones.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Calculous Cholecystitis | Acute Acalculous Cholecystitis | Cholangitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Gallstones obstructing cystic duct | Gallbladder stasis/ischemia, no stones | Bile duct obstruction (stones, stricture, tumor) + infection |\n| **Patient Profile** | Often otherwise healthy, middle-aged | Critically ill, trauma, burns, diabetes, prolonged fasting | History of gallstones, previous biliary surgery |\n| **Imaging** | Gallstones, GB wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid | GB wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, NO stones | Bile duct dilation, stones in CBD, +/- liver abscesses |\n| **Jaundice** | Rare | Rare | Common |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Septic critically ill patient + RUQ pain + no stones = Acalculous Cholecystitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (ultrasound, CT) would show gallbladder wall thickening (>3-4mm), pericholecystic fluid, and potentially intramural gas, without evidence of gallstones or bile duct dilation. A sonographic Murphy's sign may be present.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis. They recommend early cholecystectomy for acute cholecystitis, with specific considerations for acalculous cholecystitis in critically ill patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute calculous cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acute acalculous cholecystitis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Cholangitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mirizzi syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sphincter of oddi dysfunction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) This is the classic description of acalculous cholecystitis and its commonest in patients with type ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
