  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't force a Foley; check the urethra first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Urethral injury. A pelvic fracture, especially in a male, is highly associated with urethral disruption. The patient's inability to void, leading to a distended, tender bladder, is a classic presentation of urethral obstruction due to injury.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUrethral injuries, particularly posterior urethral injuries, are strongly correlated with pelvic fractures due to shear forces at the prostatomembranous junction. The classic triad includes blood at the urethral meatus (though not explicitly stated, it's implied by the context of trauma and retention), inability to void despite a full bladder, and a high-riding prostate on DRE (if performed). The distended bladder confirms urinary retention, which is a direct consequence of urethral disruption.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Bladder rupture) (Incorrect): While possible with pelvic fracture, a distended bladder suggests obstruction rather than free extravasation of urine, which would typically occur with a complete rupture.\nOption B (Ureter injury) (Incorrect): Ureteric injuries are rare in blunt trauma and typically do not cause acute urinary retention or a distended bladder. They are more often associated with penetrating trauma or iatrogenic causes.\nOption D (Clot retention) (Incorrect): Clot retention implies significant bleeding into the bladder, which could cause retention. However, in the context of a pelvic fracture, a primary urethral injury causing mechanical obstruction is a more direct and common diagnosis for acute retention.\nOption E (Prostate rupture) (Incorrect): The prostate itself is rarely \"ruptured\" in isolation. Urethral injuries often involve the prostatic urethra, but the primary injury is to the urethra, not the prostate gland itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Urethral Injury | Bladder Rupture | Ureteric Injury |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Mechanism** | Pelvic fracture (shear forces) | Pelvic fracture (direct impact/compression), blunt trauma to full bladder | Penetrating trauma, iatrogenic (surgery), rare blunt trauma |\n| **Presentation** | Inability to void, distended bladder, blood at meatus, high-riding prostate | Hematuria, suprapubic pain, abdominal distension (intraperitoneal), signs of extravasation | Flank pain, hematuria, fever, hydronephrosis (delayed) |\n| **Diagnosis** | Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG) | Cystogram (CT or plain film) | CT Urogram, IVP, retrograde pyelogram |\n| **Management** | Suprapubic catheter, delayed repair | Surgical repair (intraperitoneal), Foley catheter (extraperitoneal) | Stenting, surgical repair |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pelvic fracture + inability to void = suspect urethral injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe definitive diagnostic study for suspected urethral injury is a retrograde urethrogram (RUG). This involves injecting contrast into the urethra to visualize its integrity and identify any extravasation or complete transection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urotrauma (2020). These guidelines recommend performing a retrograde urethrogram in male patients with suspected urethral injury (e.g., pelvic fracture, blood at meatus, inability to pass a Foley).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bladder rupture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ureter injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Urethral injury | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Clot retention | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Prostate rupture | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Pelvic fractures may cause laceration of the urethra. Urinary retention, blood at the urethral meatu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
