  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't forget the steroids, or your patient might crash!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Addisonian crisis. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's history of chronic steroid use for polymyalgia rheumatica, coupled with the acute onset of delirium and hypotension post-surgery, and characteristic electrolyte derangements.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic prednisolone therapy suppresses the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, rendering the adrenal glands unable to produce sufficient cortisol during acute stress like surgery. An Addisonian crisis manifests as profound hypotension, delirium, and classic biochemical abnormalities including hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and hypoglycemia, all of which are present in this patient. Urgent hydrocortisone replacement is life-saving to prevent cardiovascular collapse.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Septic shock secondary to appendicitis): Incorrect. While sepsis is possible post-surgery, the specific electrolyte abnormalities (hyperkalemia, hyponatremia) and hypoglycemia are not typical primary features of uncomplicated septic shock, though sepsis can precipitate adrenal crisis.\nOption B (Neutropenic sepsis): Incorrect. The patient's WBC count is elevated at 14 x 10^9/l, indicating leukocytosis, not neutropenia, despite methotrexate use.\nOption C (Phaeochromocytoma): Incorrect. This condition typically presents with paroxysmal hypertension, tachycardia, and sweating, not acute hypotension and delirium in this context.\nOption D (Perforated bowel): Incorrect. While a surgical complication, a perforated bowel would primarily cause peritonitis and sepsis, not directly explain the specific hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and hypoglycemia seen here.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Addisonian Crisis | Septic Shock | Hypoglycemia (other causes) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Blood Pressure | Hypotension | Hypotension | Variable |\n| Na+ | Low | Normal/Low | Normal |\n| K+ | High | Normal/Low | Normal |\n| Glucose | Low | Variable | Low |\n| Steroid History | Often present | Not primary | Not primary |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Steroid-dependent patient + stress + hypotension = adrenal crisis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable as no imaging was provided in the question. Adrenal glands might appear atrophic on imaging in chronic steroid users, but this is not an acute diagnostic tool for crisis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Primary Adrenal Insufficiency (2016) recommends immediate IV hydrocortisone for suspected adrenal crisis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Septic shock secondary to appendicitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Neutropenic sepsis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Phaeochromocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Perforated bowel | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Addisonian crisis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Features of an addisonian crisis:\nHyponatraemia\nHyperkalaemia\nHypoglycaemia\n\nThis man is on steroids** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
