  "question": "A 48 year old woman is admitted with sepsis secondary to an infected\ndiabetic foot ulcer. She has a necrotic and infected forefoot with necrosis\nof the heel. There is a boggy indurated swelling anterior to the ankle\njoint. Pulses are normal. What is the best course of action?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Above knee amputation",
    "B": "Amputation of the foot",
    "C": "Below knee amputation",
    "D": "Incision and drainage of pus",
    "E": "Application of 4 layer bandages"
  },
  "answer": "C) A below knee amputation is the best option here. The foot is non\nsalvageable. However, she may ambulate with a prosthesis.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the foot is gone, save the knee for a better stride!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Below knee amputation. This is the best course of action because the patient has extensive necrosis of both the forefoot and heel, making the foot non-salvageable, but preserving the knee joint allows for better prosthetic rehabilitation and ambulation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn severe diabetic foot infections with extensive necrosis and sepsis, the primary goal is source control and removal of all non-viable tissue. A below-knee amputation (BKA) is often the preferred major amputation level as it removes the diseased foot while preserving the knee joint. Preservation of the knee significantly improves the patient's ability to ambulate with a prosthesis, leading to better functional outcomes and quality of life compared to an above-knee amputation. The presence of normal pulses suggests adequate proximal blood supply, making a BKA a viable option for healing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Above knee amputation) (Incorrect): This is overly aggressive and unnecessary given the clinical picture and normal pulses. Preserving the knee joint is crucial for functional rehabilitation.\nOption B (Amputation of the foot) (Incorrect): This is not feasible as the patient has necrosis of both the forefoot and heel, indicating the entire foot is non-salvageable.\nOption D (Incision and drainage of pus) (Incorrect): While incision and drainage is important for sepsis, it is insufficient for extensive necrotic tissue. The underlying problem of non-viable tissue must be addressed surgically.\nOption E (Application of 4 layer bandages) (Incorrect): This is a treatment for venous insufficiency ulcers and is completely inappropriate for an infected, necrotic diabetic foot with sepsis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Amputation Level | Indication | Functional Outcome |\n|---|---|---|\n| Toe/Ray Amputation | Localized gangrene/infection of a single digit, viable foot | Excellent, minimal functional impact |\n| Transmetatarsal Amputation | Forefoot gangrene/infection, viable midfoot/hindfoot | Good, preserves ankle function, requires special shoes |\n| Below-Knee Amputation (BKA) | Non-salvageable foot (extensive necrosis, severe infection, failed revascularization), viable calf | Good, preserves knee joint, allows prosthetic ambulation |\n| Above-Knee Amputation (AKA) | Non-salvageable lower leg/thigh, failed BKA, severe proximal disease | Poor, significant energy expenditure for ambulation, often wheelchair-bound |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Preserve the knee whenever possible for better prosthetic function.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nX-rays might show gas in soft tissues (indicating necrotizing infection) or osteomyelitis. Intraoperatively, extensive black, non-bleeding necrotic tissue would be seen involving the forefoot and heel, with purulent discharge from the boggy swelling.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Working Group on the Diabetic Foot (IWGDF) Guidelines 2023. These guidelines recommend prompt surgical debridement and appropriate amputation levels for severe diabetic foot infections to achieve source control and optimize functional outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Above knee amputation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Amputation of the foot | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Below knee amputation | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Incision and drainage of pus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Application of 4 layer bandages | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) A below knee amputation is the best option here. The foot is non\nsalvageable. However, she may ambul** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 524575718-800-MCQs-ONLY-SUCCESS-MRCS-A-UPDATED.txt**\n",
